var P_HTM = [];
P_HTM[1]="*Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa* **";
P_HTM[2]="*Saṃyuttanikāyo* **";
P_HTM[3]="*Catukkanipāta* **";
P_HTM[4]="*4. Bhaṇḍagāmavaggo* **";
P_HTM[5]="*2. Dutiyapaṇṇāsakaṃ**At Bhaṇḍa Village*";
P_HTM[6]="*1. Anubuddhasuttaṃ**Understood*";
P_HTM[7]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[8]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā vajjīsu viharati bhaṇḍagāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying in the land of the Vajjis at the village of Bhaṇḍa.*";
P_HTM[9]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[10]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[11]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[12]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[13]="*“Catunnaṃ, bhikkhave, dhammānaṃ ananubodhā appaṭivedhā evamidaṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ sandhāvitaṃ saṃsaritaṃ mamañceva tumhākañca.**“Mendicants, not understanding and not penetrating four things, both you and I have wandered and transmigrated for such a very long time.*";
P_HTM[14]="*Katamesaṃ catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[15]="*Ariyassa, bhikkhave, sīlassa ananubodhā appaṭivedhā evamidaṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ sandhāvitaṃ saṃsaritaṃ mamañceva tumhākañca.**Noble ethics,*";
P_HTM[16]="*Ariyassa, bhikkhave, samādhissa ananubodhā appaṭivedhā evamidaṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ sandhāvitaṃ saṃsaritaṃ mamañceva tumhākañca.**immersion,*";
P_HTM[17]="*Ariyāya, bhikkhave, paññāya ananubodhā appaṭivedhā evamidaṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ sandhāvitaṃ saṃsaritaṃ mamañceva tumhākañca.**wisdom,*";
P_HTM[18]="*Ariyāya, bhikkhave, vimuttiyā ananubodhā appaṭivedhā evamidaṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ sandhāvitaṃ saṃsaritaṃ mamañceva tumhākañca.**and freedom.*";
P_HTM[19]="*Tayidaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyaṃ sīlaṃ anubuddhaṃ paṭividdhaṃ, ariyo samādhi anubuddho paṭividdho, ariyā paññā anubuddhā paṭividdhā, ariyā vimutti anubuddhā paṭividdhā, ucchinnā bhavataṇhā, khīṇā bhavanetti, natthi dāni punabbhavo”ti.**These noble ethics, immersion, wisdom, and freedom have been understood and comprehended. Craving for continued existence has been cut off; the attachment to continued existence is ended; now there are no more future lives.”*";
P_HTM[20]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[21]="*Idaṃ vatvāna sugato athāparaṃ etadavoca satthā:**Then the Holy One, the Teacher, went on to say:*";
P_HTM[22]="*“Sīlaṃ samādhi paññā ca,**“Ethics, immersion, and wisdom,*";
P_HTM[23]="*vimutti ca anuttarā;**and the supreme freedom:*";
P_HTM[24]="*Anubuddhā ime dhammā,**these things have been understood*";
P_HTM[25]="*gotamena yasassinā.**by Gotama the renowned.*";
P_HTM[26]="*Iti buddho abhiññāya,**And so the Buddha, having insight,*";
P_HTM[27]="*dhammamakkhāsi bhikkhunaṃ;**explained this teaching to the mendicants.*";
P_HTM[28]="*Dukkhassantakaro satthā,**The teacher made an end of suffering,*";
P_HTM[29]="*cakkhumā parinibbuto”ti.**seeing clearly, he is extinguished.”*";
P_HTM[30]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[31]="*2. Papatitasuttaṃ**Fallen*";
P_HTM[32]="*“Catūhi, bhikkhave, dhammehi asamannāgato ‘imasmā dhammavinayā papatito’ti vuccati.**“Someone without four things is said to have ‘fallen from this teaching and training’.*";
P_HTM[33]="*Katamehi catūhi?**What four?*";
P_HTM[34]="*Ariyena, bhikkhave, sīlena asamannāgato ‘imasmā dhammavinayā papatito’ti vuccati.**Noble ethics,*";
P_HTM[35]="*Ariyena, bhikkhave, samādhinā asamannāgato ‘imasmā dhammavinayā papatito’ti vuccati.**immersion,*";
P_HTM[36]="*Ariyāya, bhikkhave, paññāya asamannāgato ‘imasmā dhammavinayā papatito’ti vuccati.**wisdom,*";
P_HTM[37]="*Ariyāya, bhikkhave, vimuttiyā asamannāgato ‘imasmā dhammavinayā papatito’ti vuccati.**and freedom.*";
P_HTM[38]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, catūhi dhammehi asamannāgato ‘imasmā dhammavinayā papatito’ti vuccati.**Someone without these four things is said to have ‘fallen from this teaching and training’.*";
P_HTM[39]="*Catūhi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato ‘imasmā dhammavinayā apapatito’ti vuccati.**Someone with four things is said to be ‘secure in this teaching and training’.*";
P_HTM[40]="*Katamehi catūhi?**What four?*";
P_HTM[41]="*Ariyena, bhikkhave, sīlena samannāgato ‘imasmā dhammavinayā apapatito’ti vuccati.**Noble ethics,*";
P_HTM[42]="*Ariyena, bhikkhave, samādhinā samannāgato ‘imasmā dhammavinayā apapatito’ti vuccati.**immersion,*";
P_HTM[43]="*Ariyāya, bhikkhave, paññāya samannāgato ‘imasmā dhammavinayā apapatito’ti vuccati.**wisdom,*";
P_HTM[44]="*Ariyāya, bhikkhave, vimuttiyā samannāgato ‘imasmā dhammavinayā apapatito’ti vuccati.**and freedom.*";
P_HTM[45]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, catūhi dhammehi samannāgato ‘imasmā dhammavinayā apapatito’ti vuccatīti.**Someone with these four things is said to be ‘secure in this teaching and training’.*";
P_HTM[46]="*Cutā patanti patitā,**They fall, collapsed and fallen;*";
P_HTM[47]="*giddhā ca punarāgatā;**greedy, they return.*";
P_HTM[48]="*Kataṃ kiccaṃ rataṃ rammaṃ,**The work is done, the joyful is enjoyed,*";
P_HTM[49]="*sukhenānvāgataṃ sukhan”ti.**happiness is found through happiness.”*";
P_HTM[50]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[51]="*3. Paṭhamakhatasuttaṃ**Broken (1st)*";
P_HTM[52]="*“Catūhi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato bālo abyatto asappuriso khataṃ upahataṃ attānaṃ pariharati, sāvajjo ca hoti sānuvajjo ca viññūnaṃ, bahuñca apuññaṃ pasavati.**“When a foolish, incompetent bad person has four qualities they keep themselves broken and damaged. They deserve to be blamed and criticized by sensible people, and they make much bad karma.*";
P_HTM[53]="*Katamehi catūhi?**What four?*";
P_HTM[54]="*Ananuvicca apariyogāhetvā avaṇṇārahassa vaṇṇaṃ bhāsati,**Without examining or scrutinizing, they praise those deserving of criticism,*";
P_HTM[55]="*ananuvicca apariyogāhetvā vaṇṇārahassa avaṇṇaṃ bhāsati,**and they criticize those deserving of praise.*";
P_HTM[56]="*ananuvicca apariyogāhetvā appasādanīye ṭhāne pasādaṃ upadaṃseti,**They arouse faith in things that are dubious,*";
P_HTM[57]="*ananuvicca apariyogāhetvā pasādanīye ṭhāne appasādaṃ upadaṃseti—**and they don’t arouse faith in things that are inspiring.*";
P_HTM[58]="*imehi kho, bhikkhave, catūhi dhammehi samannāgato bālo abyatto asappuriso khataṃ upahataṃ attānaṃ pariharati, sāvajjo ca hoti sānuvajjo ca viññūnaṃ, bahuñca apuññaṃ pasavati.**When a foolish, incompetent bad person has these four qualities they keep themselves broken and damaged. They deserve to be blamed and criticized by sensible people, and they make much bad karma.*";
P_HTM[59]="*Catūhi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato paṇḍito viyatto sappuriso akkhataṃ anupahataṃ attānaṃ pariharati, anavajjo ca hoti ananuvajjo ca viññūnaṃ, bahuñca puññaṃ pasavati.**When an astute, competent good person has four qualities they keep themselves healthy and whole. They don’t deserve to be blamed and criticized by sensible people, and they make much merit.*";
P_HTM[60]="*Katamehi catūhi?**What four?*";
P_HTM[61]="*Anuvicca pariyogāhetvā avaṇṇārahassa avaṇṇaṃ bhāsati,**After examining and scrutinizing, they criticize those deserving of criticism,*";
P_HTM[62]="*anuvicca pariyogāhetvā vaṇṇārahassa vaṇṇaṃ bhāsati,**and they praise those deserving of praise.*";
P_HTM[63]="*anuvicca pariyogāhetvā appasādanīye ṭhāne appasādaṃ upadaṃseti,**They don’t arouse faith in things that are dubious,*";
P_HTM[64]="*anuvicca pariyogāhetvā pasādanīye ṭhāne pasādaṃ upadaṃseti—**and they do arouse faith in things that are inspiring.*";
P_HTM[65]="*imehi kho, bhikkhave, catūhi dhammehi samannāgato paṇḍito viyatto sappuriso akkhataṃ anupahataṃ attānaṃ pariharati, anavajjo ca hoti ananuvajjo ca viññūnaṃ, bahuñca puññaṃ pasavatīti.**When an astute, competent good person has these four qualities they keep themselves healthy and whole. They don’t deserve to be blamed and criticized by sensible people, and they make much merit.*";
P_HTM[66]="*Yo nindiyaṃ pasaṃsati,**When you praise someone worthy of criticism,*";
P_HTM[67]="*Taṃ vā nindati yo pasaṃsiyo;**or criticize someone worthy of praise,*";
P_HTM[68]="*Vicināti mukhena so kaliṃ,**you choose bad luck with your own mouth:*";
P_HTM[69]="*Kalinā tena sukhaṃ na vindati.**you’ll never find happiness that way.*";
P_HTM[70]="*Appamatto ayaṃ kali,**Bad luck at dice is a trivial thing,*";
P_HTM[71]="*Yo akkhesu dhanaparājayo;**if all you lose is your money*";
P_HTM[72]="*Sabbassāpi sahāpi attanā,**and all you own, even yourself.*";
P_HTM[73]="*Ayameva mahantataro kali;**What’s really terrible luck*";
P_HTM[74]="*Yo sugatesu manaṃ padosaye.**is to hate the holy ones.*";
P_HTM[75]="*Sataṃ sahassānaṃ nirabbudānaṃ,**For more than two quinquadecillion years,*";
P_HTM[76]="*Chattiṃsatī pañca ca abbudāni;**and another five quattuordecillion years,*";
P_HTM[77]="*Yamariyagarahī nirayaṃ upeti,**a slanderer of noble ones goes to hell,*";
P_HTM[78]="*Vācaṃ manañca paṇidhāya pāpakan”ti.**having aimed bad words and thoughts at them.”*";
P_HTM[79]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[80]="*4. Dutiyakhatasuttaṃ**Broken (2nd)*";
P_HTM[81]="*“Catūsu, bhikkhave, micchā paṭipajjamāno bālo abyatto asappuriso khataṃ upahataṃ attānaṃ pariharati sāvajjo ca hoti sānuvajjo ca viññūnaṃ, bahuñca apuññaṃ pasavati.**“When a foolish, incompetent bad person acts wrongly toward four people they keep themselves broken and damaged. They deserve to be blamed and criticized by sensible people, and they make much bad karma.*";
P_HTM[82]="*Katamesu catūsu?**What four?*";
P_HTM[83]="*Mātari, bhikkhave, micchā paṭipajjamāno bālo abyatto asappuriso khataṃ upahataṃ attānaṃ pariharati, sāvajjo ca hoti sānuvajjo ca viññūnaṃ, bahuñca apuññaṃ pasavati.**Mother …*";
P_HTM[84]="*Pitari, bhikkhave, micchā paṭipajjamāno … pe … tathāgate, bhikkhave, micchā paṭipajjamāno … pe … tathāgatasāvake, bhikkhave, micchā paṭipajjamāno bālo abyatto asappuriso khataṃ upahataṃ attānaṃ pariharati, sāvajjo ca hoti sānuvajjo ca viññūnaṃ, bahuñca apuññaṃ pasavati.**father … a Realized One … and a disciple of a Realized One.*";
P_HTM[85]="*Imesu kho, bhikkhave, catūsu micchā paṭipajjamāno bālo abyatto asappuriso khataṃ upahataṃ attānaṃ pariharati, sāvajjo ca hoti sānuvajjo ca viññūnaṃ, bahuñca apuññaṃ pasavati.**When a foolish, incompetent bad person acts wrongly toward these four people they keep themselves broken and damaged. They deserve to be blamed and criticized by sensible people, and they make much bad karma.*";
P_HTM[86]="*Catūsu, bhikkhave, sammā paṭipajjamāno paṇḍito viyatto sappuriso akkhataṃ anupahataṃ attānaṃ pariharati, anavajjo ca hoti ananuvajjo ca viññūnaṃ, bahuñca puññaṃ pasavati.**When an astute, competent good person acts rightly toward four people they keep themselves healthy and whole. They don’t deserve to be blamed and criticized by sensible people, and they make much merit.*";
P_HTM[87]="*Katamesu catūsu?**What four?*";
P_HTM[88]="*Mātari, bhikkhave, sammā paṭipajjamāno paṇḍito viyatto sappuriso akkhataṃ anupahataṃ attānaṃ pariharati, anavajjo ca hoti ananuvajjo ca viññūnaṃ, bahuñca puññaṃ pasavati.**Mother …*";
P_HTM[89]="*Pitari, bhikkhave, sammā paṭipajjamāno … pe … tathāgate, bhikkhave, sammā paṭipajjamāno … pe … tathāgatasāvake, bhikkhave, sammā paṭipajjamāno paṇḍito viyatto sappuriso akkhataṃ anupahataṃ attānaṃ pariharati, anavajjo ca hoti ananuvajjo ca viññūnaṃ, bahuñca puññaṃ pasavati.**father … a Realized One … and a disciple of a Realized One.*";
P_HTM[90]="*Imesu kho, bhikkhave, catūsu sammā paṭipajjamāno paṇḍito viyatto sappuriso akkhataṃ anupahataṃ attānaṃ pariharati, anavajjo ca hoti ananuvajjo ca viññūnaṃ, bahuñca puññaṃ pasavatīti.**When an astute, competent good person acts rightly toward these four people they keep themselves healthy and whole. They don’t deserve to be blamed and criticized by sensible people, and they make much merit.*";
P_HTM[91]="*Mātari pitari cāpi,**A person who does wrong*";
P_HTM[92]="*yo micchā paṭipajjati;**by their mother or father,*";
P_HTM[93]="*Tathāgate vā sambuddhe,**or a Realized One, a Buddha,*";
P_HTM[94]="*atha vā tassa sāvake;**or one of their disciples,*";
P_HTM[95]="*Bahuñca so pasavati,**makes much bad karma.*";
P_HTM[96]="*apuññaṃ tādiso naro.* **";
P_HTM[97]="*Tāya naṃ adhammacariyāya,**Because of their unprincipled conduct*";
P_HTM[98]="*Mātāpitūsu paṇḍitā;**toward their parents,*";
P_HTM[99]="*Idheva naṃ garahanti,**they’re criticized in this life by the astute,*";
P_HTM[100]="*Peccāpāyañca gacchati.**and they depart to be reborn in a place of loss.*";
P_HTM[101]="*Mātari pitari cāpi,**A person who does right*";
P_HTM[102]="*yo sammā paṭipajjati;**by their mother and father,*";
P_HTM[103]="*Tathāgate vā sambuddhe,**or a Realized One, a Buddha,*";
P_HTM[104]="*atha vā tassa sāvake;**or one of their disciples,*";
P_HTM[105]="*Bahuñca so pasavati,**makes much merit.*";
P_HTM[106]="*puññaṃ etādiso naro.* **";
P_HTM[107]="*Tāya naṃ dhammacariyāya,**Because of their principled conduct*";
P_HTM[108]="*mātāpitūsu paṇḍitā;**toward their parents,*";
P_HTM[109]="*Idheva naṃ pasaṃsanti,**they’re praised in this life by the astute,*";
P_HTM[110]="*pecca sagge pamodatī”ti.**and they depart to rejoice in heaven.”*";
P_HTM[111]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[112]="*5. Anusotasuttaṃ**With the Stream*";
P_HTM[113]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, puggalā santo saṃvijjamānā lokasmiṃ.**“These four people are found in the world.*";
P_HTM[114]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[115]="*Anusotagāmī puggalo, paṭisotagāmī puggalo, ṭhitatto puggalo, tiṇṇo pāraṅgato thale tiṭṭhati brāhmaṇo.**A person who goes with the stream; a person who goes against the stream; a steadfast person; and a brahmin who has crossed over and stands on the far shore.*";
P_HTM[116]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, anusotagāmī puggalo?**And who is the person who goes with the stream?*";
P_HTM[117]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco puggalo kāme ca paṭisevati, pāpañca kammaṃ karoti.**It’s a person who takes part in sensual pleasures and does bad deeds.*";
P_HTM[118]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, anusotagāmī puggalo.**This is called a person who goes with the stream.*";
P_HTM[119]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, paṭisotagāmī puggalo?**And who is the person who goes against the stream?*";
P_HTM[120]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco puggalo kāme ca nappaṭisevati, pāpañca kammaṃ na karoti, sahāpi dukkhena sahāpi domanassena assumukhopi rudamāno paripuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ carati.**It’s a person who doesn’t take part in sensual pleasures or do bad deeds. They live the full and pure spiritual life in pain and sadness, weeping, with tearful faces.*";
P_HTM[121]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, paṭisotagāmī puggalo.**This is called a person who goes against the stream.*";
P_HTM[122]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, ṭhitatto puggalo?**And who is the steadfast person?*";
P_HTM[123]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco puggalo pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā opapātiko hoti, tattha parinibbāyī, anāvattidhammo tasmā lokā.**It’s a person who, with the ending of the five lower fetters, is reborn spontaneously. They’re extinguished there, and are not liable to return from that world.*";
P_HTM[124]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, ṭhitatto puggalo.**This is called a steadfast person.*";
P_HTM[125]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, puggalo tiṇṇo pāraṅgato thale tiṭṭhati brāhmaṇo?**And who is a brahmin who has crossed over and stands on the far shore?*";
P_HTM[126]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco puggalo āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati.**It’s a person who realizes the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life. And they live having realized it with their own insight due to the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[127]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, puggalo tiṇṇo pāraṅgato thale tiṭṭhati brāhmaṇo.**This is called a brahmin who has crossed over and stands on the far shore.*";
P_HTM[128]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro puggalā santo saṃvijjamānā lokasminti.**These are the four people found in the world.*";
P_HTM[129]="*Ye keci kāmesu asaññatā janā,**All those people with uncontrolled sensuality,*";
P_HTM[130]="*Avītarāgā idha kāmabhogino;**not free of lust, enjoying sensual pleasures in this life:*";
P_HTM[131]="*Punappunaṃ jātijarūpagāmi te,**again and again, they return to birth and old age;*";
P_HTM[132]="*Taṇhādhipannā anusotagāmino.**those who go with the stream are sunk in craving.*";
P_HTM[133]="*Tasmā hi dhīro idhupaṭṭhitassatī,**So a wise one in this life, with mindfulness established,*";
P_HTM[134]="*Kāme ca pāpe ca asevamāno;**doesn’t take part in sensual pleasures and bad deeds.*";
P_HTM[135]="*Sahāpi dukkhena jaheyya kāme,**In pain they’d give up sensual pleasures:*";
P_HTM[136]="*Paṭisotagāmīti tamāhu puggalaṃ.**they call that person ‘one who goes against the stream’.*";
P_HTM[137]="*Yo ve kilesāni pahāya pañca,**Someone who’s given up five corruptions,*";
P_HTM[138]="*Paripuṇṇasekho aparihānadhammo;**a perfect trainee, not liable to decline,*";
P_HTM[139]="*Cetovasippatto samāhitindriyo,**who’s mastered their mind, with faculties immersed in samādhi,*";
P_HTM[140]="*Sa ve ṭhitattoti naro pavuccati.**that’s called ‘a steadfast person’.*";
P_HTM[141]="*Paroparā yassa samecca dhammā,**The sage who has comprehended all things, high and low,*";
P_HTM[142]="*Vidhūpitā atthagatā na santi;**cleared them and ended them, so they are no more;*";
P_HTM[143]="*Sa ve muni vusitabrahmacariyo,**they’ve completed the spiritual journey, and gone to the end of the world,*";
P_HTM[144]="*Lokantagū pāragatoti vuccatī”ti.**they’re called ‘one who has gone beyond’.”*";
P_HTM[145]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[146]="*6. Appassutasuttaṃ**A Little Learning*";
P_HTM[147]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, puggalā santo saṃvijjamānā lokasmiṃ.**“Mendicants, these four people are found in the world.*";
P_HTM[148]="*Katame cattāro?**What four? A person may have:*";
P_HTM[149]="*Appassuto sutena anupapanno, appassuto sutena upapanno, bahussuto sutena anupapanno, bahussuto sutena upapanno.**~Little learning and not get the point of learning. ~Little learning but get the point of learning. ~Much learning but not get the point of learning. ~Much learning and get the point of learning.*";
P_HTM[150]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, puggalo appassuto hoti sutena anupapanno?**And how has a person learned little and not got the point of learning?*";
P_HTM[151]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekaccassa puggalassa appakaṃ sutaṃ hoti—**It’s when a person has learned little of the*";
P_HTM[152]="*suttaṃ geyyaṃ veyyākaraṇaṃ gāthā udānaṃ itivuttakaṃ jātakaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ vedallaṃ.**statements, songs, discussions, verses, inspired exclamations, legends, stories of past lives, amazing stories, and classifications.*";
P_HTM[153]="*So tassa appakassa sutassa na atthamaññāya dhammamaññāya dhammānudhammappaṭipanno hoti.**And with the little they’ve learned, they understand neither the meaning nor the text, nor do they practice in line with the teaching.*";
P_HTM[154]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, puggalo appassuto hoti sutena anupapanno.**That’s how a person has learned little and not got the point of learning.*";
P_HTM[155]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, puggalo appassuto hoti sutena upapanno?**And how has a person learned little but has got the point of learning?*";
P_HTM[156]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekaccassa puggalassa appakaṃ sutaṃ hoti—**It’s when a person has learned little of the*";
P_HTM[157]="*suttaṃ geyyaṃ veyyākaraṇaṃ gāthā udānaṃ itivuttakaṃ jātakaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ vedallaṃ.**statements, songs, discussions, verses, inspired exclamations, legends, stories of past lives, amazing stories, and classifications.*";
P_HTM[158]="*So tassa appakassa sutassa atthamaññāya dhammamaññāya dhammānudhammappaṭipanno hoti.**But with the little they’ve learned, they understand the meaning and the text, and they practice in line with the teaching.*";
P_HTM[159]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, puggalo appassuto hoti sutena upapanno.**That’s how a person has learned little but has got the point of learning.*";
P_HTM[160]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, puggalo bahussuto hoti sutena anupapanno?**And how has a person learned much but hasn't got the point of learning?*";
P_HTM[161]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekaccassa puggalassa bahukaṃ sutaṃ hoti—**It’s when a person has learned much of the*";
P_HTM[162]="*suttaṃ geyyaṃ veyyākaraṇaṃ gāthā udānaṃ itivuttakaṃ jātakaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ vedallaṃ.**statements, songs, discussions, verses, inspired exclamations, legends, stories of past lives, amazing stories, and classifications.*";
P_HTM[163]="*So tassa bahukassa sutassa na atthamaññāya dhammamaññāya dhammānudhammappaṭipanno hoti.**But even though they’ve learned much, they understand neither the meaning nor the text, nor do they practice in line with the teaching.*";
P_HTM[164]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, puggalo bahussuto hoti sutena anupapanno.**That’s how a person has learned much but hasn't got the point of learning.*";
P_HTM[165]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, puggalo bahussuto hoti sutena upapanno?**And how has a person learned much and has got the point of learning?*";
P_HTM[166]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekaccassa puggalassa bahukaṃ sutaṃ hoti—**It’s when a person has learned much of the*";
P_HTM[167]="*suttaṃ geyyaṃ veyyākaraṇaṃ gāthā udānaṃ itivuttakaṃ jātakaṃ abbhutadhammaṃ vedallaṃ.**statements, songs, discussions, verses, inspired exclamations, legends, stories of past lives, amazing stories, and classifications.*";
P_HTM[168]="*So tassa bahukassa sutassa atthamaññāya dhammamaññāya dhammānudhammappaṭipanno hoti.**And with the large amount they’ve learned, they understand the meaning and the text, and they practice in line with the teaching.*";
P_HTM[169]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, puggalo bahussuto hoti sutena upapanno.**That’s how a person has learned much and has got the point of learning.*";
P_HTM[170]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro puggalā santo saṃvijjamānā lokasminti.**These are the four people found in the world.*";
P_HTM[171]="*Appassutopi ce hoti,**If you don’t learn much,*";
P_HTM[172]="*sīlesu asamāhito;**and aren’t steady in ethics,*";
P_HTM[173]="*Ubhayena naṃ garahanti,**they’ll criticize you on both counts,*";
P_HTM[174]="*sīlato ca sutena ca.**for your ethics and your learning.*";
P_HTM[175]="*Appassutopi ce hoti,**If you don’t learn much,*";
P_HTM[176]="*sīlesu susamāhito;**and you are steady in ethics,*";
P_HTM[177]="*Sīlato naṃ pasaṃsanti,**they’ll praise your ethical conduct,*";
P_HTM[178]="*tassa sampajjate sutaṃ.**since your learning has succeeded.*";
P_HTM[179]="*Bahussutopi ce hoti,**If you learn much,*";
P_HTM[180]="*sīlesu asamāhito;**but aren’t steady in ethics,*";
P_HTM[181]="*Sīlato naṃ garahanti,**they’ll criticize your ethical conduct,*";
P_HTM[182]="*nāssa sampajjate sutaṃ.**for your learning hasn’t succeeded.*";
P_HTM[183]="*Bahussutopi ce hoti,**If you learn much,*";
P_HTM[184]="*sīlesu susamāhito;**and you are steady in ethics,*";
P_HTM[185]="*Ubhayena naṃ pasaṃsanti,**they’ll praise you on both counts,*";
P_HTM[186]="*sīlato ca sutena ca.**for your ethics and your learning.*";
P_HTM[187]="*Bahussutaṃ dhammadharaṃ,**A wise disciple of the Buddha*";
P_HTM[188]="*sappaññaṃ buddhasāvakaṃ;**who has much learning, and has memorized the teachings,*";
P_HTM[189]="*Nekkhaṃ jambonadasseva,**is like a coin of mountain gold.*";
P_HTM[190]="*ko taṃ ninditumarahati;**Who is worthy of criticizing them?*";
P_HTM[191]="*Devāpi naṃ pasaṃsanti,**Even the gods praise them,*";
P_HTM[192]="*brahmunāpi pasaṃsito”ti.**and by Brahmā, too, they’re praised.”*";
P_HTM[193]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[194]="*7. Sobhanasuttaṃ**Beautification*";
P_HTM[195]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, viyattā vinītā visāradā bahussutā dhammadharā dhammānudhammappaṭipannā saṃghaṃ sobhenti.**“Mendicants, these four competent, educated, assured, learned people—who have memorized the teachings and practice in line with the teachings—beautify the Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[196]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[197]="*Bhikkhu, bhikkhave, viyatto vinīto visārado bahussuto dhammadharo dhammānudhammappaṭipanno saṃghaṃ sobheti.**A monk,*";
P_HTM[198]="*Bhikkhunī, bhikkhave, viyattā vinītā visāradā bahussutā dhammadharā dhammānudhammappaṭipannā saṃghaṃ sobheti.**a nun,*";
P_HTM[199]="*Upāsako, bhikkhave, viyatto vinīto visārado bahussuto dhammadharo dhammānudhammappaṭipanno saṃghaṃ sobheti.**a layman,*";
P_HTM[200]="*Upāsikā, bhikkhave, viyattā vinītā visāradā bahussutā dhammadharā dhammānudhammappaṭipannā saṃghaṃ sobheti.**and a laywoman.*";
P_HTM[201]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro viyattā vinītā visāradā bahussutā dhammadharā dhammānudhammappaṭipannā saṃghaṃ sobhentīti.**These four competent, educated, assured, learned people—who have memorized the teachings and practice in line with the teachings—beautify the Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[202]="*Yo hoti viyatto ca visārado ca,**Whoever is competent and assured,*";
P_HTM[203]="*Bahussuto dhammadharo ca hoti;**learned, a memorizer of the teachings,*";
P_HTM[204]="*Dhammassa hoti anudhammacārī,**who lives in line with the teachings—*";
P_HTM[205]="*Sa tādiso vuccati saṃghasobhano.**such a person is said to beautify the Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[206]="*Bhikkhu ca sīlasampanno,**A monk accomplished in ethics,*";
P_HTM[207]="*bhikkhunī ca bahussutā;**and a learned nun,*";
P_HTM[208]="*Upāsako ca yo saddho,**a faithful layman,*";
P_HTM[209]="*yā ca saddhā upāsikā;**and a faithful laywoman, too:*";
P_HTM[210]="*Ete kho saṅghaṃ sobhenti,**these beautify the Saṅgha,*";
P_HTM[211]="*ete hi saṅghasobhanā”ti.**they are the beautifiers of the Saṅgha.”*";
P_HTM[212]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[213]="*8. Vesārajjasuttaṃ**Self*";
P_HTM[214]="*“Cattārimāni, bhikkhave, tathāgatassa vesārajjāni, yehi vesārajjehi samannāgato tathāgato āsabhaṃ ṭhānaṃ paṭijānāti, parisāsu sīhanādaṃ nadati, brahmacakkaṃ pavatteti.**“Mendicants, a Realized One has four kinds of self-assurance. With these he claims the bull’s place, roars his lion’s roar in the assemblies, and turns the holy wheel.*";
P_HTM[215]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[216]="*‘“Sammāsambuddhassa te paṭijānato ime dhammā anabhisambuddhā”ti tatra vata maṃ samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā devo vā māro vā brahmā vā koci vā lokasmiṃ sahadhammena paṭicodessatī’ti nimittametaṃ, bhikkhave, na samanupassāmi.**I see no reason for anyone—whether ascetic, brahmin, god, Māra, or Brahmā, or anyone else in the world—to legitimately scold me, saying: ‘You claim to be fully awakened, but you don’t understand these things.’*";
P_HTM[217]="*Etamahaṃ, bhikkhave, nimittaṃ asamanupassanto khemappatto abhayappatto vesārajjappatto viharāmi.**Since I see no such reason, I live secure, fearless, and assured.*";
P_HTM[218]="*‘“Khīṇāsavassa te paṭijānato ime āsavā aparikkhīṇā”ti tatra vata maṃ samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā devo vā māro vā brahmā vā koci vā lokasmiṃ sahadhammena paṭicodessatī’ti nimittametaṃ, bhikkhave, na samanupassāmi.**I see no reason for anyone—whether ascetic, brahmin, god, Māra, or Brahmā, or anyone else in the world—to legitimately scold me, saying: ‘You claim to have ended all defilements, but these defilements have not ended.’*";
P_HTM[219]="*Etamahaṃ, bhikkhave, nimittaṃ asamanupassanto khemappatto abhayappatto vesārajjappatto viharāmi.**Since I see no such reason, I live secure, fearless, and assured.*";
P_HTM[220]="*‘“Ye kho pana te antarāyikā dhammā vuttā te paṭisevato nālaṃ antarāyāyā”ti tatra vata maṃ samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā devo vā māro vā brahmā vā koci vā lokasmiṃ sahadhammena paṭicodessatī’ti nimittametaṃ, bhikkhave, na samanupassāmi.**I see no reason for anyone—whether ascetic, brahmin, god, Māra, or Brahmā, or anyone else in the world—to legitimately scold me, saying: ‘The acts that you say are obstructions are not really obstructions for the one who performs them.’*";
P_HTM[221]="*Etamahaṃ, bhikkhave, nimittaṃ asamanupassanto khemappatto abhayappatto vesārajjappatto viharāmi.**Since I see no such reason, I live secure, fearless, and assured.*";
P_HTM[222]="*‘“Yassa kho pana te atthāya dhammo desito so na niyyāti takkarassa sammā dukkhakkhayāyā”ti tatra vata maṃ samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā devo vā māro vā brahmā vā koci vā lokasmiṃ sahadhammena paṭicodessatī’ti nimittametaṃ, bhikkhave, na samanupassāmi.**I see no reason for anyone—whether ascetic, brahmin, god, Māra, or Brahmā, or anyone else in the world—to legitimately scold me, saying: ‘Though you teach that this teaching leads to the goal of the complete ending of suffering, it doesn’t lead there for one who practices it.’*";
P_HTM[223]="*Etamahaṃ, bhikkhave, nimittaṃ asamanupassanto khemappatto abhayappatto vesārajjappatto viharāmi.**Since I see no such reason, I live secure, fearless, and assured.*";
P_HTM[224]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, cattāri tathāgatassa vesārajjāni, yehi vesārajjehi samannāgato tathāgato āsabhaṃ ṭhānaṃ paṭijānāti, parisāsu sīhanādaṃ nadati, brahmacakkaṃ pavattetīti.**A Realized One has these four kinds of self-assurance. With these he claims the bull’s place, roars his lion’s roar in the assemblies, and turns the holy wheel.*";
P_HTM[225]="*Ye kecime vādapathā puthussitā,**The various grounds for criticism*";
P_HTM[226]="*Yaṃnissitā samaṇabrāhmaṇā ca;**that ascetics and brahmins rely on*";
P_HTM[227]="*Tathāgataṃ patvā na te bhavanti,**don’t touch a Realized One,*";
P_HTM[228]="*Visāradaṃ vādapathātivattaṃ.**assured, gone beyond grounds for criticism.*";
P_HTM[229]="*Yo dhammacakkaṃ abhibhuyya kevalī,**He rolls forth the Wheel of Dhamma as a consummate one,*";
P_HTM[230]="*Pavattayī sabbabhūtānukampī;**complete, compassionate for all living creatures.*";
P_HTM[231]="*Taṃ tādisaṃ devamanussaseṭṭhaṃ,**Sentient beings revere him, best of gods and humans,*";
P_HTM[232]="*Sattā namassanti bhavassa pāragun”ti.**who has gone beyond rebirth.”*";
P_HTM[233]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[234]="*9. Taṇhuppādasuttaṃ**The Arising of Craving*";
P_HTM[235]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, taṇhuppādā yattha bhikkhuno taṇhā uppajjamānā uppajjati.**“Mendicants, there are four things that give rise to craving in a mendicant.*";
P_HTM[236]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[237]="*Cīvarahetu vā, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno taṇhā uppajjamānā uppajjati;**For the sake of robes,*";
P_HTM[238]="*piṇḍapātahetu vā, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno taṇhā uppajjamānā uppajjati;**alms-food,*";
P_HTM[239]="*senāsanahetu vā, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno taṇhā uppajjamānā uppajjati;**lodgings,*";
P_HTM[240]="*itibhavābhavahetu vā, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno taṇhā uppajjamānā uppajjati.**or rebirth in this or that state.*";
P_HTM[241]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro taṇhuppādā yattha bhikkhuno taṇhā uppajjamānā uppajjatīti.**These are the four things that give rise to craving in a mendicant.*";
P_HTM[242]="*Taṇhā dutiyo puriso,**Craving is a person’s partner*";
P_HTM[243]="*dīghamaddhāna saṃsaraṃ;**as they transmigrate on this long journey.*";
P_HTM[244]="*Itthabhāvaññathābhāvaṃ,**They go from this state to another,*";
P_HTM[245]="*saṃsāraṃ nātivattati.**but don’t get past transmigration.*";
P_HTM[246]="*Evamādīnavaṃ ñatvā,**Knowing this drawback—*";
P_HTM[247]="*Taṇhaṃ dukkhassa sambhavaṃ;**that craving is the cause of suffering—*";
P_HTM[248]="*Vītataṇho anādāno,**rid of craving, by not grasping,*";
P_HTM[249]="*Sato bhikkhu paribbaje”ti.**a mendicant would go forth mindfully.”*";
P_HTM[250]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[251]="*10. Yogasuttaṃ**Attachments*";
P_HTM[252]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, yogā.**“Mendicants, there are these four attachments.*";
P_HTM[253]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[254]="*Kāmayogo, bhavayogo, diṭṭhiyogo, avijjāyogo.**The attachment to sensual pleasures, future lives, views, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[255]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, kāmayogo?**And what is the attachment to sensual pleasures?*";
P_HTM[256]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco kāmānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**It’s when you don’t truly understand sensual pleasures’ origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape.*";
P_HTM[257]="*Tassa kāmānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ appajānato yo kāmesu kāmarāgo kāmanandī kāmasneho kāmamucchā kāmapipāsā kāmapariḷāho kāmajjhosānaṃ kāmataṇhā sānuseti.**So greed, relishing, affection, infatuation, thirst, passion, attachment, and craving for sensual pleasures linger on inside.*";
P_HTM[258]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, kāmayogo.**This is called the attachment to sensual pleasures.*";
P_HTM[259]="*Iti kāmayogo.**Such is the attachment to sensual pleasures.*";
P_HTM[260]="*Bhavayogo ca kathaṃ hoti?**And what is the attachment to future lives?*";
P_HTM[261]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco bhavānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**It’s when you don’t truly understand future lives’ origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape.*";
P_HTM[262]="*Tassa bhavānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ appajānato yo bhavesu bhavarāgo bhavanandī bhavasneho bhavamucchā bhavapipāsā bhavapariḷāho bhavajjhosānaṃ bhavataṇhā sānuseti.**So lust, delight, affection, infatuation, thirst, passion, attachment, and craving for continued existence linger on inside.*";
P_HTM[263]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, bhavayogo.**This is called the attachment to future lives.*";
P_HTM[264]="*Iti kāmayogo bhavayogo.**Such are the attachments to sensual pleasures and future lives.*";
P_HTM[265]="*Diṭṭhiyogo ca kathaṃ hoti?**And what is the attachment to views?*";
P_HTM[266]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco diṭṭhīnaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**It’s when you don’t truly understand views’ origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape.*";
P_HTM[267]="*Tassa diṭṭhīnaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ appajānato yo diṭṭhīsu diṭṭhirāgo diṭṭhinandī diṭṭhisneho diṭṭhimucchā diṭṭhipipāsā diṭṭhipariḷāho diṭṭhijjhosānaṃ diṭṭhitaṇhā sānuseti.**So lust, delight, affection, infatuation, thirst, passion, attachment, and craving for views linger on inside.*";
P_HTM[268]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, diṭṭhiyogo.**This is called the attachment to views.*";
P_HTM[269]="*Iti kāmayogo bhavayogo diṭṭhiyogo.**Such are the attachments to sensual pleasures, future lives, and views.*";
P_HTM[270]="*Avijjāyogo ca kathaṃ hoti?**And what is the attachment to ignorance?*";
P_HTM[271]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco channaṃ phassāyatanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**It’s when you don’t truly understand the six fields of contacts’ origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape,*";
P_HTM[272]="*Tassa channaṃ phassāyatanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ appajānato yā chasu phassāyatanesu avijjā aññāṇaṃ sānuseti.**so ignorance and unknowing of the six fields of contact linger on inside.*";
P_HTM[273]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, avijjāyogo.**This is called the attachment to ignorance.*";
P_HTM[274]="*Iti kāmayogo bhavayogo diṭṭhiyogo avijjāyogo,**Such are the attachments to sensual pleasures, future lives, views, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[275]="*saṃyutto pāpakehi akusalehi dhammehi saṃkilesikehi ponobhavikehi sadarehi dukkhavipākehi āyatiṃ jātijarāmaraṇikehi. Tasmā ayogakkhemīti vuccati.**Someone attached to bad, unskillful qualities—corruptions that lead to future lives and are hurtful, resulting in suffering and future rebirth, old age, and death—is called: ‘one who has not found sanctuary from attachments’.*";
P_HTM[276]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro yogā.**These are the four attachments.*";
P_HTM[277]="*Cattārome, bhikkhave, visaṃyogā.**There are these four kinds of detachment.*";
P_HTM[278]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[279]="*Kāmayogavisaṃyogo, bhavayogavisaṃyogo, diṭṭhiyogavisaṃyogo, avijjāyogavisaṃyogo.**Detachment from sensual pleasures, future lives, views, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[280]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, kāmayogavisaṃyogo?**And what is detachment from sensual pleasures?*";
P_HTM[281]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco kāmānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**It’s when you truly understand sensual pleasures’ origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape.*";
P_HTM[282]="*Tassa kāmānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ pajānato yo kāmesu kāmarāgo kāmanandī kāmasneho kāmamucchā kāmapipāsā kāmapariḷāho kāmajjhosānaṃ kāmataṇhā sā nānuseti.**So greed, relishing, affection, infatuation, thirst, passion, attachment, and craving for sensual pleasures don’t linger on inside.*";
P_HTM[283]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, kāmayogavisaṃyogo.**This is called detachment from sensual pleasures.*";
P_HTM[284]="*Iti kāmayogavisaṃyogo.**Such is detachment from sensual pleasures.*";
P_HTM[285]="*Bhavayogavisaṃyogo ca kathaṃ hoti?**And what is detachment from future lives?*";
P_HTM[286]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco bhavānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**It’s when you truly understand future lives’ origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape.*";
P_HTM[287]="*Tassa bhavānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ pajānato yo bhavesu bhavarāgo bhavanandī bhavasneho bhavamucchā bhavapipāsā bhavapariḷāho bhavajjhosānaṃ bhavataṇhā sā nānuseti.**So lust, delight, affection, infatuation, thirst, passion, attachment, and craving for continued existence don’t linger on inside.*";
P_HTM[288]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, bhavayogavisaṃyogo.**This is called detachment from future lives.*";
P_HTM[289]="*Iti kāmayogavisaṃyogo bhavayogavisaṃyogo.**Such is detachment from sensual pleasures and future lives.*";
P_HTM[290]="*Diṭṭhiyogavisaṃyogo ca kathaṃ hoti?**And what is detachment from views?*";
P_HTM[291]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco diṭṭhīnaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**It’s when you don’t truly understand views’ origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape.*";
P_HTM[292]="*Tassa diṭṭhīnaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ pajānato yo diṭṭhīsu diṭṭhirāgo diṭṭhinandī diṭṭhisneho diṭṭhimucchā diṭṭhipipāsā diṭṭhipariḷāho diṭṭhijjhosānaṃ diṭṭhitaṇhā sā nānuseti.**So lust, delight, affection, infatuation, thirst, passion, attachment, and craving for views linger on inside.*";
P_HTM[293]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, diṭṭhiyogavisaṃyogo.**This is called detachment from views.*";
P_HTM[294]="*Iti kāmayogavisaṃyogo bhavayogavisaṃyogo diṭṭhiyogavisaṃyogo.**Such is detachment from sensual pleasures, future lives, and views.*";
P_HTM[295]="*Avijjāyogavisaṃyogo ca kathaṃ hoti?**And what is detachment from ignorance?*";
P_HTM[296]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco channaṃ phassāyatanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**It’s when you truly understand the six fields of contacts’ origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape,*";
P_HTM[297]="*Tassa channaṃ phassāyatanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ pajānato yā chasu phassāyatanesu avijjā aññāṇaṃ sā nānuseti.**so ignorance and unknowing of the six fields of contact don’t linger on inside.*";
P_HTM[298]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, avijjāyogavisaṃyogo.**This is called detachment from ignorance.*";
P_HTM[299]="*Iti kāmayogavisaṃyogo bhavayogavisaṃyogo diṭṭhiyogavisaṃyogo avijjāyogavisaṃyogo,**Such is detachment from sensual pleasures, future lives, views, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[300]="*visaṃyutto pāpakehi akusalehi dhammehi saṅkilesikehi ponobhavikehi sadarehi dukkhavipākehi āyatiṃ jātijarāmaraṇikehi. Tasmā yogakkhemīti vuccati.**Someone detached from bad, unskillful qualities—defilements that lead to future lives and are hurtful, resulting in suffering and future rebirth, old age, and death—is called: ‘one who has found sanctuary from attachments’.*";
P_HTM[301]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro visaṃyogāti.**These are the four kinds of detachment.*";
P_HTM[302]="*Kāmayogena saṃyuttā,**Attached to both sensual pleasures*";
P_HTM[303]="*bhavayogena cūbhayaṃ;**and the desire to be reborn in a future life;*";
P_HTM[304]="*Diṭṭhiyogena saṃyuttā,**attached also to views,*";
P_HTM[305]="*avijjāya purakkhatā.**with ignorance in the forefront,*";
P_HTM[306]="*Sattā gacchanti saṃsāraṃ,**sentient beings continue to transmigrate,*";
P_HTM[307]="*jātimaraṇagāmino;**with ongoing birth and death.*";
P_HTM[308]="*Ye ca kāme pariññāya,**But those who completely understand sensual pleasures,*";
P_HTM[309]="*bhavayogañca sabbaso.**and the attachment to all future lives;*";
P_HTM[310]="*Diṭṭhiyogaṃ samūhacca,**with the attachment to views eradicated,*";
P_HTM[311]="*avijjañca virājayaṃ;**and ignorance dispelled,*";
P_HTM[312]="*Sabbayogavisaṃyuttā,**detached from all attachments,*";
P_HTM[313]="*te ve yogātigā munī”ti.**those sages have gone beyond all attachments.”*";
P_HTM[314]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[315]="*Bhaṇḍagāmavaggo paṭhamo.* **";
P_HTM[316]="*Anubuddhaṃ papatitaṃ dve,* **";
P_HTM[317]="*Khatā anusotapañcamaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[318]="*Appassuto ca sobhanaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[319]="*Vesārajjaṃ taṇhāyogena te dasāti.* **";
P_HTM[320]="*3. Tatiyapaṇṇāsakaṃ**Walking*";
P_HTM[321]="*1. Carasuttaṃ**Walking*";
P_HTM[322]="*“Carato cepi, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno uppajjati kāmavitakko vā byāpādavitakko vā vihiṃsāvitakko vā.**“Mendicants, suppose a mendicant has a sensual, malicious, or cruel thought while walking.*";
P_HTM[323]="*Tañce bhikkhu adhivāseti, nappajahati na vinodeti na byantīkaroti na anabhāvaṃ gameti, carampi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu evaṃbhūto ‘anātāpī anottāpī satataṃ samitaṃ kusīto hīnavīriyo’ti vuccati.**They tolerate it and don’t give it up, get rid of it, eliminate it, and obliterate it. Such a mendicant is said to be ‘not keen or prudent, always lazy, and lacking energy’ when walking.*";
P_HTM[324]="*Ṭhitassa cepi, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno uppajjati kāmavitakko vā byāpādavitakko vā vihiṃsāvitakko vā.**Suppose a mendicant has a sensual, malicious, or cruel thought while standing …*";
P_HTM[325]="*Tañce bhikkhu adhivāseti, nappajahati na vinodeti na byantīkaroti na anabhāvaṃ gameti, ṭhitopi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu evaṃbhūto ‘anātāpī anottāpī satataṃ samitaṃ kusīto hīnavīriyo’ti vuccati.* **";
P_HTM[326]="*Nisinnassa cepi, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno uppajjati kāmavitakko vā byāpādavitakko vā vihiṃsāvitakko vā.**sitting …*";
P_HTM[327]="*Tañce bhikkhu adhivāseti, nappajahati na vinodeti na byantīkaroti na anabhāvaṃ gameti, nisinnopi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu evaṃbhūto ‘anātāpī anottāpī satataṃ samitaṃ kusīto hīnavīriyo’ti vuccati.* **";
P_HTM[328]="*Sayānassa cepi, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno jāgarassa uppajjati kāmavitakko vā byāpādavitakko vā vihiṃsāvitakko vā.**or when lying down while awake.*";
P_HTM[329]="*Tañce bhikkhu adhivāseti, nappajahati na vinodeti na byantīkaroti na anabhāvaṃ gameti, sayānopi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu jāgaro evaṃbhūto ‘anātāpī anottāpī satataṃ samitaṃ kusīto hīnavīriyo’ti vuccati.**They tolerate it and don’t give it up, get rid of it, eliminate it, and obliterate it. Such a mendicant is said to be ‘not keen or prudent, always lazy, and lacking energy’ when lying down while awake.*";
P_HTM[330]="*Carato cepi, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno uppajjati kāmavitakko vā byāpādavitakko vā vihiṃsāvitakko vā.**Suppose a mendicant has a sensual, malicious, or cruel thought while walking.*";
P_HTM[331]="*Tañce bhikkhu nādhivāseti, pajahati vinodeti byantīkaroti anabhāvaṃ gameti;**They don’t tolerate it, but give it up, get rid of it, eliminate it, and obliterate it.*";
P_HTM[332]="*carampi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu evaṃbhūto ‘ātāpī ottāpī satataṃ samitaṃ āraddhavīriyo pahitatto’ti vuccati.**Such a mendicant is said to be ‘keen and prudent, always energetic and determined’ when walking.*";
P_HTM[333]="*Ṭhitassa cepi, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno uppajjati kāmavitakko vā byāpādavitakko vā vihiṃsāvitakko vā.**Suppose a mendicant has a sensual, malicious, or cruel thought while standing …*";
P_HTM[334]="*Tañce bhikkhu nādhivāseti, pajahati vinodeti byantīkaroti anabhāvaṃ gameti;* **";
P_HTM[335]="*ṭhitopi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu evaṃbhūto ‘ātāpī ottāpī satataṃ samitaṃ āraddhavīriyo pahitatto’ti vuccati.* **";
P_HTM[336]="*Nisinnassa cepi, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno uppajjati kāmavitakko vā byāpādavitakko vā vihiṃsāvitakko vā.**sitting …*";
P_HTM[337]="*Tañce bhikkhu nādhivāseti, pajahati vinodeti byantīkaroti anabhāvaṃ gameti;* **";
P_HTM[338]="*nisinnopi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu evaṃbhūto ‘ātāpī ottāpī satataṃ samitaṃ āraddhavīriyo pahitatto’ti vuccati.* **";
P_HTM[339]="*Sayānassa cepi, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno jāgarassa uppajjati kāmavitakko vā byāpādavitakko vā vihiṃsāvitakko vā.**or when lying down while awake.*";
P_HTM[340]="*Tañce bhikkhu nādhivāseti, pajahati vinodeti byantīkaroti anabhāvaṃ gameti;**They don’t tolerate it, but give it up, get rid of it, eliminate it, and obliterate it.*";
P_HTM[341]="*sayānopi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu jāgaro evaṃbhūto ‘ātāpī ottāpī satataṃ samitaṃ āraddhavīriyo pahitatto’ti vuccatīti.**Such a mendicant is said to be ‘keen and prudent, always energetic and determined’ when lying down while awake.”*";
P_HTM[342]="*Caraṃ vā yadi vā tiṭṭhaṃ,**Whether walking or standing,*";
P_HTM[343]="*nisinno uda vā sayaṃ;**sitting or lying down,*";
P_HTM[344]="*Yo vitakkaṃ vitakketi,**if you think a bad thought*";
P_HTM[345]="*pāpakaṃ gehanissitaṃ.**to do with the lay life,*";
P_HTM[346]="*Kummaggappaṭipanno so,**you’re on the wrong path,*";
P_HTM[347]="*Mohaneyyesu mucchito;**lost among things that delude.*";
P_HTM[348]="*Abhabbo tādiso bhikkhu,**Such a mendicant is incapable*";
P_HTM[349]="*Phuṭṭhuṃ sambodhimuttamaṃ.**of touching the highest awakening.*";
P_HTM[350]="*Yo ca caraṃ vā tiṭṭhaṃ vā,**But one who, whether standing or walking,*";
P_HTM[351]="*Nisinno uda vā sayaṃ;**sitting or lying down,*";
P_HTM[352]="*Vitakkaṃ samayitvāna,**has calmed their thoughts,*";
P_HTM[353]="*Vitakkūpasame rato;**loving peace of mind;*";
P_HTM[354]="*Bhabbo so tādiso bhikkhu,**such a mendicant is capable*";
P_HTM[355]="*Phuṭṭhuṃ sambodhimuttaman”ti.**of touching the highest awakening.”*";
P_HTM[356]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[357]="*2. Sīlasuttaṃ**Ethics*";
P_HTM[358]="*“Sampannasīlā, bhikkhave, viharatha sampannapātimokkhā, pātimokkhasaṃvarasaṃvutā viharatha ācāragocarasampannā, aṇumattesu vajjesu bhayadassāvino samādāya sikkhatha sikkhāpadesu.**“Mendicants, live by the ethical precepts and the monastic code. Live restrained in the code of conduct, conducting yourselves well and seeking alms in suitable places. Seeing danger in the slightest fault, keep the rules you’ve undertaken.*";
P_HTM[359]="*Sampannasīlānaṃ vo, bhikkhave, viharataṃ sampannapātimokkhānaṃ pātimokkhasaṃvarasaṃvutānaṃ viharataṃ ācāragocarasampannānaṃ aṇumattesu vajjesu bhayadassāvīnaṃ samādāya sikkhataṃ sikkhāpadesu, kimassa uttari karaṇīyaṃ?**When you’ve done this, what more is there to do?*";
P_HTM[360]="*Carato cepi, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno abhijjhābyāpādo vigato hoti, thinamiddhaṃ … uddhaccakukkuccaṃ … vicikicchā pahīnā hoti, āraddhaṃ hoti vīriyaṃ asallīnaṃ, upaṭṭhitā sati asammuṭṭhā, passaddho kāyo asāraddho, samāhitaṃ cittaṃ ekaggaṃ, carampi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu evaṃbhūto ‘ātāpī ottāpī satataṃ samitaṃ āraddhavīriyo pahitatto’ti vuccati.**Suppose a mendicant has got rid of desire and ill will while walking, and has given up dullness and drowsiness, restlessness and remorse, and doubt. Their energy is roused up and unflagging, their mindfulness is established and lucid, their body is tranquil and undisturbed, and their mind is immersed in samādhi. Such a mendicant is said to be ‘keen and prudent, always energetic and determined’ when walking.*";
P_HTM[361]="*Ṭhitassa cepi, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno abhijjhābyāpādo vigato hoti, thinamiddhaṃ … uddhaccakukkuccaṃ … vicikicchā pahīnā hoti, āraddhaṃ hoti vīriyaṃ asallīnaṃ, upaṭṭhitā sati asammuṭṭhā, passaddho kāyo asāraddho, samāhitaṃ cittaṃ ekaggaṃ, ṭhitopi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu evaṃbhūto ‘ātāpī ottāpī satataṃ samitaṃ āraddhavīriyo pahitatto’ti vuccati.**Suppose a mendicant has got rid of desire and ill will while standing …*";
P_HTM[362]="*Nisinnassa cepi, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno abhijjhābyāpādo vigato hoti, thinamiddhaṃ … uddhaccakukkuccaṃ … vicikicchā pahīnā hoti, āraddhaṃ hoti vīriyaṃ asallīnaṃ, upaṭṭhitā sati asammuṭṭhā, passaddho kāyo asāraddho, samāhitaṃ cittaṃ ekaggaṃ, nisinnopi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu evaṃbhūto ‘ātāpī ottāpī satataṃ samitaṃ āraddhavīriyo pahitatto’ti vuccati.**sitting …*";
P_HTM[363]="*Sayānassa cepi, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno jāgarassa abhijjhābyāpādo vigato hoti, thinamiddhaṃ … uddhaccakukkuccaṃ … vicikicchā pahīnā hoti, āraddhaṃ hoti vīriyaṃ asallīnaṃ, upaṭṭhitā sati asammuṭṭhā, passaddho kāyo asāraddho, samāhitaṃ cittaṃ ekaggaṃ, sayānopi, bhikkhave, bhikkhu jāgaro evaṃbhūto ‘ātāpī ottāpī satataṃ samitaṃ āraddhavīriyo pahitatto’ti vuccatīti.**and when lying down while awake, and has given up dullness and drowsiness, restlessness and remorse, and doubt. Their energy is roused up and unflagging, their mindfulness is established and lucid, their body is tranquil and undisturbed, and their mind is immersed in samādhi. Such a mendicant is said to be ‘keen and prudent, always energetic and determined’ when lying down while awake.*";
P_HTM[364]="*Yataṃ care yataṃ tiṭṭhe,**Carefully walking, carefully standing,*";
P_HTM[365]="*Yataṃ acche yataṃ saye;**carefully sitting, carefully lying;*";
P_HTM[366]="*Yataṃ samiñjaye bhikkhu,**a mendicant carefully bends their limbs,*";
P_HTM[367]="*Yatamenaṃ pasāraye.**and carefully extends them.*";
P_HTM[368]="*Uddhaṃ tiriyaṃ apācīnaṃ,**Above, below, and all around,*";
P_HTM[369]="*yāvatājagatogati;**as far as the earth extends;*";
P_HTM[370]="*Samavekkhitā ca dhammānaṃ,**they scrutinize the rise and fall*";
P_HTM[371]="*khandhānaṃ udayabbayaṃ.**of phenomena such as the aggregates.*";
P_HTM[372]="*Cetosamathasāmīciṃ,**Training in what leads to serenity of heart,*";
P_HTM[373]="*sikkhamānaṃ sadā sataṃ;**always staying mindful;*";
P_HTM[374]="*Satataṃ pahitattoti,**they call such a mendicant*";
P_HTM[375]="*āhu bhikkhuṃ tathāvidhan”ti.**‘always determined’.”*";
P_HTM[376]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[377]="*3. Padhānasuttaṃ**Effort*";
P_HTM[378]="*“Cattārimāni, bhikkhave, sammappadhānāni.**“Mendicants, there are these four right efforts.*";
P_HTM[379]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[380]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu anuppannānaṃ pāpakānaṃ akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ anuppādāya chandaṃ janeti vāyamati vīriyaṃ ārabhati cittaṃ paggaṇhāti padahati;**A mendicant generates enthusiasm, tries, makes an effort, exerts the mind, and strives so that bad, unskillful qualities don’t arise.*";
P_HTM[381]="*uppannānaṃ pāpakānaṃ akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pahānāya chandaṃ janeti vāyamati vīriyaṃ ārabhati cittaṃ paggaṇhāti padahati;**They generate enthusiasm, try, make an effort, exert the mind, and strive so that bad, unskillful qualities that have arisen are given up.*";
P_HTM[382]="*anuppannānaṃ kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ uppādāya chandaṃ janeti vāyamati vīriyaṃ ārabhati cittaṃ paggaṇhāti padahati;**They generate enthusiasm, try, make an effort, exert the mind, and strive so that skillful qualities arise.*";
P_HTM[383]="*uppannānaṃ kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ ṭhitiyā asammosāya bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya bhāvanāya pāripūriyā chandaṃ janeti vāyamati vīriyaṃ ārabhati cittaṃ paggaṇhāti padahati.**They generate enthusiasm, try, make an effort, exert the mind, and strive so that skillful qualities that have arisen remain, are not lost, but increase, mature, and are fulfilled by development.*";
P_HTM[384]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, cattāri sammappadhānānīti.**These are the four right efforts.*";
P_HTM[385]="*Sammappadhānā māradheyyābhibhūtā,**By rightly striving, they’ve crushed Māra’s sovereignty;*";
P_HTM[386]="*Te asitā jātimaraṇabhayassa pāragū;**unattached, they’ve gone beyond the danger of birth and death.*";
P_HTM[387]="*Te tusitā jetvā māraṃ savāhiniṃ te anejā,**Contented and unstirred, they’ve vanquished Māra and his mount;*";
P_HTM[388]="*Sabbaṃ namucibalaṃ upātivattā te sukhitā”ti.**now they’ve gone beyond all Namuci’s forces, they’re happy.”*";
P_HTM[389]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[390]="*4. Saṃvarasuttaṃ**Restraint*";
P_HTM[391]="*“Cattārimāni, bhikkhave, padhānāni.**“Mendicants, there are these four efforts.*";
P_HTM[392]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[393]="*Saṃvarappadhānaṃ, pahānappadhānaṃ, bhāvanāppadhānaṃ, anurakkhaṇāppadhānaṃ.**The efforts to restrain, to give up, to develop, and to preserve.*";
P_HTM[394]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, saṃvarappadhānaṃ?**And what, mendicants, is the effort to restrain?*";
P_HTM[395]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā na nimittaggāhī hoti nānubyañjanaggāhī.**When a mendicant sees a sight with their eyes, they don’t get caught up in the features and details.*";
P_HTM[396]="*Yatvādhikaraṇamenaṃ cakkhundriyaṃ asaṃvutaṃ viharantaṃ abhijjhādomanassā pāpakā akusalā dhammā anvāssaveyyuṃ, tassa saṃvarāya paṭipajjati, rakkhati cakkhundriyaṃ, cakkhundriye saṃvaraṃ āpajjati.**If the faculty of sight were left unrestrained, bad unskillful qualities of desire and aversion would become overwhelming. For this reason, they practice restraint, protecting the faculty of sight, and achieving its restraint.*";
P_HTM[397]="*Sotena saddaṃ sutvā …**When they hear a sound with their ears …*";
P_HTM[398]="*ghānena gandhaṃ ghāyitvā …**When they smell an odor with their nose …*";
P_HTM[399]="*jivhāya rasaṃ sāyitvā …**When they taste a flavor with their tongue …*";
P_HTM[400]="*kāyena phoṭṭhabbaṃ phusitvā …**When they feel a touch with their body …*";
P_HTM[401]="*manasā dhammaṃ viññāya na nimittaggāhī hoti nānubyañjanaggāhī,**When they know a thought with their mind, they don’t get caught up in the features and details.*";
P_HTM[402]="*yatvādhikaraṇamenaṃ manindriyaṃ asaṃvutaṃ viharantaṃ abhijjhādomanassā pāpakā akusalā dhammā anvāssaveyyuṃ, tassa saṃvarāya paṭipajjati, rakkhati manindriyaṃ, manindriye saṃvaraṃ āpajjati.**If the faculty of mind were left unrestrained, bad unskillful qualities of desire and aversion would become overwhelming. For this reason, they practice restraint, protecting the faculty of mind, and achieving its restraint.*";
P_HTM[403]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, saṃvarappadhānaṃ.**This is called the effort to restrain.*";
P_HTM[404]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, pahānappadhānaṃ?**And what, mendicants, is the effort to give up?*";
P_HTM[405]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu uppannaṃ kāmavitakkaṃ nādhivāseti pajahati vinodeti byantīkaroti anabhāvaṃ gameti; uppannaṃ byāpādavitakkaṃ … pe … uppannaṃ vihiṃsāvitakkaṃ … pe … uppannuppanne pāpake akusale dhamme nādhivāseti pajahati vinodeti byantīkaroti anabhāvaṃ gameti.**It’s when a mendicant doesn’t tolerate a sensual, malicious, or cruel thought that’s arisen, but gives it up, gets rid of it, eliminates it, and obliterates it. They don’t tolerate any bad, unskillful qualities that have arisen, but give them up, get rid of them, eliminate them, and obliterate them.*";
P_HTM[406]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, pahānappadhānaṃ.**This is called the effort to give up.*";
P_HTM[407]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, bhāvanāppadhānaṃ?**And what, mendicants, is the effort to develop?*";
P_HTM[408]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu satisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ, dhammavicayasambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … vīriyasambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … pītisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … passaddhisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … samādhisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … upekkhāsambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ.**It’s when a mendicant develops the awakening factors of mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity, which rely on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripen as letting go.*";
P_HTM[409]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, bhāvanāppadhānaṃ.**This is called the effort to develop.*";
P_HTM[410]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, anurakkhaṇāppadhānaṃ?**And what, mendicants, is the effort to preserve?*";
P_HTM[411]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu uppannaṃ bhaddakaṃ samādhinimittaṃ anurakkhati aṭṭhikasaññaṃ puḷavakasaññaṃ vinīlakasaññaṃ vicchiddakasaññaṃ uddhumātakasaññaṃ.**It’s when a mendicant preserves a meditation subject that’s a fine foundation of immersion: the perception of a skeleton, a worm-infested corpse, a livid corpse, a split open corpse, or a bloated corpse.*";
P_HTM[412]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, anurakkhaṇāppadhānaṃ.**This is called the effort to preserve.*";
P_HTM[413]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, cattāri padhānānīti.**These are the four efforts.*";
P_HTM[414]="*Saṃvaro ca pahānañca,**Restraint and giving up,*";
P_HTM[415]="*bhāvanā anurakkhaṇā;**development and preservation:*";
P_HTM[416]="*Ete padhānā cattāro,**these are the four efforts*";
P_HTM[417]="*desitādiccabandhunā;**taught by the Kinsman of the Sun.*";
P_HTM[418]="*Yehi bhikkhu idhātāpī,**Any mendicant who keenly applies these*";
P_HTM[419]="*khayaṃ dukkhassa pāpuṇe”ti.**may attain the ending of suffering.”*";
P_HTM[420]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[421]="*5. Paññattisuttaṃ**Regarded as Foremost*";
P_HTM[422]="*“Catasso imā, bhikkhave, aggapaññattiyo.**“Mendicants, these four are regarded as foremost.*";
P_HTM[423]="*Katamā catasso?**What four?*";
P_HTM[424]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, attabhāvīnaṃ yadidaṃ—**The foremost in size of life-form is*";
P_HTM[425]="*rāhu asurindo.**Rāhu, lord of demons.*";
P_HTM[426]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, kāmabhogīnaṃ yadidaṃ—**The foremost sensualist is*";
P_HTM[427]="*rājā mandhātā.**King Mandhātā.*";
P_HTM[428]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, ādhipateyyānaṃ yadidaṃ—**The foremost in sovereignty is*";
P_HTM[429]="*māro pāpimā.**Māra the Wicked.*";
P_HTM[430]="*Sadevake, bhikkhave, loke samārake sabrahmake sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya tathāgato aggamakkhāyati arahaṃ sammāsambuddho.**In this world—with its gods, Māras and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, gods and humans—a Realized One, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha is said to be the best.*";
P_HTM[431]="*Imā kho, bhikkhave, catasso aggapaññattiyoti.**These are the four regarded as foremost.*";
P_HTM[432]="*Rāhuggaṃ attabhāvīnaṃ,**Rāhu is foremost in size of life-form,*";
P_HTM[433]="*mandhātā kāmabhoginaṃ;**Mandhātā in enjoying sensual pleasures,*";
P_HTM[434]="*Māro ādhipateyyānaṃ,**Māra in sovereignty,*";
P_HTM[435]="*iddhiyā yasasā jalaṃ.**shining with power and glory.*";
P_HTM[436]="*Uddhaṃ tiriyaṃ apācīnaṃ,**Above, below, and all around,*";
P_HTM[437]="*yāvatājagatogati;**as far as the earth extends;*";
P_HTM[438]="*Sadevakassa lokassa,**in all the world with its gods,*";
P_HTM[439]="*buddho aggo pavuccatī”ti.**the Buddha is declared foremost.”*";
P_HTM[440]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[441]="*6. Sokhummasuttaṃ**Subtlety*";
P_HTM[442]="*“Cattārimāni, bhikkhave, sokhummāni.**“Mendicants, there are these four kinds of subtlety.*";
P_HTM[443]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[444]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu rūpasokhummena samannāgato hoti paramena;**A mendicant has ultimate subtlety of form.*";
P_HTM[445]="*tena ca rūpasokhummena aññaṃ rūpasokhummaṃ uttaritaraṃ vā paṇītataraṃ vā na samanupassati;**They don’t see any other subtlety of form that’s better or finer than that,*";
P_HTM[446]="*tena ca rūpasokhummena aññaṃ rūpasokhummaṃ uttaritaraṃ vā paṇītataraṃ vā na pattheti.**nor do they aim for it.*";
P_HTM[447]="*Vedanāsokhummena samannāgato hoti paramena;**A mendicant has ultimate subtlety of feeling.*";
P_HTM[448]="*tena ca vedanāsokhummena aññaṃ vedanāsokhummaṃ uttaritaraṃ vā paṇītataraṃ vā na samanupassati;**They don’t see any other subtlety of feeling that’s better or finer than that,*";
P_HTM[449]="*tena ca vedanāsokhummena aññaṃ vedanāsokhummaṃ uttaritaraṃ vā paṇītataraṃ vā na pattheti.**nor do they aim for it.*";
P_HTM[450]="*Saññāsokhummena samannāgato hoti paramena;**A mendicant has ultimate subtlety of perception.*";
P_HTM[451]="*tena ca saññāsokhummena aññaṃ saññāsokhummaṃ uttaritaraṃ vā paṇītataraṃ vā na samanupassati;**They don’t see any other subtlety of perception that’s better or finer than that,*";
P_HTM[452]="*tena ca saññāsokhummena aññaṃ saññāsokhummaṃ uttaritaraṃ vā paṇītataraṃ vā na pattheti.**nor do they aim for it.*";
P_HTM[453]="*Saṅkhārasokhummena samannāgato hoti paramena;**A mendicant has ultimate subtlety of choices.*";
P_HTM[454]="*tena ca saṅkhārasokhummena aññaṃ saṅkhārasokhummaṃ uttaritaraṃ vā paṇītataraṃ vā na samanupassati;**They don’t see any other subtlety of choices that’s better or finer than that,*";
P_HTM[455]="*tena ca saṅkhārasokhummena aññaṃ saṅkhārasokhummaṃ uttaritaraṃ vā paṇītataraṃ vā na pattheti.**nor do they aim for it.*";
P_HTM[456]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, cattāri sokhummānīti.**These are the four kinds of subtlety.*";
P_HTM[457]="*Rūpasokhummataṃ ñatvā,**Knowing the subtlety of form,*";
P_HTM[458]="*vedanānañca sambhavaṃ;**the cause of feelings,*";
P_HTM[459]="*Saññā yato samudeti,**where perception comes from,*";
P_HTM[460]="*atthaṃ gacchati yattha ca;**and where it ends;*";
P_HTM[461]="*Saṅkhāre parato ñatvā,**and knowing choices as other,*";
P_HTM[462]="*dukkhato no ca attato.**as suffering and not-self,*";
P_HTM[463]="*Sa ve sammaddaso bhikkhu,**that mendicant sees rightly,*";
P_HTM[464]="*santo santipade rato;**peaceful, in love with the state of peace.*";
P_HTM[465]="*Dhāreti antimaṃ dehaṃ,**They bear their final body,*";
P_HTM[466]="*jetvā māraṃ savāhinin”ti.**having vanquished Māra and his mount.”*";
P_HTM[467]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[468]="*7. Paṭhamaagatisuttaṃ**Prejudice (1st)*";
P_HTM[469]="*“Cattārimāni, bhikkhave, agatigamanāni.**“Mendicants, there are these four ways of making prejudiced decisions.*";
P_HTM[470]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[471]="*Chandāgatiṃ gacchati, dosāgatiṃ gacchati, mohāgatiṃ gacchati, bhayāgatiṃ gacchati—**Making decisions prejudiced by favoritism, hostility, stupidity, and cowardice.*";
P_HTM[472]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, cattāri agatigamanānīti.**These are the four ways of making prejudiced decisions.*";
P_HTM[473]="*Chandā dosā bhayā mohā,**If you act against the teaching*";
P_HTM[474]="*yo dhammaṃ ativattati;**out of favoritism, hostility, cowardice, or stupidity,*";
P_HTM[475]="*Nihīyati tassa yaso,**your fame fades away,*";
P_HTM[476]="*kāḷapakkheva candimā”ti.**like the moon in the waning fortnight.”*";
P_HTM[477]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[478]="*8. Dutiyaagatisuttaṃ**Prejudice (2nd)*";
P_HTM[479]="*“Cattārimāni, bhikkhave, nāgatigamanāni.**“Mendicants, there are these four ways of making unprejudiced decisions.*";
P_HTM[480]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[481]="*Na chandāgatiṃ gacchati, na dosāgatiṃ gacchati, na mohāgatiṃ gacchati, na bhayāgatiṃ gacchati—**Making decisions unprejudiced by favoritism, hostility, stupidity, and cowardice.*";
P_HTM[482]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, cattāri nāgatigamanānīti.**These are the four ways of making unprejudiced decisions.*";
P_HTM[483]="*Chandā dosā bhayā mohā,**If you don’t act against the teaching*";
P_HTM[484]="*yo dhammaṃ nātivattati;**out of favoritism, hostility, cowardice, and stupidity,*";
P_HTM[485]="*Āpūrati tassa yaso,**your fame swells,*";
P_HTM[486]="*sukkapakkheva candimā”ti.**like the moon in the waxing fortnight.”*";
P_HTM[487]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[488]="*9. Tatiyaagatisuttaṃ**Prejudice (3rd)*";
P_HTM[489]="*“Cattārimāni, bhikkhave, agatigamanāni.**“Mendicants, there are these four ways of making prejudiced decisions.*";
P_HTM[490]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[491]="*Chandāgatiṃ gacchati, dosāgatiṃ gacchati, mohāgatiṃ gacchati, bhayāgatiṃ gacchati—**Making decisions prejudiced by favoritism, hostility, stupidity, and cowardice.*";
P_HTM[492]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, cattāri agatigamanāni.**These are the four ways of making prejudiced decisions.*";
P_HTM[493]="*Cattārimāni, bhikkhave, nāgatigamanāni.**There are these four ways of making unprejudiced decisions.*";
P_HTM[494]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[495]="*Na chandāgatiṃ gacchati, na dosāgatiṃ gacchati, na mohāgatiṃ gacchati, na bhayāgatiṃ gacchati—**Making decisions unprejudiced by favoritism, hostility, stupidity, and cowardice.*";
P_HTM[496]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, cattāri nāgatigamanānīti.**These are the four ways of making unprejudiced decisions.*";
P_HTM[497]="*Chandā dosā bhayā mohā,**If you act against the teaching*";
P_HTM[498]="*yo dhammaṃ ativattati;**out of favoritism, hostility, cowardice, or stupidity,*";
P_HTM[499]="*Nihīyati tassa yaso,**your fame fades away,*";
P_HTM[500]="*kāḷapakkheva candimā.**like the moon in the waning fortnight.*";
P_HTM[501]="*Chandā dosā bhayā mohā,**If you don’t act against the teaching*";
P_HTM[502]="*yo dhammaṃ nātivattati;**out of favoritism, hostility, cowardice, and stupidity,*";
P_HTM[503]="*Āpūrati tassa yaso,**your fame swells,*";
P_HTM[504]="*sukkapakkheva candimā”ti.**like the moon in the waxing fortnight.”*";
P_HTM[505]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[506]="*10. Bhattuddesakasuttaṃ**A Meal*";
P_HTM[507]="*“Catūhi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato bhattuddesako yathābhataṃ nikkhitto evaṃ niraye.**“Mendicants, a meal-allocator who has four qualities is cast down to hell.*";
P_HTM[508]="*Katamehi catūhi?**What four?*";
P_HTM[509]="*Chandāgatiṃ gacchati, dosāgatiṃ gacchati, mohāgatiṃ gacchati, bhayāgatiṃ gacchati—**They make decisions prejudiced by favoritism, hostility, stupidity, and cowardice.*";
P_HTM[510]="*imehi kho, bhikkhave, catūhi dhammehi samannāgato bhattuddesako yathābhataṃ nikkhitto evaṃ niraye.**A meal-allocator who has these four qualities is cast down to hell.*";
P_HTM[511]="*Catūhi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato bhattuddesako yathābhataṃ nikkhitto evaṃ sagge.**A meal-allocator who has four qualities is raised up to heaven.*";
P_HTM[512]="*Katamehi catūhi?**What four?*";
P_HTM[513]="*Na chandāgatiṃ gacchati, na dosāgatiṃ gacchati, na mohāgatiṃ gacchati, na bhayāgatiṃ gacchati—**They make decisions unprejudiced by favoritism, hostility, stupidity, and cowardice.*";
P_HTM[514]="*imehi kho, bhikkhave, catūhi dhammehi samannāgato bhattuddesako yathābhataṃ nikkhitto evaṃ saggeti.**A meal-allocator who has these four qualities is raised up to heaven.*";
P_HTM[515]="*Ye keci kāmesu asaññatā janā,**All those people with uncontrolled sensuality,*";
P_HTM[516]="*Adhammikā honti adhammagāravā;**unprincipled, with no respect for principle,*";
P_HTM[517]="*Chandā dosā mohā ca bhayā gāmino,**led astray by favoritism, hatred, stupidity, or cowardice,*";
P_HTM[518]="*Parisākasaṭo ca panesa vuccati.**are called ‘an assembly of the dregs’:*";
P_HTM[519]="*Evañhi vuttaṃ samaṇena jānatā,**that’s what was said by the ascetic who knows.*";
P_HTM[520]="*Tasmā hi te sappurisā pasaṃsiyā;**And so those good, praiseworthy people,*";
P_HTM[521]="*Dhamme ṭhitā ye na karonti pāpakaṃ,**standing on principle, doing nothing wrong,*";
P_HTM[522]="*Na chandā na dosā na mohā na bhayā ca gāmino;**not led astray by favoritism, hatred, stupidity, or cowardice,*";
P_HTM[523]="*Parisāya maṇḍo ca panesa vuccati,**are called ‘an assembly of the cream’:*";
P_HTM[524]="*Evañhi vuttaṃ samaṇena jānatā”ti.**that’s what was said by the ascetic who knows.”*";
P_HTM[525]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[526]="*Caravaggo dutiyo.* **";
P_HTM[527]="*Caraṃ sīlaṃ padhānāni,* **";
P_HTM[528]="*saṃvaraṃ paññatti pañcamaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[529]="*Sokhummaṃ tayo agatī,* **";
P_HTM[530]="*bhattuddesena te dasāti.* **";
P_HTM[531]="*4. Catutthapaṇṇāsakaṃ**At Uruvelā*";
P_HTM[532]="*1. Paṭhamauruvelasuttaṃ**At Uruvelā (1st)*";
P_HTM[533]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[534]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[535]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[536]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[537]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[538]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[539]="*“Ekamidāhaṃ, bhikkhave, samayaṃ uruvelāyaṃ viharāmi najjā nerañjarāya tīre ajapālanigrodhe paṭhamābhisambuddho.**“Mendicants, this one time, when I was first awakened, I was staying near Uruvelā at the goatherd’s banyan tree on the bank of the Nerañjarā River.*";
P_HTM[540]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhikkhave, rahogatassa paṭisallīnassa evaṃ cetaso parivitakko udapādi:**As I was in private retreat this thought came to mind:*";
P_HTM[541]="*‘dukkhaṃ kho agāravo viharati appatisso.**‘One without respect and reverence lives in suffering.*";
P_HTM[542]="*Kiṃ nu kho ahaṃ samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā sakkatvā garuṃ katvā upanissāya vihareyyan’ti?**What ascetic or brahmin should I honor and respect and rely on?’*";
P_HTM[543]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhikkhave, etadahosi:**Then it occurred to me:*";
P_HTM[544]="*‘aparipūrassa kho ahaṃ sīlakkhandhassa pāripūriyā aññaṃ samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā sakkatvā garuṃ katvā upanissāya vihareyyaṃ.**‘I would honor and respect and rely on another ascetic or brahmin so as to complete the full spectrum of ethics, if it were incomplete.*";
P_HTM[545]="*Na kho panāhaṃ passāmi sadevake loke samārake sabrahmake sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya aññaṃ samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā attanā sīlasampannataraṃ, yamahaṃ sakkatvā garuṃ katvā upanissāya vihareyyaṃ.**But I don’t see any other ascetic or brahmin in this world—with its gods, Māras, and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, its gods and humans—who is more accomplished than myself in ethics, who I should honor and respect and rely on.*";
P_HTM[546]="*Aparipūrassa kho ahaṃ samādhikkhandhassa pāripūriyā aññaṃ samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā sakkatvā garuṃ katvā upanissāya vihareyyaṃ.**I would honor and respect and rely on another ascetic or brahmin so as to complete the full spectrum of immersion, if it were incomplete.*";
P_HTM[547]="*Na kho panāhaṃ passāmi sadevake loke samārake sabrahmake sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya aññaṃ samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā attanā samādhisampannataraṃ, yamahaṃ sakkatvā garuṃ katvā upanissāya vihareyyaṃ.**But I don’t see any other ascetic or brahmin … who is more accomplished than myself in immersion …*";
P_HTM[548]="*Aparipūrassa kho ahaṃ paññākkhandhassa pāripūriyā aññaṃ samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā sakkatvā garuṃ katvā upanissāya vihareyyaṃ.**I would honor and respect and rely on another ascetic or brahmin so as to complete the full spectrum of wisdom, if it were incomplete.*";
P_HTM[549]="*Na kho panāhaṃ passāmi sadevake loke samārake sabrahmake sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya aññaṃ samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā attanā paññāsampannataraṃ, yamahaṃ sakkatvā garuṃ katvā upanissāya vihareyyaṃ.**But I don’t see any other ascetic or brahmin in this world … who is more accomplished than myself in wisdom …*";
P_HTM[550]="*Aparipūrassa kho ahaṃ vimuttikkhandhassa pāripūriyā aññaṃ samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā sakkatvā garuṃ katvā upanissāya vihareyyaṃ.**I would honor and respect and rely on another ascetic or brahmin so as to complete the full spectrum of freedom, if it were incomplete.*";
P_HTM[551]="*Na kho panāhaṃ passāmi sadevake loke samārake sabrahmake sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya aññaṃ samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā attanā vimuttisampannataraṃ, yamahaṃ sakkatvā garuṃ katvā upanissāya vihareyyan’ti.**But I don’t see any other ascetic or brahmin in this world … who is more accomplished than myself in freedom …’*";
P_HTM[552]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhikkhave, etadahosi:**Then it occurred to me:*";
P_HTM[553]="*‘yannūnāhaṃ yvāyaṃ dhammo mayā abhisambuddho tameva dhammaṃ sakkatvā garuṃ katvā upanissāya vihareyyan’ti.**‘Why don’t I honor and respect and rely on the same teaching to which I was awakened?’*";
P_HTM[554]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, brahmā sahampati mama cetasā cetoparivitakkamaññāya—seyyathāpi nāma balavā puriso samiñjitaṃ vā bāhaṃ pasāreyya, pasāritaṃ vā bāhaṃ samiñjeyya; evamevaṃ—brahmaloke antarahito mama purato pāturahosi.**And then Brahmā Sahampati, knowing what I was thinking, vanished from the Brahmā realm and appeared in front of me, as easily as a strong man would extend or contract his arm.*";
P_HTM[555]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, brahmā sahampati ekaṃsaṃ uttarāsaṅgaṃ karitvā dakkhiṇaṃ jāṇumaṇḍalaṃ pathaviyaṃ nihantvā yenāhaṃ tenañjaliṃ paṇāmetvā maṃ etadavoca:**He arranged his robe over one shoulder, knelt on his right knee, raised his joined palms toward me, and said:*";
P_HTM[556]="*‘evametaṃ, bhagavā, evametaṃ, sugata.**‘That’s so true, Blessed One! That’s so true, Holy One!*";
P_HTM[557]="*Yepi te, bhante, ahesuṃ atītamaddhānaṃ arahanto sammāsambuddhā tepi bhagavanto dhammaṃyeva sakkatvā garuṃ katvā upanissāya vihariṃsu;**All the perfected ones, the fully awakened Buddhas who lived in the past honored and respected and relied on this same teaching.*";
P_HTM[558]="*yepi te, bhante, bhavissanti anāgatamaddhānaṃ arahanto sammāsambuddhā tepi bhagavanto dhammaṃyeva sakkatvā garuṃ katvā upanissāya viharissanti;**All the perfected ones, the fully awakened Buddhas who will live in the future will honor and respect and rely on this same teaching.*";
P_HTM[559]="*bhagavāpi, bhante, etarahi arahaṃ sammāsambuddho dhammaṃyeva sakkatvā garuṃ katvā upanissāya viharatū’ti.**May the Blessed One, who is the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha at present, also honor and respect and rely on this same teaching.’*";
P_HTM[560]="*Idamavoca brahmā sahampati.**That’s what Brahmā Sahampati said,*";
P_HTM[561]="*Idaṃ vatvā athāparaṃ etadavoca:**Then he went on to say:*";
P_HTM[562]="*‘Ye ca atītā sambuddhā,**‘All Buddhas, whether in the past,*";
P_HTM[563]="*ye ca buddhā anāgatā;**the Buddhas of the future,*";
P_HTM[564]="*Yo cetarahi sambuddho,**and the Buddha at present—*";
P_HTM[565]="*bahūnaṃ sokanāsano.**destroyer of the sorrows of many—*";
P_HTM[566]="*Sabbe saddhammagaruno,**respecting the true teaching*";
P_HTM[567]="*vihaṃsu viharanti ca;**they did live, they do live,*";
P_HTM[568]="*Athopi viharissanti,**and they also will live.*";
P_HTM[569]="*esā buddhāna dhammatā.**This is the nature of the Buddhas.*";
P_HTM[570]="*Tasmā hi attakāmena,**Therefore someone who loves themselves,*";
P_HTM[571]="*mahattamabhikaṅkhatā;**aspiring to transcendence,*";
P_HTM[572]="*Saddhammo garukātabbo,**should respect the true teaching,*";
P_HTM[573]="*saraṃ buddhāna sāsanan’ti.**remembering the instructions of the Buddhas.’*";
P_HTM[574]="*Idamavoca, bhikkhave, brahmā sahampati.**That’s what Brahmā Sahampati said.*";
P_HTM[575]="*Idaṃ vatvā maṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā tatthevantaradhāyi.**Then he bowed and respectfully circled me, keeping me on his right side, before vanishing right there.*";
P_HTM[576]="*Atha khvāhaṃ, bhikkhave, brahmuno ca ajjhesanaṃ viditvā attano ca patirūpaṃ yvāyaṃ dhammo mayā abhisambuddho tameva dhammaṃ sakkatvā garuṃ katvā upanissāya vihāsiṃ.**Then, knowing the request of Brahmā and what was suitable for myself, I honored and respected and relied on the same teaching to which I was awakened.*";
P_HTM[577]="*Yato ca kho, bhikkhave, saṃghopi mahattena samannāgato, atha me saṃghepi gāravo”ti.**And since the Saṅgha has also achieved greatness, I also respect the Saṅgha.”*";
P_HTM[578]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[579]="*2. Dutiyauruvelasuttaṃ**At Uruvelā (2nd)*";
P_HTM[580]="*“Ekamidāhaṃ, bhikkhave, samayaṃ uruvelāyaṃ viharāmi najjā nerañjarāya tīre ajapālanigrodhe paṭhamābhisambuddho.**“Mendicants, this one time, when I was first awakened, I was staying near Uruvelā at the goatherd’s banyan tree on the bank of the Nerañjarā River.*";
P_HTM[581]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, sambahulā brāhmaṇā jiṇṇā vuddhā mahallakā addhagatā vayoanuppattā yenāhaṃ tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā mayā saddhiṃ sammodiṃsu.**Then several old brahmins—elderly and senior, who were advanced in years and had reached the final stage of life—came up to me, and exchanged greetings with me.*";
P_HTM[582]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho, bhikkhave, te brāhmaṇā maṃ etadavocuṃ:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, they sat down to one side, and said to me:*";
P_HTM[583]="*‘sutaṃ netaṃ, bho gotama:**‘Master Gotama, we have heard this:*";
P_HTM[584]="*“na samaṇo gotamo brāhmaṇe jiṇṇe vuddhe mahallake addhagate vayoanuppatte abhivādeti vā paccuṭṭheti vā āsanena vā nimantetī”ti.**“The ascetic Gotama does not bow to old brahmins, elderly and senior, who are advanced in years and have reached the final stage of life; nor does he rise in their presence or offer them a seat.”*";
P_HTM[585]="*Tayidaṃ, bho gotama, tatheva.**And this is indeed the case,*";
P_HTM[586]="*Na hi bhavaṃ gotamo brāhmaṇe jiṇṇe vuddhe mahallake addhagate vayoanuppatte abhivādeti vā paccuṭṭheti vā āsanena vā nimanteti.**for Master Gotama does not bow to old brahmins, elderly and senior, who are advanced in years and have reached the final stage of life; nor does he rise in their presence or offer them a seat.*";
P_HTM[587]="*Tayidaṃ, bho gotama, na sampannamevā’ti.**This is not appropriate, Master Gotama.’*";
P_HTM[588]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhikkhave, etadahosi:**Then it occurred to me,*";
P_HTM[589]="*‘nayime āyasmanto jānanti theraṃ vā therakaraṇe vā dhamme’ti.**‘These venerables don’t know what a senior is, or what qualities make you a senior.’*";
P_HTM[590]="*Vuddho cepi, bhikkhave, hoti āsītiko vā nāvutiko vā vassasatiko vā jātiyā.**Mendicants, suppose you’re eighty, ninety, or a hundred years old.*";
P_HTM[591]="*So ca hoti akālavādī abhūtavādī anatthavādī adhammavādī avinayavādī, anidhānavatiṃ vācaṃ bhāsitā akālena anapadesaṃ apariyantavatiṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ.**But your speech is untimely, false, meaningless, and against the teaching or training. You say things at the wrong time which are worthless, unreasonable, rambling, and unbeneficial.*";
P_HTM[592]="*Atha kho so ‘bālo thero’tveva saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**Then you’ll be considered a ‘childish senior’.*";
P_HTM[593]="*Daharo cepi, bhikkhave, hoti yuvā susukāḷakeso bhadrena yobbanena samannāgato paṭhamena vayasā.**Now suppose you’re a youth, young, black-haired, blessed with youth, in the prime of life.*";
P_HTM[594]="*So ca hoti kālavādī bhūtavādī atthavādī dhammavādī vinayavādī nidhānavatiṃ vācaṃ bhāsitā kālena sāpadesaṃ pariyantavatiṃ atthasaṃhitaṃ.**But your speech is timely, true, meaningful, and in line with the teaching and training. You say things at the right time which are valuable, reasonable, succinct, and beneficial.*";
P_HTM[595]="*Atha kho so ‘paṇḍito thero’tveva saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**Then you’ll be considered an ‘astute senior’.*";
P_HTM[596]="*Cattārome, bhikkhave, therakaraṇā dhammā.**There are these four qualities that make a senior.*";
P_HTM[597]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[598]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sīlavā hoti, pātimokkhasaṃvarasaṃvuto viharati ācāragocarasampanno aṇumattesu vajjesu bhayadassāvī, samādāya sikkhati sikkhāpadesu**A mendicant is ethical, restrained in the monastic code, conducting themselves well and seeking alms in suitable places. Seeing danger in the slightest fault, they keep the rules they’ve undertaken.*";
P_HTM[599]="*Bahussuto hoti sutadharo sutasannicayo, ye te dhammā ādikalyāṇā majjhekalyāṇā pariyosānakalyāṇā sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ abhivadanti, tathārūpāssa dhammā bahussutā honti dhātā vacasā paricitā manasānupekkhitā, diṭṭhiyā suppaṭividdhā.**They’re very learned, remembering and keeping what they’ve learned. These teachings are good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, meaningful and well-phrased, describing a spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure. They are very learned in such teachings, remembering them, reinforcing them by recitation, mentally scrutinizing them, and comprehending them theoretically.*";
P_HTM[600]="*Catunnaṃ jhānānaṃ ābhicetasikānaṃ diṭṭhadhammasukhavihārānaṃ nikāmalābhī hoti akicchalābhī akasiralābhī.**They get the four absorptions—blissful meditations in the present life that belong to the higher mind—when they want, without trouble or difficulty.*";
P_HTM[601]="*Āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati.**They realize the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life. And they live having realized it with their own insight due to the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[602]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro therakaraṇā dhammāti.**These are the four qualities that make a senior.*";
P_HTM[603]="*Yo uddhatena cittena,**The creature with a restless mind*";
P_HTM[604]="*samphañca bahu bhāsati;**speaks a lot of nonsense.*";
P_HTM[605]="*Asamāhitasaṅkappo,**Their thoughts are unsettled,*";
P_HTM[606]="*asaddhammarato mago;**and they don’t like the true teaching.*";
P_HTM[607]="*Ārā so thāvareyyamhā,**They’re far from seniority, with their bad views*";
P_HTM[608]="*pāpadiṭṭhi anādaro.**and their lack of regard for others.*";
P_HTM[609]="*Yo ca sīlena sampanno,**But one accomplished in ethics,*";
P_HTM[610]="*sutavā paṭibhānavā;**learned and eloquent, that wise one*";
P_HTM[611]="*Saññato dhīro dhammesu,**is restrained when experiencing phenomena,*";
P_HTM[612]="*paññāyatthaṃ vipassati.**discerning the meaning with wisdom.*";
P_HTM[613]="*Pāragū sabbadhammānaṃ,**Gone beyond all things,*";
P_HTM[614]="*akhilo paṭibhānavā;**kind, eloquent,*";
P_HTM[615]="*Pahīnajātimaraṇo,**they’ve given up birth and death,*";
P_HTM[616]="*brahmacariyassa kevalī.**and have completed the spiritual journey.*";
P_HTM[617]="*Tamahaṃ vadāmi theroti,**That’s who I call a senior,*";
P_HTM[618]="*yassa no santi āsavā;**who has no defilements.*";
P_HTM[619]="*Āsavānaṃ khayā bhikkhu,**With the ending of defilements, a mendicant*";
P_HTM[620]="*so theroti pavuccatī”ti.**is declared a ‘senior’.”*";
P_HTM[621]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[622]="*3. Lokasuttaṃ**The World*";
P_HTM[623]="*“Loko, bhikkhave, tathāgatena abhisambuddho.**“Mendicants, the world has been understood by a Realized One;*";
P_HTM[624]="*Lokasmā tathāgato visaṃyutto.**and he is detached from the world.*";
P_HTM[625]="*Lokasamudayo, bhikkhave, tathāgatena abhisambuddho.**The origin of the world has been understood by a Realized One;*";
P_HTM[626]="*Lokasamudayo tathāgatassa pahīno.**and he has given up the origin of the world.*";
P_HTM[627]="*Lokanirodho, bhikkhave, tathāgatena abhisambuddho.**The cessation of the world has been understood by a Realized One;*";
P_HTM[628]="*Lokanirodho tathāgatassa sacchikato.**and he has realized the cessation of the world.*";
P_HTM[629]="*Lokanirodhagāminī paṭipadā, bhikkhave, tathāgatena abhisambuddhā.**The practice that leads to the cessation of the world has been understood by a Realized One;*";
P_HTM[630]="*Lokanirodhagāminī paṭipadā tathāgatassa bhāvitā.**and he has developed the practice that leads to the cessation of the world.*";
P_HTM[631]="*Yaṃ, bhikkhave, sadevakassa lokassa samārakassa sabrahmakassa sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya diṭṭhaṃ sutaṃ mutaṃ viññātaṃ pattaṃ pariyesitaṃ anuvicaritaṃ manasā, sabbaṃ taṃ tathāgatena abhisambuddhaṃ.**In this world—with its gods, Māras, and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, its gods and humans—whatever is seen, heard, thought, known, sought, and explored by the mind, all that has been understood by a Realized One.*";
P_HTM[632]="*Tasmā ‘tathāgato’ti vuccati.**That’s why he’s called the ‘Realized One’.*";
P_HTM[633]="*Yañca, bhikkhave, rattiṃ tathāgato anuttaraṃ sammāsambodhiṃ abhisambujjhati yañca rattiṃ anupādisesāya nibbānadhātuyā parinibbāyati, yaṃ etasmiṃ antare bhāsati lapati niddisati sabbaṃ taṃ tatheva hoti, no aññathā.**From the night when a Realized One understands the supreme perfect awakening until the night he becomes fully extinguished—through the natural principle of extinguishment, without anything left over—everything he speaks, says, and expresses is real, not otherwise.*";
P_HTM[634]="*Tasmā ‘tathāgato’ti vuccati.**That’s why he’s called the ‘Realized One’.*";
P_HTM[635]="*Yathāvādī, bhikkhave, tathāgato tathākārī, yathākārī tathāvādī.**The Realized One does as he says, and says as he does.*";
P_HTM[636]="*Iti yathāvādī tathākārī, yathākārī tathāvādī.**Since this is so,*";
P_HTM[637]="*Tasmā ‘tathāgato’ti vuccati.**that’s why he’s called the ‘Realized One’.*";
P_HTM[638]="*Sadevake, bhikkhave, loke samārake sabrahmake sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya tathāgato abhibhū anabhibhūto aññadatthu daso vasavattī.**In this world—with its gods, Māras and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, gods and humans—the Realized One is the undefeated, the champion, the universal seer, the wielder of power.*";
P_HTM[639]="*Tasmā ‘tathāgato’ti vuccati.**That’s why he’s called the ‘Realized One’.*";
P_HTM[640]="*Sabbaṃ lokaṃ abhiññāya,**Directly knowing the whole world as it is,*";
P_HTM[641]="*sabbaṃ loke yathātathaṃ;**and everything in it,*";
P_HTM[642]="*Sabbaṃ lokaṃ visaṃyutto,**he is detached from the whole world,*";
P_HTM[643]="*sabbaloke anūpayo.**disengaged from the whole world.*";
P_HTM[644]="*Sa ve sabbābhibhū dhīro,**That wise one is the champion*";
P_HTM[645]="*sabbaganthappamocano;**who has escaped all ties.*";
P_HTM[646]="*Phuṭṭha’ssa paramā santi,**He has reached ultimate peace:*";
P_HTM[647]="*nibbānaṃ akutobhayaṃ.**extinguishment, fearing nothing from any quarter.*";
P_HTM[648]="*Esa khīṇāsavo buddho,**He is the Buddha, with defilements ended,*";
P_HTM[649]="*anīgho chinnasaṃsayo;**untroubled, with doubts cut off.*";
P_HTM[650]="*Sabbakammakkhayaṃ patto,**He has attained the end of all karma,*";
P_HTM[651]="*vimutto upadhisaṅkhaye.**freed with the end of attachments.*";
P_HTM[652]="*Esa so bhagavā buddho,**That Blessed One is the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[653]="*esa sīho anuttaro;**he is the supreme lion,*";
P_HTM[654]="*Sadevakassa lokassa,**in all the world with its gods,*";
P_HTM[655]="*brahmacakkaṃ pavattayī.**he turns the holy wheel.*";
P_HTM[656]="*Iti devā manussā ca,**And so those gods and humans,*";
P_HTM[657]="*ye buddhaṃ saraṇaṃ gatā;**who have gone to the Buddha for refuge,*";
P_HTM[658]="*Saṅgamma taṃ namassanti,**come together and revere him,*";
P_HTM[659]="*mahantaṃ vītasāradaṃ.**the great one, rid of naivety:*";
P_HTM[660]="*Danto damayataṃ seṭṭho,**‘Tamed, he is the best of tamers,*";
P_HTM[661]="*santo samayataṃ isi;**peaceful, he is the hermit among the peaceful,*";
P_HTM[662]="*Mutto mocayataṃ aggo,**liberated, he is the foremost of liberators,*";
P_HTM[663]="*tiṇṇo tārayataṃ varo.**crossed over, he is the most excellent of guides across.’*";
P_HTM[664]="*Iti hetaṃ namassanti,**And so they revere him,*";
P_HTM[665]="*mahantaṃ vītasāradaṃ;**the great one, rid of naivety.*";
P_HTM[666]="*Sadevakasmiṃ lokasmiṃ,**In the world with its gods,*";
P_HTM[667]="*natthi me paṭipuggalo”ti.**he has no counterpart.”*";
P_HTM[668]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[669]="*4. Kāḷakārāmasuttaṃ**At Kāḷaka’s Monastery*";
P_HTM[670]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sākete viharati kāḷakārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāketa, in Kāḷaka’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[671]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[672]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[673]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[674]="*Bhagavā etadavoca—**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[675]="*Yaṃ, bhikkhave, sadevakassa lokassa samārakassa sabrahmakassa sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya diṭṭhaṃ sutaṃ mutaṃ viññātaṃ pattaṃ pariyesitaṃ anuvicaritaṃ manasā, tamahaṃ jānāmi.**“In this world—with its gods, Māras and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, its gods and humans—whatever is seen, heard, thought, known, sought, and explored by the mind: that I know.*";
P_HTM[676]="*Yaṃ, bhikkhave, sadevakassa lokassa samārakassa sabrahmakassa sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya diṭṭhaṃ sutaṃ mutaṃ viññātaṃ pattaṃ pariyesitaṃ anuvicaritaṃ manasā, tamahaṃ abbhaññāsiṃ.**In this world—with its gods, Māras, and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, its gods and humans—whatever is seen, heard, thought, known, sought, and explored by the mind: that I have insight into.*";
P_HTM[677]="*Taṃ tathāgatassa viditaṃ, taṃ tathāgato na upaṭṭhāsi.**That has been known by a Realized One, but a Realized One is not subject to it.*";
P_HTM[678]="*Yaṃ, bhikkhave, sadevakassa lokassa samārakassa sabrahmakassa sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya diṭṭhaṃ sutaṃ mutaṃ viññātaṃ pattaṃ pariyesitaṃ anuvicaritaṃ manasā, tamahaṃ na jānāmīti vadeyyaṃ, taṃ mamassa musā.**If I were to say that ‘I do not know … the world with its gods’, I would be lying.*";
P_HTM[679]="*Yaṃ, bhikkhave … pe … tamahaṃ jānāmi ca na ca jānāmīti vadeyyaṃ, tampassa tādisameva.**If I were to say that ‘I both know and do not know … the world with its gods’, that would be just the same.*";
P_HTM[680]="*Yaṃ, bhikkhave … pe … tamahaṃ neva jānāmi na na jānāmīti vadeyyaṃ, taṃ mamassa kali.**If I were to say that ‘I neither know nor do not know … the world with its gods’, that would be my fault.*";
P_HTM[681]="*Iti kho, bhikkhave, tathāgato daṭṭhā daṭṭhabbaṃ, diṭṭhaṃ na maññati, adiṭṭhaṃ na maññati, daṭṭhabbaṃ na maññati, daṭṭhāraṃ na maññati;**So a Realized One sees what is to be seen, but does not identify with what is seen, does not identify with what is unseen, does not identify with what is to be seen, and does not identify with a seer.*";
P_HTM[682]="*sutvā sotabbaṃ, sutaṃ na maññati, asutaṃ na maññati, sotabbaṃ na maññati, sotāraṃ na maññati;**He hears what is to be heard, but does not identify with what is heard, does not identify with what is unheard, does not identify with what is to be heard, and does not identify with a hearer.*";
P_HTM[683]="*mutvā motabbaṃ, mutaṃ na maññati, amutaṃ na maññati, motabbaṃ na maññati, motāraṃ na maññati;**He thinks what is to be thought, but does not identify with what is thought, does not identify with what is not thought, does not identify with what is to be thought, and does not identify with a thinker.*";
P_HTM[684]="*viññatvā viññātabbaṃ, viññātaṃ na maññati, aviññātaṃ na maññati, viññātabbaṃ na maññati, viññātāraṃ na maññati.**He knows what is to be known, but does not identify with what is known, does not identify with what is unknown, does not identify with what is to be known, and does not identify with a knower.*";
P_HTM[685]="*Iti kho, bhikkhave, tathāgato diṭṭhasutamutaviññātabbesu dhammesu tādīyeva tādī.**Since a Realized One is poised in the midst of things seen, heard, thought, and known, he is the poised one.*";
P_HTM[686]="*‘Tamhā ca pana tādimhā añño tādī uttaritaro vā paṇītataro vā natthī’ti vadāmīti.**And I say that there is no-one who has better or finer poise than this.*";
P_HTM[687]="*Yaṃ kiñci diṭṭhaṃva sutaṃ mutaṃ vā,**The poised one does not take anything*";
P_HTM[688]="*Ajjhositaṃ saccamutaṃ paresaṃ;**seen, heard, or thought to be ultimately true or false.*";
P_HTM[689]="*Na tesu tādī sayasaṃvutesu,**But others get attached, thinking it’s the truth,*";
P_HTM[690]="*Saccaṃ musā vāpi paraṃ daheyya.**limited by their preconceptions.*";
P_HTM[691]="*Etañca sallaṃ paṭikacca disvā,**Since they’ve already seen this dart,*";
P_HTM[692]="*Ajjhositā yattha pajā visattā;**to which people are attached and cling,*";
P_HTM[693]="*Jānāmi passāmi tatheva etaṃ,**they say, ‘I know, I see, that’s how it is’;*";
P_HTM[694]="*Ajjhositaṃ natthi tathāgatānan”ti.**the Realized Ones have no attachments.”*";
P_HTM[695]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[696]="*5. Brahmacariyasuttaṃ**The Spiritual Life*";
P_HTM[697]="*“Nayidaṃ, bhikkhave, brahmacariyaṃ vussati janakuhanatthaṃ, na janalapanatthaṃ, na lābhasakkārasilokānisaṃsatthaṃ, na itivādappamokkhānisaṃsatthaṃ, na ‘iti maṃ jano jānātū’ti.**“Mendicants, this spiritual life is not lived for the sake of deceiving people or flattering them, nor for the benefit of possessions, honor, or popularity, nor for the benefit of winning debates, nor thinking, ‘So let people know about me!’*";
P_HTM[698]="*Atha kho idaṃ, bhikkhave, brahmacariyaṃ vussati saṃvaratthaṃ pahānatthaṃ virāgatthaṃ nirodhatthanti.**This spiritual life is lived for the sake of restraint, giving up, fading away, and cessation.*";
P_HTM[699]="*Saṃvaratthaṃ pahānatthaṃ,**The Buddha taught the spiritual life*";
P_HTM[700]="*brahmacariyaṃ anītihaṃ;**not because of tradition,*";
P_HTM[701]="*Adesayi so bhagavā,**but for the sake of restraint and giving up,*";
P_HTM[702]="*nibbānogadhagāminaṃ;**and because it culminates in extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[703]="*Esa maggo mahantehi,**This is the path followed by the great souls,*";
P_HTM[704]="*anuyāto mahesibhi.**the great hermits.*";
P_HTM[705]="*Ye ca taṃ paṭipajjanti,**Those who practice it*";
P_HTM[706]="*yathā buddhena desitaṃ;**as it was taught by the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[707]="*Dukkhassantaṃ karissanti,**doing the teacher’s bidding,*";
P_HTM[708]="*satthusāsanakārino”ti.**make an end of suffering.”*";
P_HTM[709]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[710]="*6. Kuhasuttaṃ**Deceivers*";
P_HTM[711]="*“Ye te, bhikkhave, bhikkhū kuhā thaddhā lapā siṅgī unnaḷā asamāhitā, na me te, bhikkhave, bhikkhū māmakā.**“Mendicants, those mendicants who are deceivers, stubborn, flatterers, frauds, insolent, and scattered: they are no mendicants of mine.*";
P_HTM[712]="*Apagatā ca te, bhikkhave, bhikkhū imasmā dhammavinayā, na ca te imasmiṃ dhammavinaye vuddhiṃ viruḷhiṃ vepullaṃ āpajjanti.**They’ve left this teaching and training, and they don’t achieve growth, improvement, or maturity in this teaching and training.*";
P_HTM[713]="*Ye ca kho te, bhikkhave, bhikkhū nikkuhā nillapā dhīrā atthaddhā susamāhitā, te kho me, bhikkhave, bhikkhū māmakā.**But those mendicants who are genuine, not flatterers, wise, amenable, and serene: they are mendicants of mine.*";
P_HTM[714]="*Anapagatā ca te, bhikkhave, bhikkhū imasmā dhammavinayā.**They haven’t left this teaching and training,*";
P_HTM[715]="*Te ca imasmiṃ dhammavinaye vuddhiṃ viruḷhiṃ vepullaṃ āpajjantīti.**and they achieve growth, improvement, or maturity in this teaching and training.*";
P_HTM[716]="*Kuhā thaddhā lapā siṅgī,**Those who are deceivers, stubborn, flatterers, and frauds,*";
P_HTM[717]="*unnaḷā asamāhitā;**insolent and scattered:*";
P_HTM[718]="*Na te dhamme virūhanti,**these don’t grow in the teaching*";
P_HTM[719]="*sammāsambuddhadesite.**that was taught by the perfected Buddha.*";
P_HTM[720]="*Nikkuhā nillapā dhīrā,**But those who are genuine, not flatterers, wise,*";
P_HTM[721]="*atthaddhā susamāhitā;**amenable, and serene:*";
P_HTM[722]="*Te ve dhamme virūhanti,**these do grow in the teaching*";
P_HTM[723]="*sammāsambuddhadesite”ti.**that was taught by the perfected Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[724]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[725]="*7. Santuṭṭhisuttaṃ**Contentment*";
P_HTM[726]="*“Cattārimāni, bhikkhave, appāni ca sulabhāni ca, tāni ca anavajjāni.**“Mendicants, these four trifles are easy to get hold of and are blameless.*";
P_HTM[727]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[728]="*Paṃsukūlaṃ, bhikkhave, cīvarānaṃ appañca sulabhañca, tañca anavajjaṃ.**Rag-robes …*";
P_HTM[729]="*Piṇḍiyālopo, bhikkhave, bhojanānaṃ appañca sulabhañca, tañca anavajjaṃ.**A lump of alms-food …*";
P_HTM[730]="*Rukkhamūlaṃ, bhikkhave, senāsanānaṃ appañca sulabhañca, tañca anavajjaṃ.**Lodgings at the root of a tree …*";
P_HTM[731]="*Pūtimuttaṃ, bhikkhave, bhesajjānaṃ appañca sulabhañca, tañca anavajjaṃ.**Fermented urine as medicine …*";
P_HTM[732]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, cattāri appāni ca sulabhāni ca, tāni ca anavajjāni.**These four trifles are easy to get hold of and are blameless.*";
P_HTM[733]="*Yato kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu appena ca tuṭṭho hoti sulabhena ca, idamassāhaṃ aññataraṃ sāmaññaṅganti vadāmīti.**When a mendicant is content with trifles that are easy to get hold of, they have one of the factors of the ascetic life, I say.*";
P_HTM[734]="*Anavajjena tuṭṭhassa,**When you’re content with what’s blameless,*";
P_HTM[735]="*appena sulabhena ca;**trifling, and easy to get hold of,*";
P_HTM[736]="*Na senāsanamārabbha,**you don’t get upset*";
P_HTM[737]="*cīvaraṃ pānabhojanaṃ;**about lodgings, robes,*";
P_HTM[738]="*Vighāto hoti cittassa,**food, and drink,*";
P_HTM[739]="*disā nappaṭihaññati.**and you’re not obstructed anywhere.*";
P_HTM[740]="*Ye cassa dhammā akkhātā,**These qualities are said to be*";
P_HTM[741]="*sāmaññassānulomikā;**integral to the ascetic life.*";
P_HTM[742]="*Adhiggahitā tuṭṭhassa,**They’re acquired by one who trains,*";
P_HTM[743]="*appamattassa sikkhato”ti.**content and diligent.”*";
P_HTM[744]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[745]="*8. Ariyavaṃsasuttaṃ**The Noble Traditions*";
P_HTM[746]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, ariyavaṃsā aggaññā rattaññā vaṃsaññā porāṇā asaṃkiṇṇā asaṃkiṇṇapubbā, na saṅkīyanti na saṅkīyissanti, appaṭikuṭṭhā samaṇehi brāhmaṇehi viññūhi.**“Mendicants, these four noble traditions are original, long-standing, traditional, and ancient. They are uncorrupted, as they have been since the beginning. They’re not being corrupted now, nor will they be. Sensible ascetics and brahmins don’t look down on them.*";
P_HTM[747]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[748]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu santuṭṭho hoti itarītarena cīvarena, itarītaracīvarasantuṭṭhiyā ca vaṇṇavādī, na ca cīvarahetu anesanaṃ appatirūpaṃ āpajjati, aladdhā ca cīvaraṃ na paritassati, laddhā ca cīvaraṃ agadhito amucchito anajjhosanno ādīnavadassāvī nissaraṇapañño paribhuñjati;**Firstly, a mendicant is content with any kind of robe, and praises such contentment. They don’t try to get hold of a robe in an improper way. They don’t get upset if they don’t get a robe. And if they do get a robe, they use it untied, uninfatuated, unattached, seeing the drawback, and understanding the escape.*";
P_HTM[749]="*tāya ca pana itarītaracīvarasantuṭṭhiyā nevattānukkaṃseti, no paraṃ vambheti.**But they don’t glorify themselves or put others down on account of their contentment.*";
P_HTM[750]="*Yo hi tattha dakkho analaso sampajāno patissato, ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, bhikkhu porāṇe aggaññe ariyavaṃse ṭhito.**A mendicant who is deft, tireless, aware, and mindful in this is said to stand in the ancient, original noble tradition.*";
P_HTM[751]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu santuṭṭho hoti itarītarena piṇḍapātena, itarītarapiṇḍapātasantuṭṭhiyā ca vaṇṇavādī, na ca piṇḍapātahetu anesanaṃ appatirūpaṃ āpajjati, aladdhā ca piṇḍapātaṃ na paritassati, laddhā ca piṇḍapātaṃ agadhito amucchito anajjhosanno ādīnavadassāvī nissaraṇapañño paribhuñjati;**Furthermore, a mendicant is content with any kind of alms-food …*";
P_HTM[752]="*tāya ca pana itarītarapiṇḍapātasantuṭṭhiyā nevattānukkaṃseti, no paraṃ vambheti.* **";
P_HTM[753]="*Yo hi tattha dakkho analaso sampajāno patissato, ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, bhikkhu porāṇe aggaññe ariyavaṃse ṭhito.* **";
P_HTM[754]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu santuṭṭho hoti itarītarena senāsanena, itarītarasenāsanasantuṭṭhiyā ca vaṇṇavādī, na ca senāsanahetu anesanaṃ appatirūpaṃ āpajjati, aladdhā ca senāsanaṃ na paritassati, laddhā ca senāsanaṃ agadhito amucchito anajjhosanno ādīnavadassāvī nissaraṇapañño paribhuñjati;**Furthermore, a mendicant is content with any kind of lodgings …*";
P_HTM[755]="*tāya ca pana itarītarasenāsanasantuṭṭhiyā nevattānukkaṃseti, no paraṃ vambheti.* **";
P_HTM[756]="*Yo hi tattha dakkho analaso sampajāno patissato, ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, bhikkhu porāṇe aggaññe ariyavaṃse ṭhito.* **";
P_HTM[757]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu bhāvanārāmo hoti bhāvanārato, pahānārāmo hoti pahānarato;**Furthermore, a mendicant enjoys meditation and loves to meditate. They enjoy giving up and love to give up.*";
P_HTM[758]="*tāya ca pana bhāvanārāmatāya bhāvanāratiyā pahānārāmatāya pahānaratiyā nevattānukkaṃseti, no paraṃ vambheti.**But they don’t glorify themselves or put down others on account of their love for meditation and giving up.*";
P_HTM[759]="*Yo hi tattha dakkho analaso sampajāno patissato, ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, bhikkhu porāṇe aggaññe ariyavaṃse ṭhito.**A mendicant who is deft, tireless, aware, and mindful in this is said to stand in the ancient, original noble tradition.*";
P_HTM[760]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro ariyavaṃsā aggaññā rattaññā vaṃsaññā porāṇā asaṅkiṇṇā asaṅkiṇṇapubbā, na saṅkīyanti na saṅkīyissanti, appaṭikuṭṭhā samaṇehi brāhmaṇehi viññūhi.**These four noble traditions are original, long-standing, traditional, and ancient. They are uncorrupted, as they have been since the beginning. They’re not being corrupted now nor will they be. Sensible ascetics and brahmins don’t look down on them.*";
P_HTM[761]="*Imehi ca pana, bhikkhave, catūhi ariyavaṃsehi samannāgato bhikkhu puratthimāya cepi disāya viharati sveva aratiṃ sahati, na taṃ arati sahati;**When a mendicant has these four noble traditions, if they live in the east they prevail over discontent, and discontent doesn’t prevail over them.*";
P_HTM[762]="*pacchimāya cepi disāya viharati sveva aratiṃ sahati, na taṃ arati sahati;**If they live in the west …*";
P_HTM[763]="*uttarāya cepi disāya viharati sveva aratiṃ sahati, na taṃ arati sahati;**the north …*";
P_HTM[764]="*dakkhiṇāya cepi disāya viharati sveva aratiṃ sahati, na taṃ arati sahati.**the south, they prevail over discontent, and discontent doesn’t prevail over them.*";
P_HTM[765]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[766]="*Aratiratisaho hi, bhikkhave, dhīroti.**Because a wise one prevails over desire and discontent.*";
P_HTM[767]="*Nārati sahati dhīraṃ,**Dissatisfaction doesn’t prevail over a wise one;*";
P_HTM[768]="*nārati dhīraṃ sahati;**for the wise one is not beaten by discontent.*";
P_HTM[769]="*Dhīrova aratiṃ sahati,**A wise one prevails over discontent,*";
P_HTM[770]="*dhīro hi aratissaho.**for the wise one is a beater of discontent.*";
P_HTM[771]="*Sabbakammavihāyīnaṃ,**Who can hold back the dispeller,*";
P_HTM[772]="*panuṇṇaṃ ko nivāraye;**who’s thrown away all karma?*";
P_HTM[773]="*Nekkhaṃ jambonadasseva,**They’re like a coin of mountain gold:*";
P_HTM[774]="*ko taṃ ninditumarahati;**who is worthy of criticizing them?*";
P_HTM[775]="*Devāpi naṃ pasaṃsanti,**Even the gods praise them,*";
P_HTM[776]="*brahmunāpi pasaṃsito”ti.**and by Brahmā, too, they’re praised.”*";
P_HTM[777]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[778]="*9. Dhammapadasuttaṃ**Basic Principles*";
P_HTM[779]="*“Cattārimāni, bhikkhave, dhammapadāni aggaññāni rattaññāni vaṃsaññāni porāṇāni asaṅkiṇṇāni asaṅkiṇṇapubbāni, na saṅkīyanti na saṅkīyissanti, appaṭikuṭṭhāni samaṇehi brāhmaṇehi viññūhi.**“Mendicants, these four basic principles are original, long-standing, traditional, and ancient. They are uncorrupted, as they have been since the beginning. They’re not being corrupted now nor will they be. Sensible ascetics and brahmins don’t look down on them.*";
P_HTM[780]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[781]="*Anabhijjhā, bhikkhave, dhammapadaṃ aggaññaṃ rattaññaṃ vaṃsaññaṃ porāṇaṃ asaṅkiṇṇaṃ asaṅkiṇṇapubbaṃ, na saṅkīyati na saṅkīyissati, appaṭikuṭṭhaṃ samaṇehi brāhmaṇehi viññūhi.**Contentment, good will, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[782]="*Abyāpādo, bhikkhave, dhammapadaṃ aggaññaṃ rattaññaṃ vaṃsaññaṃ porāṇaṃ asaṅkiṇṇaṃ asaṅkiṇṇapubbaṃ, na saṅkīyati na saṅkīyissati, appaṭikuṭṭhaṃ samaṇehi brāhmaṇehi viññūhi.* **";
P_HTM[783]="*Sammāsati, bhikkhave, dhammapadaṃ aggaññaṃ rattaññaṃ vaṃsaññaṃ porāṇaṃ asaṅkiṇṇaṃ asaṅkiṇṇapubbaṃ, na saṅkīyati na saṅkīyissati, appaṭikuṭṭhaṃ samaṇehi brāhmaṇehi viññūhi.* **";
P_HTM[784]="*Sammāsamādhi, bhikkhave, dhammapadaṃ aggaññaṃ rattaññaṃ vaṃsaññaṃ porāṇaṃ asaṅkiṇṇaṃ asaṅkiṇṇapubbaṃ, na saṅkīyati na saṅkīyissati, appaṭikuṭṭhaṃ samaṇehi brāhmaṇehi viññūhi.* **";
P_HTM[785]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, cattāri dhammapadāni aggaññāni rattaññāni vaṃsaññāni porāṇāni asaṅkiṇṇāni asaṅkiṇṇapubbāni, na saṅkīyanti na saṅkīyissanti, appaṭikuṭṭhāni samaṇehi brāhmaṇehi viññūhīti.**These four basic principles are original, long-standing, traditional, and ancient. They are uncorrupted, as they have been since the beginning. They’re not being corrupted now nor will they be. Sensible ascetics and brahmins don’t look down on them.*";
P_HTM[786]="*Anabhijjhālu vihareyya,**You should live with contentment,*";
P_HTM[787]="*abyāpannena cetasā;**and a heart of good will,*";
P_HTM[788]="*Sato ekaggacittassa,**mindful, with unified mind,*";
P_HTM[789]="*ajjhattaṃ susamāhito”ti.**serene within.”*";
P_HTM[790]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[791]="*10. Paribbājakasuttaṃ**Wanderers*";
P_HTM[792]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati gijjhakūṭe pabbate.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha, on the Vulture’s Peak Mountain.*";
P_HTM[793]="*Tena kho pana samayena sambahulā abhiññātā abhiññātā paribbājakā sippinikātīre paribbājakārāme paṭivasanti, seyyathidaṃ annabhāro varadharo sakuludāyī ca paribbājako aññe ca abhiññātā abhiññātā paribbājakā.**Now at that time several very well-known wanderers were residing in the monastery of the wanderers on the bank of the Sappinī river. They included Annabhāra, Varadhara, Sakuludāyī, and other very well-known wanderers.*";
P_HTM[794]="*Atha kho bhagavā sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhito yena sippinikātīraṃ paribbājakārāmo tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi. Nisajja kho bhagavā te paribbājake etadavoca:**Then in the late afternoon, the Buddha came out of retreat and went to the wanderer’s monastery on the banks of the Sappinī river, He sat down on the seat spread out, and said to the wanderers:*";
P_HTM[795]="*“Cattārimāni, paribbājakā, dhammapadāni aggaññāni rattaññāni vaṃsaññāni porāṇāni asaṅkiṇṇāni asaṅkiṇṇapubbāni, na saṅkīyanti na saṅkīyissanti, appaṭikuṭṭhāni samaṇehi brāhmaṇehi viññūhi.**“Wanderers, these four basic principles are original, long-standing, traditional, and ancient. They are uncorrupted, as they have been since the beginning. They’re not being corrupted now nor will they be. Sensible ascetics and brahmins don’t look down on them.*";
P_HTM[796]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[797]="*Anabhijjhā, paribbājakā, dhammapadaṃ aggaññaṃ rattaññaṃ vaṃsaññaṃ porāṇaṃ asaṅkiṇṇaṃ asaṅkiṇṇapubbaṃ, na saṅkīyati na saṅkīyissati, appaṭikuṭṭhaṃ samaṇehi brāhmaṇehi viññūhi.**Contentment …*";
P_HTM[798]="*Abyāpādo, paribbājakā, dhammapadaṃ … pe … sammāsati, paribbājakā, dhammapadaṃ … pe … sammāsamādhi, paribbājakā, dhammapadaṃ aggaññaṃ rattaññaṃ vaṃsaññaṃ porāṇaṃ asaṅkiṇṇaṃ asaṅkiṇṇapubbaṃ, na saṅkīyati na saṅkīyissati, appaṭikuṭṭhaṃ samaṇehi brāhmaṇehi viññūhi.**Good will … Right mindfulness … Right immersion …*";
P_HTM[799]="*Imāni kho, paribbājakā, cattāri dhammapadāni aggaññāni rattaññāni vaṃsaññāni porāṇāni asaṅkiṇṇāni asaṅkiṇṇapubbāni, na saṅkīyanti na saṅkīyissanti, appaṭikuṭṭhāni samaṇehi brāhmaṇehi viññūhi.**These four basic principles are original, long-standing, traditional, and ancient. They are uncorrupted, as they have been since the beginning. They’re not being corrupted now nor will they be. Sensible ascetics and brahmins don’t look down on them.*";
P_HTM[800]="*Yo kho, paribbājakā, evaṃ vadeyya:**Wanderers, if someone should say:*";
P_HTM[801]="*‘ahametaṃ anabhijjhaṃ dhammapadaṃ paccakkhāya abhijjhāluṃ kāmesu tibbasārāgaṃ samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā paññāpessāmī’ti, tamahaṃ tattha evaṃ vadeyyaṃ:**‘I’ll reject this basic principle of contentment, and describe a true ascetic or brahmin who covets sensual pleasures with acute lust.’ Then I’d say to them:*";
P_HTM[802]="*‘etu vadatu byāharatu passāmissānubhāvan’ti.**‘Let them come, speak, and discuss. We’ll see how powerful they are.’*";
P_HTM[803]="*So vata, paribbājakā, anabhijjhaṃ dhammapadaṃ paccakkhāya abhijjhāluṃ kāmesu tibbasārāgaṃ samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā paññāpessatīti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**It’s simply impossible to reject this basic principle of contentment, and point out a true ascetic or brahmin who covets sensual pleasures with acute lust.*";
P_HTM[804]="*Yo kho, paribbājakā, evaṃ vadeyya:**If someone should say:*";
P_HTM[805]="*‘ahametaṃ abyāpādaṃ dhammapadaṃ paccakkhāya byāpannacittaṃ paduṭṭhamanasaṅkappaṃ samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā paññāpessāmī’ti, tamahaṃ tattha evaṃ vadeyyaṃ:**‘I’ll reject this basic principle of good will, and describe a true ascetic or brahmin who has ill will and hateful intent.’ Then I’d say to them:*";
P_HTM[806]="*‘etu vadatu byāharatu passāmissānubhāvan’ti.**‘Let them come, speak, and discuss. We’ll see how powerful they are.’*";
P_HTM[807]="*So vata, paribbājakā, abyāpādaṃ dhammapadaṃ paccakkhāya byāpannacittaṃ paduṭṭhamanasaṅkappaṃ samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā paññāpessatīti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**It’s simply impossible to reject this basic principle of good will, and point out a true ascetic or brahmin who has ill will and hateful intent.*";
P_HTM[808]="*Yo kho, paribbājakā, evaṃ vadeyya:**If someone should say:*";
P_HTM[809]="*‘ahametaṃ sammāsatiṃ dhammapadaṃ paccakkhāya muṭṭhassatiṃ asampajānaṃ samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā paññāpessāmī’ti, tamahaṃ tattha evaṃ vadeyyaṃ:**‘I’ll reject this basic principle of right mindfulness, and describe a true ascetic or brahmin who is unmindful, with no situational awareness.’ Then I’d say to them:*";
P_HTM[810]="*‘etu vadatu byāharatu passāmissānubhāvan’ti.**‘Let them come, speak, and discuss. We’ll see how powerful they are.’*";
P_HTM[811]="*So vata, paribbājakā, sammāsatiṃ dhammapadaṃ paccakkhāya muṭṭhassatiṃ asampajānaṃ samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā paññāpessatīti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**It’s simply impossible to reject this basic principle of right mindfulness, and point out a true ascetic or brahmin who is unmindful, with no situational awareness.*";
P_HTM[812]="*Yo kho, paribbājakā, evaṃ vadeyya:**If someone should say:*";
P_HTM[813]="*‘ahametaṃ sammāsamādhiṃ dhammapadaṃ paccakkhāya asamāhitaṃ vibbhantacittaṃ samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā paññāpessāmī’ti, tamahaṃ tattha evaṃ vadeyyaṃ:**‘I’ll reject this basic principle of right immersion, and describe a true ascetic or brahmin who is scattered, with straying mind.’ Then I’d say to them:*";
P_HTM[814]="*‘etu vadatu byāharatu passāmissānubhāvan’ti.**‘Let them come, speak, and discuss. We’ll see how powerful they are.’*";
P_HTM[815]="*So vata, paribbājakā, sammāsamādhiṃ dhammapadaṃ paccakkhāya asamāhitaṃ vibbhantacittaṃ samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā paññāpessatīti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**It’s simply impossible to reject this basic principle of right immersion, and point out a true ascetic or brahmin who is scattered, with straying mind.*";
P_HTM[816]="*Yo kho, paribbājakā, imāni cattāri dhammapadāni garahitabbaṃ paṭikkositabbaṃ maññeyya, tassa diṭṭheva dhamme cattāro sahadhammikā vādānupātā gārayhā ṭhānā āgacchanti.**If anyone imagines they can criticize and reject these four basic principles, they deserve rebuke and criticism on four legitimate grounds in the present life.*";
P_HTM[817]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[818]="*Anabhijjhañce bhavaṃ dhammapadaṃ garahati paṭikkosati, ye ca hi abhijjhālū kāmesu tibbasārāgā samaṇabrāhmaṇā te bhoto pujjā te bhoto pāsaṃsā.**If you reject the basic principle of contentment, then you must honor and praise those ascetics and brahmins who covet sensual pleasures with acute lust.*";
P_HTM[819]="*Abyāpādañce bhavaṃ dhammapadaṃ garahati paṭikkosati, ye ca hi byāpannacittā paduṭṭhamanasaṅkappā samaṇabrāhmaṇā te bhoto pujjā te bhoto pāsaṃsā.**If you reject the basic principle of good will, you must honor and praise those ascetics and brahmins who have ill will and hateful intent.*";
P_HTM[820]="*Sammāsatiñce bhavaṃ dhammapadaṃ garahati paṭikkosati, ye ca hi muṭṭhassatī asampajānā samaṇabrāhmaṇā te bhoto pujjā te bhoto pāsaṃsā.**If you reject the basic principle of right mindfulness, then you must honor and praise those ascetics and brahmins who are unmindful, with no situational awareness.*";
P_HTM[821]="*Sammāsamādhiñce bhavaṃ dhammapadaṃ garahati paṭikkosati, ye ca hi asamāhitā vibbhantacittā samaṇabrāhmaṇā te bhoto pujjā te bhoto pāsaṃsā.**If you reject the basic principle of right immersion, you must honor and praise those ascetics and brahmins who are scattered, with straying minds.*";
P_HTM[822]="*Yo kho, paribbājakā, imāni cattāri dhammapadāni garahitabbaṃ paṭikkositabbaṃ maññeyya, tassa diṭṭheva dhamme ime cattāro sahadhammikā vādānupātā gārayhā ṭhānā āgacchanti.**If anyone imagines they can criticize and reject these four basic principles, they deserve rebuke and criticism on four legitimate grounds in the present life.*";
P_HTM[823]="*Yepi te paribbājakā ahesuṃ ukkalā vassabhaññā ahetukavādā akiriyavādā natthikavādā, tepi imāni cattāri dhammapadāni na garahitabbaṃ na paṭikkositabbaṃ amaññiṃsu.**Even those wanderers of the past, Vassa and Bhañña of Ukkalā, who taught the doctrines of no-cause, inaction, and nihilism, didn’t imagine that these four basic principles should be criticized or rejected.*";
P_HTM[824]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[825]="*Nindābyārosanaupārambhabhayāti.**For fear of being blamed, criticized, and faulted.*";
P_HTM[826]="*Abyāpanno sadā sato,**One who has good will, ever mindful,*";
P_HTM[827]="*ajjhattaṃ susamāhito;**serene within,*";
P_HTM[828]="*Abhijjhāvinaye sikkhaṃ,**training to remove desire,*";
P_HTM[829]="*appamattoti vuccatī”ti.**is called ‘a diligent one’.”*";
P_HTM[830]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[831]="*Uruvelavaggo tatiyo.* **";
P_HTM[832]="*Dve uruvelā loko kāḷako,* **";
P_HTM[833]="*Brahmacariyena pañcamaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[834]="*Kuhaṃ santuṭṭhi vaṃso ca,* **";
P_HTM[835]="*Dhammapadaṃ paribbājakena cāti.* **";
P_HTM[836]="*5. Pañcamapaṇṇāsakaṃ**Situations*";
P_HTM[837]="*1. Cakkasuttaṃ**Situations*";
P_HTM[838]="*“Cattārimāni, bhikkhave, cakkāni, yehi samannāgatānaṃ devamanussānaṃ catucakkaṃ vattati, yehi samannāgatā devamanussā nacirasseva mahantattaṃ vepullattaṃ pāpuṇanti bhogesu.**“Mendicants, there are these four situations. When these situations come about, any god or human who takes advantage of them will soon acquire great and abundant wealth.*";
P_HTM[839]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[840]="*Patirūpadesavāso, sappurisāvassayo, attasammāpaṇidhi, pubbe ca katapuññatā—**Living in a suitable region, relying on good people, being rightly resolved in oneself, and past merit.*";
P_HTM[841]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, cattāri cakkāni, yehi samannāgatānaṃ devamanussānaṃ catucakkaṃ vattati, yehi samannāgatā devamanussā nacirasseva mahantattaṃ vepullattaṃ pāpuṇanti bhogesūti.**These are the four situations. When these situations come about, any god or human who takes advantage of them will soon acquire great and abundant wealth.*";
P_HTM[842]="*Patirūpe vase dese,**When a person lives in a suitable region,*";
P_HTM[843]="*ariyamittakaro siyā;**making friends with noble ones,*";
P_HTM[844]="*Sammāpaṇidhisampanno,**possessing right resolve,*";
P_HTM[845]="*pubbe puññakato naro;**and having merit from the past,*";
P_HTM[846]="*Dhaññaṃ dhanaṃ yaso kitti,**grain, riches, fame, reputation,*";
P_HTM[847]="*sukhañcetaṃdhivattatī”ti.**and happiness come to them.”*";
P_HTM[848]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[849]="*2. Saṅgahasuttaṃ**Inclusion*";
P_HTM[850]="*“Cattārimāni, bhikkhave, saṅgahavatthūni.**“Mendicants, there are these four ways of being inclusive.*";
P_HTM[851]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[852]="*Dānaṃ, peyyavajjaṃ, atthacariyā, samānattatā—**Giving, kindly words, taking care, and equality.*";
P_HTM[853]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, cattāri saṅgahavatthūnīti.**These are the four ways of being inclusive.*";
P_HTM[854]="*Dānañca peyyavajjañca,**Giving and kindly words,*";
P_HTM[855]="*atthacariyā ca yā idha;**taking care here,*";
P_HTM[856]="*Samānattatā ca dhammesu,**and equality in worldly conditions,*";
P_HTM[857]="*tattha tattha yathārahaṃ;**in each case as they deserve.*";
P_HTM[858]="*Ete kho saṅgahā loke,**These ways of being inclusive in the world*";
P_HTM[859]="*rathassāṇīva yāyato.**are like a moving chariot’s linchpin.*";
P_HTM[860]="*Ete ca saṅgahā nāssu,**If there were no such ways of being inclusive,*";
P_HTM[861]="*na mātā puttakāraṇā;**neither mother nor father*";
P_HTM[862]="*Labhetha mānaṃ pūjaṃ vā,**would be respected and honored*";
P_HTM[863]="*pitā vā puttakāraṇā.**for what they’ve done for their children.*";
P_HTM[864]="*Yasmā ca saṅgahā ete,**But since these ways of being inclusive do exist,*";
P_HTM[865]="*samavekkhanti paṇḍitā;**the astute do regard them well,*";
P_HTM[866]="*Tasmā mahattaṃ papponti,**so they achieve greatness*";
P_HTM[867]="*pāsaṃsā ca bhavanti te”ti.**and are praised.”*";
P_HTM[868]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[869]="*3. Sīhasuttaṃ**The Lion*";
P_HTM[870]="*“Sīho, bhikkhave, migarājā sāyanhasamayaṃ āsayā nikkhamati.**“Mendicants, towards evening the lion, king of beasts, emerges from his den,*";
P_HTM[871]="*Āsayā nikkhamitvā vijambhati.**yawns,*";
P_HTM[872]="*Vijambhitvā samantā catuddisā anuviloketi.**looks all around the four directions,*";
P_HTM[873]="*Samantā catuddisā anuviloketvā tikkhattuṃ sīhanādaṃ nadati.**and roars his lion’s roar three times.*";
P_HTM[874]="*Tikkhattuṃ sīhanādaṃ naditvā gocarāya pakkamati.**Then he sets out on the hunt.*";
P_HTM[875]="*Ye kho pana te, bhikkhave, tiracchānagatā pāṇā sīhassa migarañño nadato saddaṃ suṇanti, te yebhuyyena bhayaṃ saṃvegaṃ santāsaṃ āpajjanti.**And the animals who hear the roar of the lion, king of beasts, are typically filled with fear, awe, and terror.*";
P_HTM[876]="*Bilaṃ bilāsayā pavisanti, dakaṃ dakāsayā pavisanti, vanaṃ vanāsayā pavisanti, ākāsaṃ pakkhino bhajanti.**They return to their lairs, be they in a hole, the water, or a wood; and the birds take to the air.*";
P_HTM[877]="*Yepi te, bhikkhave, rañño nāgā gāmanigamarājadhānīsu daḷhehi varattehi bandhanehi baddhā, tepi tāni bandhanāni sañchinditvā sampadāletvā bhītā muttakarīsaṃ cajamānā yena vā tena vā palāyanti.**Even the royal elephants, bound with strong harnesses in the villages, towns, and capital cities, break apart their bonds, and urinate and defecate in terror as they flee here and there.*";
P_HTM[878]="*Evaṃ mahiddhiko kho, bhikkhave, sīho migarājā tiracchānagatānaṃ pāṇānaṃ, evaṃ mahesakkho evaṃ mahānubhāvo.**That’s how powerful is the lion, king of beasts, among animals, how illustrious and mighty.*";
P_HTM[879]="*Evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, yadā tathāgato loke uppajjati arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā, so dhammaṃ deseti:**In the same way, when a Realized One arises in the world—perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed—he teaches the Dhamma:*";
P_HTM[880]="*‘iti sakkāyo, iti sakkāyasamudayo, iti sakkāyanirodho, iti sakkāyanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti.**‘Such is identity, such is the origin of identity, such is the cessation of identity, such is the practice that leads to the cessation of identity.’*";
P_HTM[881]="*Yepi te, bhikkhave, devā dīghāyukā vaṇṇavanto sukhabahulā uccesu vimānesu ciraṭṭhitikā, tepi tathāgatassa dhammadesanaṃ sutvā yebhuyyena bhayaṃ saṃvegaṃ santāsaṃ āpajjanti:**Now, there are gods who are long-lived, beautiful, and very happy, lasting long in their divine palaces. When they hear this teaching by the Realized One, they’re typically filled with fear, awe, and terror.*";
P_HTM[882]="*‘aniccā vata kira, bho, mayaṃ samānā niccamhāti amaññimha;**‘Oh no! It turns out we’re impermanent, though we thought we were permanent!*";
P_HTM[883]="*addhuvā vata kira, bho, mayaṃ samānā dhuvamhāti amaññimha;**It turns out we don’t last, though we thought we were everlasting!*";
P_HTM[884]="*asassatā vata kira, bho, mayaṃ samānā sassatamhāti amaññimha.**It turns out we’re transient, though we thought we were eternal!*";
P_HTM[885]="*Mayaṃ kira, bho, aniccā addhuvā asassatā sakkāyapariyāpannā’ti.**It turns out that we’re impermanent, not lasting, transient, and included within identity.’*";
P_HTM[886]="*Evaṃ mahiddhiko kho, bhikkhave, tathāgato sadevakassa lokassa, evaṃ mahesakkho evaṃ mahānubhāvoti.**That’s how powerful is the Realized One in the world with its gods, how illustrious and mighty.*";
P_HTM[887]="*Yadā buddho abhiññāya,**The Buddha, the teacher without a peer*";
P_HTM[888]="*dhammacakkaṃ pavattayī;**in all the world with its gods,*";
P_HTM[889]="*Sadevakassa lokassa,**rolls forth the Wheel of Dhamma*";
P_HTM[890]="*satthā appaṭipuggalo.**from his own insight:*";
P_HTM[891]="*Sakkāyañca nirodhañca,**identity, its cessation,*";
P_HTM[892]="*sakkāyassa ca sambhavaṃ;**the origin of identity,*";
P_HTM[893]="*Ariyañcaṭṭhaṅgikaṃ maggaṃ,**and the noble eightfold path*";
P_HTM[894]="*dukkhūpasamagāminaṃ.**that leads to the stilling of suffering.*";
P_HTM[895]="*Yepi dīghāyukā devā,**And then the long-lived gods,*";
P_HTM[896]="*vaṇṇavanto yasassino;**so beautiful and famous,*";
P_HTM[897]="*Bhītā santāsamāpāduṃ,**are afraid and full of terror,*";
P_HTM[898]="*sīhassevitare migā.**like the other beasts when they hear a lion.*";
P_HTM[899]="*Avītivattā sakkāyaṃ,**‘We haven’t transcended identity!*";
P_HTM[900]="*aniccā kira bho mayaṃ;**It turns out we’re impermanent!’*";
P_HTM[901]="*Sutvā arahato vākyaṃ,**So they say when they hear the word*";
P_HTM[902]="*vippamuttassa tādino”ti.**of the perfected one, free and poised.”*";
P_HTM[903]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[904]="*4. Aggappasādasuttaṃ**The Best Kinds of Confidence*";
P_HTM[905]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, aggappasādā.**“Mendicants, these four kinds of confidence are the best.*";
P_HTM[906]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[907]="*Yāvatā, bhikkhave, sattā apadā vā dvipadā vā catuppadā vā bahuppadā vā rūpino vā arūpino vā saññino vā asaññino vā nevasaññināsaññino vā, tathāgato tesaṃ aggamakkhāyati arahaṃ sammāsambuddho.**The Realized One, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha, is said to be the best of all sentient beings—be they footless, with two feet, four feet, or many feet; with form or formless; with perception or without perception or with neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[908]="*Ye, bhikkhave, buddhe pasannā, agge te pasannā.**Those who have confidence in the Buddha have confidence in the best.*";
P_HTM[909]="*Agge kho pana pasannānaṃ aggo vipāko hoti.**Having confidence in the best, the result is the best.*";
P_HTM[910]="*Yāvatā, bhikkhave, dhammā saṅkhatā, ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo tesaṃ aggamakkhāyati.**The noble eightfold path is said to be the best of all conditioned things.*";
P_HTM[911]="*Ye, bhikkhave, ariye aṭṭhaṅgike magge pasannā, agge te pasannā.**Those who have confidence in the noble eightfold path have confidence in the best.*";
P_HTM[912]="*Agge kho pana pasannānaṃ aggo vipāko hoti.**Having confidence in the best, the result is the best.*";
P_HTM[913]="*Yāvatā, bhikkhave, dhammā saṅkhatā vā asaṅkhatā vā, virāgo tesaṃ aggamakkhāyati, yadidaṃ madanimmadano pipāsavinayo ālayasamugghāto vaṭṭupacchedo taṇhākkhayo virāgo nirodho nibbānaṃ.**Fading away is said to be the best of all things whether conditioned or unconditioned. That is, the quelling of vanity, the removing of thirst, the abolishing of clinging, the breaking of the round, the ending of craving, fading away, cessation, extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[914]="*Ye, bhikkhave, virāge dhamme pasannā, agge te pasannā.**Those who have confidence in the teaching of fading away have confidence in the best.*";
P_HTM[915]="*Agge kho pana pasannānaṃ aggo vipāko hoti.**Having confidence in the best, the result is the best.*";
P_HTM[916]="*Yāvatā, bhikkhave, saṅghā vā gaṇā vā, tathāgatasāvakasaṅgho tesaṃ aggamakkhāyati, yadidaṃ cattāri purisayugāni aṭṭha purisapuggalā esa bhagavato sāvakasaṅgho āhuneyyo pāhuneyyo dakkhiṇeyyo añjalikaraṇīyo anuttaraṃ puññakkhettaṃ lokassa.**The Saṅgha of the Buddha’s disciples is practicing the way that’s good, straightforward, methodical, and proper. It consists of the four pairs, the eight individuals. This is the Saṅgha of the Buddha’s disciples that is worthy of offerings dedicated to the gods, worthy of hospitality, worthy of a religious donation, worthy of greeting with joined palms, and is the supreme field of merit for the world.*";
P_HTM[917]="*Ye, bhikkhave, saṅghe pasannā, agge te pasannā.**Those who have confidence in the Saṅgha have confidence in the best.*";
P_HTM[918]="*Agge kho pana pasannānaṃ aggo vipāko hoti.**Having confidence in the best, the result is the best.*";
P_HTM[919]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro aggappasādāti.**These are the four best kinds of confidence.*";
P_HTM[920]="*Aggato ve pasannānaṃ,**For those who, knowing the best teaching,*";
P_HTM[921]="*aggaṃ dhammaṃ vijānataṃ;**base their confidence on the best—*";
P_HTM[922]="*Agge buddhe pasannānaṃ,**confident in the best Awakened One,*";
P_HTM[923]="*dakkhiṇeyye anuttare.**supremely worthy of a religious donation;*";
P_HTM[924]="*Agge dhamme pasannānaṃ,**confident in the best teaching,*";
P_HTM[925]="*virāgūpasame sukhe;**the bliss of fading and stilling;*";
P_HTM[926]="*Agge saṅghe pasannānaṃ,**confident in the best Saṅgha,*";
P_HTM[927]="*puññakkhette anuttare.**the supreme field of merit—*";
P_HTM[928]="*Aggasmiṃ dānaṃ dadataṃ,**giving gifts to the best,*";
P_HTM[929]="*aggaṃ puññaṃ pavaḍḍhati;**the best of merit grows:*";
P_HTM[930]="*Aggaṃ āyu ca vaṇṇo ca,**the best lifespan, beauty,*";
P_HTM[931]="*yaso kitti sukhaṃ balaṃ.**fame, reputation, happiness, and strength.*";
P_HTM[932]="*Aggassa dātā medhāvī,**An intelligent person gives to the best,*";
P_HTM[933]="*aggadhammasamāhito;**settled on the best teaching.*";
P_HTM[934]="*Devabhūto manusso vā,**When they become a god or human,*";
P_HTM[935]="*aggappatto pamodatī”ti.**they rejoice at reaching the best.”*";
P_HTM[936]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[937]="*5. Vassakārasuttaṃ**With Vassakāra*";
P_HTM[938]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati veḷuvane kalandakanivāpe.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha, in the Bamboo Grove, the squirrels’ feeding ground.*";
P_HTM[939]="*Atha kho vassakāro brāhmaṇo magadhamahāmatto yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavatā saddhiṃ sammodi.**Then Vassakāra the brahmin, a chief minister of Magadha, went up to the Buddha, and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[940]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho vassakāro brāhmaṇo magadhamahāmatto bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side and said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[941]="*“Catūhi kho mayaṃ, bho gotama, dhammehi samannāgataṃ mahāpaññaṃ mahāpurisaṃ paññāpema.**“Master Gotama, when someone has four qualities we describe him as a great man with great wisdom.*";
P_HTM[942]="*Katamehi catūhi?**What four?*";
P_HTM[943]="*Idha, bho gotama, bahussuto hoti tassa tasseva sutajātassa**They are very learned in diverse fields of learning.*";
P_HTM[944]="*tassa tasseva kho pana bhāsitassa atthaṃ jānāti: ‘ayaṃ imassa bhāsitassa attho, ayaṃ imassa bhāsitassa attho’ti.**They understand the meaning of diverse statements, saying: ‘This is what that statement means; that is what this statement means.’*";
P_HTM[945]="*Satimā kho pana hoti cirakatampi cirabhāsitampi saritā anussaritā**They are mindful, able to remember and recollect what was said and done long ago.*";
P_HTM[946]="*yāni kho pana tāni gahaṭṭhakāni kiṃkaraṇīyāni, tattha dakkho hoti analaso, tatrupāyāya vīmaṃsāya samannāgato alaṃ kātuṃ alaṃ saṃvidhātuṃ.**They are deft and tireless in household duties, understanding how to go about things in order to complete and organize the work.*";
P_HTM[947]="*Imehi kho mayaṃ, bho gotama, catūhi dhammehi samannāgataṃ mahāpaññaṃ mahāpurisaṃ paññāpema.**When someone has these four qualities we describe him as a great man with great wisdom.*";
P_HTM[948]="*Sace me, bho gotama, anumoditabbaṃ anumodatu me bhavaṃ gotamo;**If Master Gotama agrees with me, please say so.*";
P_HTM[949]="*sace pana me, bho gotama, paṭikkositabbaṃ paṭikkosatu me bhavaṃ gotamo”ti.**If he disagrees, please say so.”*";
P_HTM[950]="*“Neva kho tyāhaṃ, brāhmaṇa, anumodāmi na paṭikkosāmi.**“Brahmin, I neither agree nor disagree with you,*";
P_HTM[951]="*Catūhi kho ahaṃ, brāhmaṇa, dhammehi samannāgataṃ mahāpaññaṃ mahāpurisaṃ paññāpemi.**but when someone has four qualities I describe him as a great man with great wisdom.*";
P_HTM[952]="*Katamehi catūhi?**What four?*";
P_HTM[953]="*Idha, brāhmaṇa, bahujanahitāya paṭipanno hoti bahujanasukhāya;**It’s when someone practices for the welfare and happiness of the people.*";
P_HTM[954]="*bahu’ssa janatā ariye ñāye patiṭṭhāpitā, yadidaṃ kalyāṇadhammatā kusaladhammatā.**They’ve established many people in the noble method, that is, the principles of goodness and skillfulness.*";
P_HTM[955]="*So yaṃ vitakkaṃ ākaṅkhati vitakketuṃ taṃ vitakkaṃ vitakketi, yaṃ vitakkaṃ nākaṅkhati vitakketuṃ na taṃ vitakkaṃ vitakketi;**They think what they want to think, and don’t think what they don’t want to think.*";
P_HTM[956]="*yaṃ saṅkappaṃ ākaṅkhati saṅkappetuṃ taṃ saṅkappaṃ saṅkappeti, yaṃ saṅkappaṃ nākaṅkhati saṅkappetuṃ na taṃ saṅkappaṃ saṅkappeti.**They consider what they want to consider, and don’t consider what they don’t want to consider.*";
P_HTM[957]="*Iti cetovasippatto hoti vitakkapathe.**Thus they have achieved mental mastery of the paths of thought.*";
P_HTM[958]="*Catunnaṃ jhānānaṃ ābhicetasikānaṃ diṭṭhadhammasukhavihārānaṃ nikāmalābhī hoti akicchalābhī akasiralābhī.**They get the four absorptions—blissful meditations in the present life that belong to the higher mind—when they want, without trouble or difficulty.*";
P_HTM[959]="*Āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati.**They realize the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life. And they live having realized it with their own insight due to the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[960]="*Neva kho tyāhaṃ, brāhmaṇa, anumodāmi na pana paṭikkosāmi.**Brahmin, I neither agree nor disagree with you,*";
P_HTM[961]="*Imehi kho ahaṃ, brāhmaṇa, catūhi dhammehi samannāgataṃ mahāpaññaṃ mahāpurisaṃ paññāpemī”ti.**but when someone has these four qualities I describe him as a great man with great wisdom.”*";
P_HTM[962]="*“Acchariyaṃ, bho gotama, abbhutaṃ, bho gotama.**“It’s incredible, Master Gotama, it’s amazing!*";
P_HTM[963]="*Yāva subhāsitañcidaṃ bhotā gotamena.**How well said this was by Master Gotama!*";
P_HTM[964]="*Imehi ca mayaṃ, bho gotama, catūhi dhammehi samannāgataṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ dhārema;**And we will remember Master Gotama as someone who has these four qualities.*";
P_HTM[965]="*bhavañhi gotamo bahujanahitāya paṭipanno bahujanasukhāya;**For Master Gotama practices for the welfare and happiness of the people …*";
P_HTM[966]="*bahu te janatā ariye ñāye patiṭṭhāpitā, yadidaṃ kalyāṇadhammatā kusaladhammatā.* **";
P_HTM[967]="*Bhavañhi gotamo yaṃ vitakkaṃ ākaṅkhati vitakketuṃ taṃ vitakkaṃ vitakketi, yaṃ vitakkaṃ nākaṅkhati vitakketuṃ na taṃ vitakkaṃ vitakketi, yaṃ saṅkappaṃ ākaṅkhati saṅkappetuṃ taṃ saṅkappaṃ saṅkappeti, yaṃ saṅkappaṃ nākaṅkhati saṅkappetuṃ na taṃ saṅkappaṃ saṅkappeti.* **";
P_HTM[968]="*Bhavañhi gotamo cetovasippatto vitakkapathe.**Master Gotama has achieved mental mastery of the paths of thought.*";
P_HTM[969]="*Bhavañhi gotamo catunnaṃ jhānānaṃ ābhicetasikānaṃ diṭṭhadhammasukhavihārānaṃ nikāmalābhī akicchalābhī akasiralābhī.**Master Gotama gets the four absorptions … when he wants, without trouble or difficulty.*";
P_HTM[970]="*Bhavañhi gotamo āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharatī”ti.**Master Gotama has realized the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life. He lives having realized it with his own insight due to the ending of defilements.”*";
P_HTM[971]="*“Addhā kho tyāhaṃ, brāhmaṇa, āsajja upanīya vācā bhāsitā.**“Your words are clearly invasive and intrusive, brahmin.*";
P_HTM[972]="*Api ca tyāhaṃ byākarissāmi:**Nevertheless, I will answer you.*";
P_HTM[973]="*‘ahañhi, brāhmaṇa, bahujanahitāya paṭipanno bahujanasukhāya;**For I do practice for the welfare and happiness of the people …*";
P_HTM[974]="*bahu me janatā ariye ñāye patiṭṭhāpitā, yadidaṃ kalyāṇadhammatā kusaladhammatā.* **";
P_HTM[975]="*Ahañhi, brāhmaṇa, yaṃ vitakkaṃ ākaṅkhāmi vitakketuṃ taṃ vitakkaṃ vitakkemi, yaṃ vitakkaṃ nākaṅkhāmi vitakketuṃ na taṃ vitakkaṃ vitakkemi, yaṃ saṅkappaṃ ākaṅkhāmi saṅkappetuṃ taṃ saṅkappaṃ saṅkappemi, yaṃ saṅkappaṃ nākaṅkhāmi saṅkappetuṃ na taṃ saṅkappaṃ saṅkappemi.* **";
P_HTM[976]="*Ahañhi, brāhmaṇa, cetovasippatto vitakkapathe.**I have achieved mental mastery of the paths of thought.*";
P_HTM[977]="*Ahañhi, brāhmaṇa, catunnaṃ jhānānaṃ ābhicetasikānaṃ diṭṭhadhammasukhavihārānaṃ nikāmalābhī akicchalābhī akasiralābhī.**I do get the four absorptions … when I want, without trouble or difficulty.*";
P_HTM[978]="*Ahañhi, brāhmaṇa, āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharāmī’ti.**I have realized the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life. I live having realized it with my own insight due to the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[979]="*Yo vedi sabbasattānaṃ,**He discovered release from the snare of death*";
P_HTM[980]="*maccupāsappamocanaṃ;**for all beings,*";
P_HTM[981]="*Hitaṃ devamanussānaṃ,**and explained the method of the teaching*";
P_HTM[982]="*ñāyaṃ dhammaṃ pakāsayi;**for the welfare of gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[983]="*Yaṃ ve disvā ca sutvā ca,**When they see him or hear him,*";
P_HTM[984]="*pasīdanti bahū janā.**many people become confident.*";
P_HTM[985]="*Maggāmaggassa kusalo,**He is skilled in the variety of paths,*";
P_HTM[986]="*Katakicco anāsavo;**he has completed the task and is free of defilements.*";
P_HTM[987]="*Buddho antimasārīro,**The Buddha, bearing his final body,*";
P_HTM[988]="*Mahāpañño mahāpurisoti vuccatī”ti.**is called ‘a great man, of great wisdom’.”*";
P_HTM[989]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[990]="*6. Doṇasuttaṃ**Doṇa*";
P_HTM[991]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā antarā ca ukkaṭṭhaṃ antarā ca setabyaṃ addhānamaggappaṭipanno hoti.**At one time the Buddha was traveling along the road between Ukkaṭṭhā and Setabya,*";
P_HTM[992]="*Doṇopi sudaṃ brāhmaṇo antarā ca ukkaṭṭhaṃ antarā ca setabyaṃ addhānamaggappaṭipanno hoti.**as was the brahmin Doṇa.*";
P_HTM[993]="*Addasā kho doṇo brāhmaṇo bhagavato pādesu cakkāni sahassārāni sanemikāni sanābhikāni sabbākāraparipūrāni;**Doṇa saw that the Buddha’s footprints had thousand-spoked wheels, with rims and hubs, complete in every detail.*";
P_HTM[994]="*disvānassa etadahosi:**It occurred to him,*";
P_HTM[995]="*“acchariyaṃ vata bho, abbhutaṃ vata bho.**“It’s incredible, it’s amazing!*";
P_HTM[996]="*Na vatimāni manussabhūtassa padāni bhavissantī”ti.**Surely these couldn’t be the footprints of a human being?”*";
P_HTM[997]="*Atha kho bhagavā maggā okkamma aññatarasmiṃ rukkhamūle nisīdi pallaṅkaṃ ābhujitvā ujuṃ kāyaṃ paṇidhāya parimukhaṃ satiṃ upaṭṭhapetvā.**The Buddha had left the road and sat at the root of a tree cross-legged, with his body straight and his mindfulness established right there.*";
P_HTM[998]="*Atha kho doṇo brāhmaṇo bhagavato padāni anugacchanto addasa bhagavantaṃ aññatarasmiṃ rukkhamūle nisinnaṃ pāsādikaṃ pasādanīyaṃ santindriyaṃ santamānasaṃ uttamadamathasamathamanuppattaṃ dantaṃ guttaṃ saṃyatindriyaṃ nāgaṃ.**Then Doṇa, following the Buddha’s footprints, saw him sitting at the tree root—impressive and inspiring, with peaceful faculties and mind, attained to the highest taming and serenity, like an elephant with tamed, guarded, and controlled faculties.*";
P_HTM[999]="*Disvāna yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**He went up to the Buddha and said to him:*";
P_HTM[1000]="*“Devo no bhavaṃ bhavissatī”ti?**“Sir, might you be a god?”*";
P_HTM[1001]="*“Na kho ahaṃ, brāhmaṇa, devo bhavissāmī”ti.**“I will not be a god, brahmin.”*";
P_HTM[1002]="*“Gandhabbo no bhavaṃ bhavissatī”ti?**“Might you be a fairy?”*";
P_HTM[1003]="*“Na kho ahaṃ, brāhmaṇa, gandhabbo bhavissāmī”ti.**“I will not be a fairy.”*";
P_HTM[1004]="*“Yakkho no bhavaṃ bhavissatī”ti?**“Might you be a native spirit?”*";
P_HTM[1005]="*“Na kho ahaṃ, brāhmaṇa, yakkho bhavissāmī”ti.**“I will not be a native spirit.”*";
P_HTM[1006]="*“Manusso no bhavaṃ bhavissatī”ti?**“Might you be a human?”*";
P_HTM[1007]="*“Na kho ahaṃ, brāhmaṇa, manusso bhavissāmī”ti.**“I will not be a human.”*";
P_HTM[1008]="*“‘Devo no bhavaṃ bhavissatī’ti, iti puṭṭho samāno:**“When asked whether you might be a god, fairy, native spirit, or human,*";
P_HTM[1009]="*‘na kho ahaṃ, brāhmaṇa, devo bhavissāmī’ti vadesi.**you answer that you will not be any of these.*";
P_HTM[1010]="*‘Gandhabbo no bhavaṃ bhavissatī’ti, iti puṭṭho samāno:* **";
P_HTM[1011]="*‘na kho ahaṃ, brāhmaṇa, gandhabbo bhavissāmī’ti vadesi.* **";
P_HTM[1012]="*‘Yakkho no bhavaṃ bhavissatī’ti, iti puṭṭho samāno:* **";
P_HTM[1013]="*‘na kho ahaṃ, brāhmaṇa, yakkho bhavissāmī’ti vadesi.* **";
P_HTM[1014]="*‘Manusso no bhavaṃ bhavissatī’ti, iti puṭṭho samāno:* **";
P_HTM[1015]="*‘na kho ahaṃ, brāhmaṇa, manusso bhavissāmī’ti vadesi.* **";
P_HTM[1016]="*Atha ko carahi bhavaṃ bhavissatī”ti?**What then might you be?”*";
P_HTM[1017]="*“Yesaṃ kho ahaṃ, brāhmaṇa, āsavānaṃ appahīnattā devo bhaveyyaṃ, te me āsavā pahīnā ucchinnamūlā tālāvatthukatā anabhāvaṅkatā āyatiṃ anuppādadhammā.**“Brahmin, if I had not given up defilements I might have become a god … a fairy … a native spirit … or a human. But I have given up those defilements, cut them off at the root, made them like a palm stump, obliterated them so they are unable to arise in the future.*";
P_HTM[1018]="*Yesaṃ kho ahaṃ, brāhmaṇa, āsavānaṃ appahīnattā gandhabbo bhaveyyaṃ … yakkho bhaveyyaṃ … manusso bhaveyyaṃ, te me āsavā pahīnā ucchinnamūlā tālāvatthukatā anabhāvaṅkatā āyatiṃ anuppādadhammā.* **";
P_HTM[1019]="*Seyyathāpi, brāhmaṇa, uppalaṃ vā padumaṃ vā puṇḍarīkaṃ vā udake jātaṃ udake saṃvaḍḍhaṃ udakā accuggamma tiṭṭhati anupalittaṃ udakena;**Suppose there was a blue water lily, or a pink or white lotus. Though it sprouted and grew in the water, it would rise up above the water and stand with no water clinging to it.*";
P_HTM[1020]="*evamevaṃ kho ahaṃ, brāhmaṇa, loke jāto loke saṃvaḍḍho lokaṃ abhibhuyya viharāmi anupalitto lokena.**In the same way, though I was born and grew up in the world, I live having mastered the world, and the world does not cling to me.*";
P_HTM[1021]="*Buddhoti maṃ, brāhmaṇa, dhārehīti.**Remember me, brahmin, as a Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1022]="*Yena devūpapatyassa,**I could have been reborn as a god,*";
P_HTM[1023]="*gandhabbo vā vihaṅgamo;**or as a fairy flying through the sky.*";
P_HTM[1024]="*Yakkhattaṃ yena gaccheyyaṃ,**I could have become a native spirit,*";
P_HTM[1025]="*manussattañca abbaje;**or returned as a human.*";
P_HTM[1026]="*Te mayhaṃ āsavā khīṇā,**But the defilements that could bring about these rebirths*";
P_HTM[1027]="*viddhastā vinaḷīkatā.**I’ve ended, smashed, and gutted.*";
P_HTM[1028]="*Puṇḍarīkaṃ yathā vaggu,**Like a graceful lotus,*";
P_HTM[1029]="*Toyena nupalippati;**to which water does not cling,*";
P_HTM[1030]="*Nupalippāmi lokena,**the world doesn’t cling to me,*";
P_HTM[1031]="*Tasmā buddhosmi brāhmaṇā”ti.**and so, brahmin, I am a Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[1032]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1033]="*7. Aparihāniyasuttaṃ**Non*";
P_HTM[1034]="*“Catūhi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu abhabbo parihānāya nibbānasseva santike.**“Mendicants, a mendicant who has four qualities can’t decline, and is close to extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[1035]="*Katamehi catūhi?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1036]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sīlasampanno hoti, indriyesu guttadvāro hoti, bhojane mattaññū hoti, jāgariyaṃ anuyutto hoti.**A mendicant is accomplished in ethics, guards the sense doors, eats in moderation, and is dedicated to wakefulness.*";
P_HTM[1037]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sīlasampanno hoti?**And how is a mendicant accomplished in ethics?*";
P_HTM[1038]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sīlavā hoti pātimokkhasaṃvarasaṃvuto viharati ācāragocarasampanno aṇumattesu vajjesu bhayadassāvī, samādāya sikkhati sikkhāpadesu.**It’s when a mendicant is ethical, restrained in the monastic code, conducting themselves well and seeking alms in suitable places. Seeing danger in the slightest fault, they keep the rules they’ve undertaken.*";
P_HTM[1039]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sīlasampanno hoti.**That’s how a mendicant is accomplished in ethics.*";
P_HTM[1040]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu indriyesu guttadvāro hoti?**And how does a mendicant guard the sense doors?*";
P_HTM[1041]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā na nimittaggāhī hoti nānubyañjanaggāhī.**When a mendicant sees a sight with their eyes, they don’t get caught up in the features and details.*";
P_HTM[1042]="*Yatvādhikaraṇamenaṃ cakkhundriyaṃ asaṃvutaṃ viharantaṃ abhijjhādomanassā pāpakā akusalā dhammā anvāssaveyyuṃ, tassa saṃvarāya paṭipajjati; rakkhati cakkhundriyaṃ; cakkhundriye saṃvaraṃ āpajjati.**If the faculty of sight were left unrestrained, bad unskillful qualities of desire and aversion would become overwhelming. For this reason, they practice restraint, protecting the faculty of sight, and achieving restraint over it.*";
P_HTM[1043]="*Sotena saddaṃ sutvā …**Hearing a sound with their ears …*";
P_HTM[1044]="*ghānena gandhaṃ ghāyitvā …**Smelling an odor with their nose …*";
P_HTM[1045]="*jivhāya rasaṃ sāyitvā …**Tasting a flavor with their tongue …*";
P_HTM[1046]="*kāyena phoṭṭhabbaṃ phusitvā …**Feeling a touch with their body …*";
P_HTM[1047]="*manasā dhammaṃ viññāya na nimittaggāhī hoti nānubyañjanaggāhī.**Knowing a thought with their mind, they don’t get caught up in the features and details.*";
P_HTM[1048]="*Yatvādhikaraṇamenaṃ manindriyaṃ asaṃvutaṃ viharantaṃ abhijjhādomanassā pāpakā akusalā dhammā anvāssaveyyuṃ, tassa saṃvarāya paṭipajjati; rakkhati manindriyaṃ; manindriye saṃvaraṃ āpajjati.**If the faculty of mind were left unrestrained, bad unskillful qualities of desire and aversion would become overwhelming. For this reason, they practice restraint, protecting the faculty of mind, and achieving restraint over it.*";
P_HTM[1049]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu indriyesu guttadvāro hoti.**That’s how a mendicant guards the sense doors.*";
P_HTM[1050]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu bhojane mattaññū hoti?**And how does a mendicant eat in moderation?*";
P_HTM[1051]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu paṭisaṅkhā yoniso āhāraṃ āhāreti:**It’s when a mendicant reflects properly on the food that they eat:*";
P_HTM[1052]="*‘neva davāya na madāya na maṇḍanāya na vibhūsanāya; yāvadeva imassa kāyassa ṭhitiyā yāpanāya vihiṃsūparatiyā brahmacariyānuggahāya. Iti purāṇañca vedanaṃ paṭihaṅkhāmi, navañca vedanaṃ na uppādessāmi, yātrā ca me bhavissati, anavajjatā ca phāsuvihāro cā’ti.**‘Not for fun, indulgence, adornment, or decoration, but only to sustain this body, to avoid harm, and to support spiritual practice. In this way, I shall put an end to old discomfort and not give rise to new discomfort, and I will live blamelessly and at ease.’*";
P_HTM[1053]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu bhojane mattaññū hoti.**That’s how a mendicant eats in moderation.*";
P_HTM[1054]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu jāgariyaṃ anuyutto hoti?**And how is a mendicant dedicated to wakefulness?*";
P_HTM[1055]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu divasaṃ caṅkamena nisajjāya āvaraṇīyehi dhammehi cittaṃ parisodheti;**It’s when a mendicant practices walking and sitting meditation by day, purifying their mind from obstacles.*";
P_HTM[1056]="*rattiyā paṭhamaṃ yāmaṃ caṅkamena nisajjāya āvaraṇīyehi dhammehi cittaṃ parisodheti;**In the evening, they continue to practice walking and sitting meditation.*";
P_HTM[1057]="*rattiyā majjhimaṃ yāmaṃ dakkhiṇena passena sīhaseyyaṃ kappeti, pāde pādaṃ accādhāya, sato sampajāno uṭṭhānasaññaṃ manasi karitvā;**In the middle of the night, they lie down in the lion’s posture—on the right side, placing one foot on top of the other—mindful and aware, and focused on the time of getting up.*";
P_HTM[1058]="*rattiyā pacchimaṃ yāmaṃ paccuṭṭhāya caṅkamena nisajjāya āvaraṇīyehi dhammehi cittaṃ parisodheti.**In the last part of the night, they get up and continue to practice walking and sitting meditation, purifying their mind from obstacles.*";
P_HTM[1059]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu jāgariyaṃ anuyutto hoti.**This is how a mendicant is dedicated to wakefulness.*";
P_HTM[1060]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, catūhi dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu abhabbo parihānāya, nibbānasseva santiketi.**A mendicant who has these four qualities can’t decline, and has drawn near to extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[1061]="*Sīle patiṭṭhito bhikkhu,**Established in ethics,*";
P_HTM[1062]="*indriyesu ca saṃvuto;**restrained in the sense faculties,*";
P_HTM[1063]="*Bhojanamhi ca mattaññū,**eating in moderation,*";
P_HTM[1064]="*jāgariyaṃ anuyuñjati.**and dedicated to wakefulness;*";
P_HTM[1065]="*Evaṃ vihārī ātāpī,**a mendicant lives like this, with keen energy,*";
P_HTM[1066]="*ahorattamatandito;**tireless all night and day,*";
P_HTM[1067]="*Bhāvayaṃ kusalaṃ dhammaṃ,**developing skillful qualities,*";
P_HTM[1068]="*yogakkhemassa pattiyā.**for the sake of finding sanctuary.*";
P_HTM[1069]="*Appamādarato bhikkhu,**A mendicant who loves to be diligent,*";
P_HTM[1070]="*pamāde bhayadassi vā;**seeing fear in negligence,*";
P_HTM[1071]="*Abhabbo parihānāya,**can’t decline,*";
P_HTM[1072]="*nibbānasseva santike”ti.**and has drawn near to extinguishment.”*";
P_HTM[1073]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1074]="*8. Patilīnasuttaṃ**Withdrawn*";
P_HTM[1075]="*“Panuṇṇapaccekasacco, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ‘samavayasaṭṭhesano passaddhakāyasaṅkhāro patilīno’ti vuccati.**“Mendicants, a mendicant has eliminated idiosyncratic interpretations of the truth, has totally given up searching, has stilled the physical process, and is said to be ‘withdrawn’.*";
P_HTM[1076]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu panuṇṇapaccekasacco hoti?**And how has a mendicant eliminated idiosyncratic interpretations of the truth?*";
P_HTM[1077]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno yāni tāni puthusamaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ puthupaccekasaccāni, seyyathidaṃ—**Different ascetics and brahmins have different idiosyncratic interpretations of the truth. For example:*";
P_HTM[1078]="*sassato lokoti vā, asassato lokoti vā, antavā lokoti vā, anantavā lokoti vā, taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīranti vā, aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīranti vā, hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇāti vā, na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇāti vā, hoti ca na ca hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇāti vā, neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇāti vā;**the world is eternal, or not eternal, or finite, or infinite; the soul and the body are the same thing, or they are different things; after death, a Realized One exists, or doesn’t exist, or both exists and doesn’t exist, or neither exists nor doesn’t exist.*";
P_HTM[1079]="*sabbāni tāni nuṇṇāni honti panuṇṇāni cattāni vantāni muttāni pahīnāni paṭinissaṭṭhāni.**A mendicant has dispelled, eliminated, thrown out, rejected, let go of, given up, and relinquished all these.*";
P_HTM[1080]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu panuṇṇapaccekasacco hoti.**That’s how a mendicant has eliminated idiosyncratic interpretations of the truth.*";
P_HTM[1081]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu samavayasaṭṭhesano hoti?**And how has a mendicant totally given up searching?*";
P_HTM[1082]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno kāmesanā pahīnā hoti, bhavesanā pahīnā hoti, brahmacariyesanā paṭippassaddhā.**It’s when they’ve given up searching for sensual pleasures, for continued existence, and for a spiritual path.*";
P_HTM[1083]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu samavayasaṭṭhesano hoti.**That’s how a mendicant has totally given up searching.*";
P_HTM[1084]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu passaddhakāyasaṅkhāro hoti?**And how has a mendicant stilled the physical process?*";
P_HTM[1085]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sukhassa ca pahānā dukkhassa ca pahānā pubbeva somanassadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamā adukkhamasukhaṃ upekkhāsatipārisuddhiṃ catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**It’s when, giving up pleasure and pain, and ending former happiness and sadness, they enter and remain in the fourth absorption, without pleasure or pain, with pure equanimity and mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[1086]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu passaddhakāyasaṅkhāro hoti.**That’s how a mendicant has stilled the physical process.*";
P_HTM[1087]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu patilīno hoti?**And how is a mendicant withdrawn?*";
P_HTM[1088]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno asmimāno pahīno hoti ucchinnamūlo tālāvatthukato anabhāvaṅkato āyatiṃ anuppādadhammo.**It’s when they’ve given up the conceit ‘I am’, cut it off at the root, made it like a palm stump, obliterated it, so it’s unable to arise in the future.*";
P_HTM[1089]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu patilīno hoti.**That’s how a mendicant is withdrawn.*";
P_HTM[1090]="*Panuṇṇapaccekasacco, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ‘samavayasaṭṭhesano passaddhakāyasaṅkhāro patilīno’ti vuccatīti.**A mendicant has eliminated idiosyncratic interpretations of the truth, has totally given up searching, has stilled the physical process, and is said to be ‘withdrawn’.*";
P_HTM[1091]="*Kāmesanā bhavesanā,**The search for sensual pleasures, for a good rebirth,*";
P_HTM[1092]="*brahmacariyesanā saha;**together with the search for a spiritual path;*";
P_HTM[1093]="*Iti saccaparāmāso,**holding tight to the notion ‘this is the truth’,*";
P_HTM[1094]="*diṭṭhiṭṭhānā samussayā.**and the mass of grounds for views.*";
P_HTM[1095]="*Sabbarāgavirattassa,**For one detached from all lusts,*";
P_HTM[1096]="*taṇhakkhayavimuttino;**freed by the ending of craving,*";
P_HTM[1097]="*Esanā paṭinissaṭṭhā,**searching has been relinquished,*";
P_HTM[1098]="*diṭṭhiṭṭhānā samūhatā.**and viewpoints eradicated.*";
P_HTM[1099]="*Sa ve santo sato bhikkhu,**That mendicant is peaceful and mindful,*";
P_HTM[1100]="*passaddho aparājito;**a tranquil champion.*";
P_HTM[1101]="*Mānābhisamayā buddho,**And when they’re awakened by comprehending conceit,*";
P_HTM[1102]="*patilīnoti vuccatī”ti.**they’re called ‘withdrawn’.”*";
P_HTM[1103]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1104]="*9. Ujjayasuttaṃ**With Ujjaya*";
P_HTM[1105]="*Atha kho ujjayo brāhmaṇo yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavatā saddhiṃ sammodi.**Then Ujjaya the brahmin went up to the Buddha, and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[1106]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho ujjayo brāhmaṇo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side and said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[1107]="*“bhavampi no gotamo yaññaṃ vaṇṇetī”ti?**“Does Master Gotama praise sacrifice?”*";
P_HTM[1108]="*“Na kho ahaṃ, brāhmaṇa, sabbaṃ yaññaṃ vaṇṇemi;**“Brahmin, I don’t praise all sacrifices.*";
P_HTM[1109]="*na panāhaṃ, brāhmaṇa, sabbaṃ yaññaṃ na vaṇṇemi.**Nor do I criticize all sacrifices.*";
P_HTM[1110]="*Yathārūpe kho, brāhmaṇa, yaññe gāvo haññanti, ajeḷakā haññanti, kukkuṭasūkarā haññanti, vividhā pāṇā saṅghātaṃ āpajjanti;**Take the kind of sacrifice where cattle, goats and sheep, chickens and pigs, and various kinds of creatures are slaughtered.*";
P_HTM[1111]="*evarūpaṃ kho ahaṃ, brāhmaṇa, sārambhaṃ yaññaṃ na vaṇṇemi.**I criticize that kind of violent sacrifice.*";
P_HTM[1112]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[1113]="*Evarūpañhi, brāhmaṇa, sārambhaṃ yaññaṃ na upasaṅkamanti arahanto vā arahattamaggaṃ vā samāpannā.**Because neither perfected ones nor those who have entered the path to perfection will attend such a violent sacrifice.*";
P_HTM[1114]="*Yathārūpe ca kho, brāhmaṇa, yaññe neva gāvo haññanti, na ajeḷakā haññanti, na kukkuṭasūkarā haññanti, na vividhā pāṇā saṅghātaṃ āpajjanti;**But take the kind of sacrifice where cattle, goats and sheep, chickens and pigs, and various kinds of creatures are not slaughtered.*";
P_HTM[1115]="*evarūpaṃ kho ahaṃ, brāhmaṇa, nirārambhaṃ yaññaṃ vaṇṇemi, yadidaṃ niccadānaṃ anukulayaññaṃ.**I praise that kind of non-violent sacrifice; for example, a regular gift as an ongoing family sacrifice.*";
P_HTM[1116]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[1117]="*Evarūpañhi, brāhmaṇa, nirārambhaṃ yaññaṃ upasaṅkamanti arahanto vā arahattamaggaṃ vā samāpannāti.**Because perfected ones and those who have entered the path to perfection will attend such a non-violent sacrifice.*";
P_HTM[1118]="*Assamedhaṃ purisamedhaṃ,**Horse sacrifice, human sacrifice,*";
P_HTM[1119]="*Sammāpāsaṃ vājapeyyaṃ niraggaḷaṃ;**the sacrifices of the ‘stick-casting’,*";
P_HTM[1120]="*Mahāyaññā mahārambhā,**the ‘royal soma drinking’, and the ‘unbarred’—*";
P_HTM[1121]="*Na te honti mahapphalā.**these huge violent sacrifices yield no great fruit.*";
P_HTM[1122]="*Ajeḷakā ca gāvo ca,**The great sages of good conduct*";
P_HTM[1123]="*vividhā yattha haññare;**don’t attend sacrifices*";
P_HTM[1124]="*Na taṃ sammaggatā yaññaṃ,**where goats, sheep, and cattle,*";
P_HTM[1125]="*upayanti mahesino.**and various creatures are killed.*";
P_HTM[1126]="*Ye ca yaññā nirārambhā,**But the great sages of good conduct*";
P_HTM[1127]="*yajanti anukulaṃ sadā;**do attend non-violent sacrifices*";
P_HTM[1128]="*Ajeḷakā ca gāvo ca,**of regular family tradition,*";
P_HTM[1129]="*vividhā nettha haññare;**where goats, sheep, and cattle,*";
P_HTM[1130]="*Tañca sammaggatā yaññaṃ,**and various creatures aren’t killed.*";
P_HTM[1131]="*upayanti mahesino.* **";
P_HTM[1132]="*Etaṃ yajetha medhāvī,**An intelligent person should sacrifice like this,*";
P_HTM[1133]="*eso yañño mahapphalo;**for this sacrifice is very fruitful.*";
P_HTM[1134]="*Etaṃ hi yajamānassa,**For a sponsor of sacrifices like this,*";
P_HTM[1135]="*seyyo hoti na pāpiyo;**things get better, not worse.*";
P_HTM[1136]="*Yañño ca vipulo hoti,**Such a sacrifice is truly abundant,*";
P_HTM[1137]="*pasīdanti ca devatā”ti.**and even the deities are pleased.”*";
P_HTM[1138]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1139]="*10. Udāyīsuttaṃ**With Udāyī*";
P_HTM[1140]="*Atha kho udāyī brāhmaṇo yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavatā … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho udāyī brāhmaṇo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Udāyī the brahmin went up to the Buddha, … and asked him,*";
P_HTM[1141]="*“bhavampi no gotamo yaññaṃ vaṇṇetī”ti?**“Does Master Gotama praise sacrifice?”*";
P_HTM[1142]="*“Na kho ahaṃ, brāhmaṇa, sabbaṃ yaññaṃ vaṇṇemi;**“Brahmin, I don’t praise all sacrifices.*";
P_HTM[1143]="*na panāhaṃ, brāhmaṇa, sabbaṃ yaññaṃ na vaṇṇemi.**Nor do I criticize all sacrifices. …*";
P_HTM[1144]="*Yathārūpe kho, brāhmaṇa, yaññe gāvo haññanti, ajeḷakā haññanti, kukkuṭasūkarā haññanti, vividhā pāṇā saṅghātaṃ āpajjanti;**Take the kind of sacrifice where cattle, goats and sheep, chickens and pigs, and various kinds of animals are slaughtered.*";
P_HTM[1145]="*evarūpaṃ kho ahaṃ, brāhmaṇa, sārambhaṃ yaññaṃ na vaṇṇemi.**I don’t praise that kind of violent sacrifice.*";
P_HTM[1146]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?* **";
P_HTM[1147]="*Evarūpañhi, brāhmaṇa, sārambhaṃ yaññaṃ na upasaṅkamanti arahanto vā arahattamaggaṃ vā samāpannā.* **";
P_HTM[1148]="*Yathārūpe ca kho, brāhmaṇa, yaññe neva gāvo haññanti, na ajeḷakā haññanti, na kukkuṭasūkarā haññanti, na vividhā pāṇā saṅghātaṃ āpajjanti;**But take the kind of sacrifice where cattle, goats and sheep, chickens and pigs, and various kinds of animals are not slaughtered.*";
P_HTM[1149]="*evarūpaṃ kho ahaṃ, brāhmaṇa, nirārambhaṃ yaññaṃ vaṇṇemi, yadidaṃ niccadānaṃ anukulayaññaṃ.**I do praise that kind of non-violent sacrifice; for example, a regular gift as an ongoing family sacrifice.*";
P_HTM[1150]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?* **";
P_HTM[1151]="*Evarūpañhi, brāhmaṇa, nirārambhaṃ yaññaṃ upasaṅkamanti arahanto vā arahattamaggaṃ vā samāpannāti.* **";
P_HTM[1152]="*Abhisaṅkhataṃ nirārambhaṃ,**The kind of sacrifice that’s allowable and timely,*";
P_HTM[1153]="*yaññaṃ kālena kappiyaṃ;**well prepared and non-violent,*";
P_HTM[1154]="*Tādisaṃ upasaṃyanti,**is attended by*";
P_HTM[1155]="*saññatā brahmacārayo.**disciplined spiritual practitioners.*";
P_HTM[1156]="*Vivaṭacchadā ye loke,**The Buddhas—who have drawn back the veil from the world,*";
P_HTM[1157]="*vītivattā kulaṃ gatiṃ;**transcending time and rebirth—*";
P_HTM[1158]="*Yaññametaṃ pasaṃsanti,**praise this sacrifice,*";
P_HTM[1159]="*buddhā yaññassa kovidā.**as they are expert in sacrifice.*";
P_HTM[1160]="*Yaññe vā yadi vā saddhe,**When you’ve prepared a suitable offering,*";
P_HTM[1161]="*habyaṃ katvā yathārahaṃ;**whether as sacrifice or for ancestors,*";
P_HTM[1162]="*Pasannacitto yajati,**sacrifice it with confident heart,*";
P_HTM[1163]="*sukhette brahmacārisu.**in the fertile field of spiritual practitioners.*";
P_HTM[1164]="*Suhutaṃ suyiṭṭhaṃ suppattaṃ,**When it’s well-gotten, well-offered, and well-sacrificed,*";
P_HTM[1165]="*Dakkhiṇeyyesu yaṃ kataṃ;**to those worthy of a religious donation,*";
P_HTM[1166]="*Yañño ca vipulo hoti,**a sacrifice is truly abundant,*";
P_HTM[1167]="*Pasīdanti ca devatā.**and even the deities are pleased.*";
P_HTM[1168]="*Evaṃ yajitvā medhāvī,**When an intelligent, faithful person,*";
P_HTM[1169]="*saddho muttena cetasā;**sacrifices like this, with a mind of letting go,*";
P_HTM[1170]="*Abyābajjhaṃ sukhaṃ lokaṃ,**that astute one is reborn*";
P_HTM[1171]="*paṇḍito upapajjatī”ti.**in a happy, pleasing world.”*";
P_HTM[1172]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1173]="*Cakkavaggo catuttho.* **";
P_HTM[1174]="*Cakko saṅgaho sīho,* **";
P_HTM[1175]="*Pasādo vassakārena pañcamaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[1176]="*Doṇo aparihāniyo patilīno,* **";
P_HTM[1177]="*Ujjayo udāyinā te dasāti.* **";
P_HTM[1178]="*3____31-510. Dosaabhiññādisuttāni**With Rohitassa*";
P_HTM[1179]="*1. Samādhibhāvanāsuttaṃ**Ways of Developing Immersion Further*";
P_HTM[1180]="*“Catasso imā, bhikkhave, samādhibhāvanā.**“Mendicants, there are these four ways of developing immersion further.*";
P_HTM[1181]="*Katamā catasso?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1182]="*Atthi, bhikkhave, samādhibhāvanā bhāvitā bahulīkatā diṭṭhadhammasukhavihārāya saṃvattati;**There is a way of developing immersion further that leads to blissful meditation in the present life.*";
P_HTM[1183]="*atthi, bhikkhave, samādhibhāvanā bhāvitā bahulīkatā ñāṇadassanappaṭilābhāya saṃvattati;**There is a way of developing immersion further that leads to gaining knowledge and vision.*";
P_HTM[1184]="*atthi, bhikkhave, samādhibhāvanā bhāvitā bahulīkatā satisampajaññāya saṃvattati;**There is a way of developing immersion further that leads to mindfulness and awareness.*";
P_HTM[1185]="*atthi, bhikkhave, samādhibhāvanā bhāvitā bahulīkatā āsavānaṃ khayāya saṃvattati.**There is a way of developing immersion further that leads to the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[1186]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, samādhibhāvanā bhāvitā bahulīkatā diṭṭhadhammasukhavihārāya saṃvattati?**And what is the way of developing immersion further that leads to blissful meditation in the present life?*";
P_HTM[1187]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi … pe … catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**It’s when a mendicant, quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, enters and remains in the first absorption … second absorption … third absorption … fourth absorption.*";
P_HTM[1188]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, samādhibhāvanā bhāvitā bahulīkatā diṭṭhadhammasukhavihārāya saṃvattati.**This is the way of developing immersion further that leads to blissful meditation in the present life.*";
P_HTM[1189]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, samādhibhāvanā bhāvitā bahulīkatā ñāṇadassanappaṭilābhāya saṃvattati?**And what is the way of developing immersion further that leads to gaining knowledge and vision?*";
P_HTM[1190]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ālokasaññaṃ manasi karoti, divāsaññaṃ adhiṭṭhāti—**It’s when a mendicant focuses on the perception of light, concentrating on the perception of day,*";
P_HTM[1191]="*yathā divā tathā rattiṃ, yathā rattiṃ tathā divā.**regardless of whether it’s night or day.*";
P_HTM[1192]="*Iti vivaṭena cetasā apariyonaddhena sappabhāsaṃ cittaṃ bhāveti.**And so, with an open and unenveloped heart, they develop a mind that’s full of radiance.*";
P_HTM[1193]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, samādhibhāvanā bhāvitā bahulīkatā ñāṇadassanappaṭilābhāya saṃvattati.**This is the way of developing immersion further that leads to gaining knowledge and vision.*";
P_HTM[1194]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, samādhibhāvanā bhāvitā bahulīkatā satisampajaññāya saṃvattati?**And what is the way of developing immersion further that leads to mindfulness and awareness?*";
P_HTM[1195]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno viditā vedanā uppajjanti, viditā upaṭṭhahanti, viditā abbhatthaṃ gacchanti;**It’s when a mendicant knows feelings as they arise, as they remain, and as they go away.*";
P_HTM[1196]="*viditā saññā … pe … viditā vitakkā uppajjanti, viditā upaṭṭhahanti, viditā abbhatthaṃ gacchanti.**They know perceptions as they arise, as they remain, and as they go away. They know thoughts as they arise, as they remain, and as they go away.*";
P_HTM[1197]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, samādhibhāvanā bhāvitā bahulīkatā satisampajaññāya saṃvattati.**This is the way of developing immersion further that leads to mindfulness and awareness.*";
P_HTM[1198]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, samādhibhāvanā bhāvitā bahulīkatā āsavānaṃ khayāya saṃvattati?**And what is the way of developing immersion further that leads to the ending of defilements?*";
P_HTM[1199]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu udayabbayānupassī viharati:**It’s when a mendicant meditates observing rise and fall in the five grasping aggregates.*";
P_HTM[1200]="*‘iti rūpaṃ, iti rūpassa samudayo, iti rūpassa atthaṅgamo;**‘Such is form, such is the origin of form, such is the ending of form.*";
P_HTM[1201]="*iti vedanā, iti vedanāya samudayo, iti vedanāya atthaṅgamo;**Such is feeling, such is the origin of feeling, such is the ending of feeling.*";
P_HTM[1202]="*iti saññā, iti saññāya samudayo, iti saññāya atthaṅgamo;**Such is perception, such is the origin of perception, such is the ending of perception.*";
P_HTM[1203]="*iti saṅkhārā, iti saṅkhārānaṃ samudayo, iti saṅkhārānaṃ atthaṅgamo;**Such are choices, such is the origin of choices, such is the ending of choices.*";
P_HTM[1204]="*iti viññāṇaṃ, iti viññāṇassa samudayo, iti viññāṇassa atthaṅgamo’ti.**Such is consciousness, such is the origin of consciousness, such is the ending of consciousness.’*";
P_HTM[1205]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, samādhibhāvanā bhāvitā bahulīkatā āsavānaṃ khayāya saṃvattati.**This is the way of developing immersion further that leads to the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[1206]="*Imā kho, bhikkhave, catasso samādhibhāvanā.**These are the four ways of developing immersion further.*";
P_HTM[1207]="*Idañca pana metaṃ, bhikkhave, sandhāya bhāsitaṃ pārāyane puṇṇakapañhe:**And it was in this connection that I said in ‘The Way to the Beyond’, in ‘The Questions of Puṇṇaka’:*";
P_HTM[1208]="*‘Saṅkhāya lokasmiṃ paroparāni,**‘Having surveyed the world high and low,*";
P_HTM[1209]="*Yassiñjitaṃ natthi kuhiñci loke;**they’re not shaken by anything in the world.*";
P_HTM[1210]="*Santo vidhūmo anīgho nirāso,**Peaceful, unclouded, untroubled, with no need for hope,*";
P_HTM[1211]="*Atāri so jātijaranti brūmī’”ti.**they’ve crossed over birth and old age, I declare.’”*";
P_HTM[1212]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1213]="*2. Pañhabyākaraṇasuttaṃ**Ways of Answering Questions*";
P_HTM[1214]="*“Cattārimāni, bhikkhave, pañhabyākaraṇāni.**“Mendicants, there are these four ways of answering questions.*";
P_HTM[1215]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1216]="*Atthi, bhikkhave, pañho ekaṃsabyākaraṇīyo;**There is a question that should be answered definitively.*";
P_HTM[1217]="*atthi, bhikkhave, pañho vibhajjabyākaraṇīyo;**There is a question that should be answered analytically.*";
P_HTM[1218]="*atthi, bhikkhave, pañho paṭipucchābyākaraṇīyo;**There is a question that should be answered with a counter-question.*";
P_HTM[1219]="*atthi, bhikkhave, pañho ṭhapanīyo.**There is a question that should be set aside.*";
P_HTM[1220]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, cattāri pañhabyākaraṇānīti.**These are the four ways of answering questions.*";
P_HTM[1221]="*Ekaṃsavacanaṃ ekaṃ,**One is stated definitively,*";
P_HTM[1222]="*vibhajjavacanāparaṃ;**another analytically,*";
P_HTM[1223]="*Tatiyaṃ paṭipuccheyya,**a third with a counter-question,*";
P_HTM[1224]="*catutthaṃ pana ṭhāpaye.**while a fourth is set aside.*";
P_HTM[1225]="*Yo ca tesaṃ tattha tattha,**A mendicant who knows each of these,*";
P_HTM[1226]="*jānāti anudhammataṃ;**in line with good principles,*";
P_HTM[1227]="*Catupañhassa kusalo,**is said to be skilled*";
P_HTM[1228]="*āhu bhikkhuṃ tathāvidhaṃ.**in the four kinds of questions.*";
P_HTM[1229]="*Durāsado duppasaho,**They’re intimidating, hard to defeat,*";
P_HTM[1230]="*gambhīro duppadhaṃsiyo;**deep, and hard to crush.*";
P_HTM[1231]="*Atho atthe anatthe ca,**They’re expert in both*";
P_HTM[1232]="*ubhayassa hoti kovido.**what the meaning is and what it isn’t.*";
P_HTM[1233]="*Anatthaṃ parivajjeti,**Rejecting what is not the meaning,*";
P_HTM[1234]="*atthaṃ gaṇhāti paṇḍito;**an astute person grasps the meaning.*";
P_HTM[1235]="*Atthābhisamayā dhīro,**A wise one, comprehending the meaning,*";
P_HTM[1236]="*paṇḍitoti pavuccatī”ti.**is called ‘astute’.”*";
P_HTM[1237]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1238]="*3. Paṭhamakodhagarusuttaṃ**Valuing Anger*";
P_HTM[1239]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, puggalā santo saṃvijjamānā lokasmiṃ.**“Mendicants, these four people are found in the world.*";
P_HTM[1240]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1241]="*Kodhagaru na saddhammagaru, makkhagaru na saddhammagaru, lābhagaru na saddhammagaru, sakkāragaru na saddhammagaru.**People who value anger, or denigration, or material possessions, or honor rather than the true teaching.*";
P_HTM[1242]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro puggalā santo saṃvijjamānā lokasmiṃ.**These are the four people found in the world.*";
P_HTM[1243]="*Cattārome, bhikkhave, puggalā santo saṃvijjamānā lokasmiṃ.**These four people are found in the world.*";
P_HTM[1244]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1245]="*Saddhammagaru na kodhagaru, saddhammagaru na makkhagaru, saddhammagaru na lābhagaru, saddhammagaru na sakkāragaru.**People who value the true teaching rather than anger, or denigration, or material possessions, or honor.*";
P_HTM[1246]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro puggalā santo saṃvijjamānā lokasminti.**These are the four people found in the world.*";
P_HTM[1247]="*Kodhamakkhagarū bhikkhū,**Mendicants who value anger and denigration,*";
P_HTM[1248]="*lābhasakkāragāravā;**possessions and honor,*";
P_HTM[1249]="*Na te dhamme virūhanti,**don’t grow in the teaching*";
P_HTM[1250]="*sammāsambuddhadesite.**that was taught by the perfected Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1251]="*Ye ca saddhammagaruno,**But those who value the true teaching,*";
P_HTM[1252]="*vihaṃsu viharanti ca;**who have lived it, and are living it now,*";
P_HTM[1253]="*Te ve dhamme virūhanti,**these do grow in the teaching*";
P_HTM[1254]="*sammāsambuddhadesite”ti.**that was taught by the perfected Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[1255]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1256]="*4. Dutiyakodhagarusuttaṃ**Valuing Anger (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1257]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, asaddhammā.**“Mendicants, these four things oppose the true teaching.*";
P_HTM[1258]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1259]="*Kodhagarutā na saddhammagarutā, makkhagarutā na saddhammagarutā, lābhagarutā na saddhammagarutā, sakkāragarutā na saddhammagarutā.**Valuing anger, denigration, material possessions, and honor rather than the true teaching.*";
P_HTM[1260]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro asaddhammā.**These are the four things that oppose the true teaching.*";
P_HTM[1261]="*Cattārome, bhikkhave, saddhammā.**These four things are the true teaching.*";
P_HTM[1262]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1263]="*Saddhammagarutā na kodhagarutā, saddhammagarutā na makkhagarutā, saddhammagarutā na lābhagarutā, saddhammagarutā na sakkāragarutā.**Valuing the true teaching rather than anger, denigration, material possessions, and honor.*";
P_HTM[1264]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro saddhammāti.**These are the four things that are the true teaching.*";
P_HTM[1265]="*Kodhamakkhagaru bhikkhu,**A mendicant who values anger and denigration,*";
P_HTM[1266]="*lābhasakkāragāravo;**possessions and honor,*";
P_HTM[1267]="*Sukhette pūtibījaṃva,**doesn’t grow in the true teaching,*";
P_HTM[1268]="*saddhamme na virūhati.**like a rotten seed in a good field.*";
P_HTM[1269]="*Ye ca saddhammagaruno,**But those who value the true teaching,*";
P_HTM[1270]="*vihaṃsu viharanti ca;**who have lived it, and are living it now,*";
P_HTM[1271]="*Te ve dhamme virūhanti,**these do grow in the teaching,*";
P_HTM[1272]="*snehānvayamivosadhā”ti.**like well-watered herbs.”*";
P_HTM[1273]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1274]="*5. Rohitassasuttaṃ**With Rohitassa*";
P_HTM[1275]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[1276]="*Atha kho rohitasso devaputto abhikkantāya rattiyā abhikkantavaṇṇo kevalakappaṃ jetavanaṃ obhāsetvā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhāsi. Ekamantaṃ ṭhito kho rohitasso devaputto bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then, late at night, the glorious god Rohitassa, lighting up the entire Jeta’s Grove, went up to the Buddha, bowed, stood to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[1277]="*“Yattha nu kho, bhante, na jāyati na jīyati na mīyati na cavati na upapajjati, sakkā nu kho so, bhante, gamanena lokassa anto ñātuṃ vā daṭṭhuṃ vā pāpuṇituṃ vā”ti?**“Sir, is it possible to know or see or reach the end of the world by traveling to a place where there’s no being born, growing old, dying, passing away, or being reborn?”*";
P_HTM[1278]="*“Yattha kho, āvuso, na jāyati na jīyati na mīyati na cavati na upapajjati, nāhaṃ taṃ gamanena lokassa antaṃ ñāteyyaṃ daṭṭheyyaṃ patteyyanti vadāmī”ti.**“Reverend, I say it’s not possible to know or see or reach the end of the world by traveling to a place where there’s no being born, growing old, dying, passing away, or being reborn.”*";
P_HTM[1279]="*“Acchariyaṃ, bhante, abbhutaṃ, bhante.**“It’s incredible, sir, it’s amazing,*";
P_HTM[1280]="*Yāva subhāsitamidaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā:**how well said this was by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1281]="*‘yattha kho, āvuso, na jāyati na jīyati na mīyati na cavati na upapajjati, nāhaṃ taṃ gamanena lokassa antaṃ ñāteyyaṃ daṭṭheyyaṃ patteyyanti vadāmī’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1282]="*“Bhūtapubbāhaṃ, bhante, rohitasso nāma isi ahosiṃ bhojaputto iddhimā vehāsaṅgamo.**Once upon a time, I was a hermit called Rohitassa, son of Bhoja. I was a sky-walker with psychic powers.*";
P_HTM[1283]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhante, evarūpo javo ahosi, seyyathāpi nāma daḷhadhammā dhanuggaho sikkhito katahattho katūpāsano lahukena asanena appakasirena tiriyaṃ tālacchāyaṃ atipāteyya.**I was as fast as a light arrow easily shot across the shadow of a palm tree by a well-trained expert archer with a strong bow.*";
P_HTM[1284]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhante, evarūpo padavītihāro ahosi, seyyathāpi nāma puratthimā samuddā pacchimo samuddo.**My stride was such that it could span from the eastern ocean to the western ocean.*";
P_HTM[1285]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhante, evarūpena javena samannāgatassa evarūpena ca padavītihārena evarūpaṃ icchāgataṃ uppajji:**Having such speed and stride, this wish came to me:*";
P_HTM[1286]="*‘ahaṃ gamanena lokassa antaṃ pāpuṇissāmī’ti.**‘I will reach the end of the world by traveling.’*";
P_HTM[1287]="*So kho ahaṃ, bhante, aññatreva asitapītakhāyitasāyitā aññatra uccārapassāvakammā aññatra niddākilamathapaṭivinodanā vassasatāyuko vassasatajīvī vassasataṃ gantvā appatvāva lokassa antaṃ antarāyeva kālaṅkato.**I traveled for my whole lifespan of a hundred years—pausing only to eat and drink, go to the toilet, and sleep to dispel weariness—and I passed away along the way, never reaching the end of the world.*";
P_HTM[1288]="*Acchariyaṃ, bhante, abbhutaṃ, bhante.**It’s incredible, sir, it’s amazing,*";
P_HTM[1289]="*Yāva subhāsitamidaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā:**how well said this was by the Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[1290]="*‘yattha kho, āvuso, na jāyati na jīyati na mīyati na cavati na upapajjati, nāhaṃ taṃ gamanena lokassa antaṃ ñāteyyaṃ daṭṭheyyaṃ patteyyanti vadāmī’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1291]="*“‘Yattha kho, āvuso, na jāyati na jīyati na mīyati na cavati na upapajjati, nāhaṃ taṃ gamanena lokassa antaṃ ñāteyyaṃ daṭṭheyyaṃ patteyyan’ti vadāmi.**“Reverend, I say it’s not possible to know or see or reach the end of the world by traveling to a place where there’s no being born, growing old, dying, passing away, or being reborn.*";
P_HTM[1292]="*Na cāhaṃ, āvuso, appatvāva lokassa antaṃ dukkhassa antakiriyaṃ vadāmi.**But I also say there’s no making an end of suffering without reaching the end of the world.*";
P_HTM[1293]="*Api cāhaṃ, āvuso, imasmiṃyeva byāmamatte kaḷevare sasaññimhi samanake lokañca paññāpemi lokasamudayañca lokanirodhañca lokanirodhagāminiñca paṭipadanti.**For it is in this fathom-long carcass with its perception and mind that I describe the world, its origin, its cessation, and the practice that leads to its cessation.*";
P_HTM[1294]="*Gamanena na pattabbo,**The end of the world can never*";
P_HTM[1295]="*lokassanto kudācanaṃ;**be reached by traveling.*";
P_HTM[1296]="*Na ca appatvā lokantaṃ,**But without reaching the end of the world,*";
P_HTM[1297]="*dukkhā atthi pamocanaṃ.**there’s no release from suffering.*";
P_HTM[1298]="*Tasmā have lokavidū sumedho,**So a clever person, understanding the world,*";
P_HTM[1299]="*Lokantagū vusitabrahmacariyo;**has completed the spiritual journey, and gone to the end of the world.*";
P_HTM[1300]="*Lokassa antaṃ samitāvi ñatvā,**A peaceful one, knowing the end of the world,*";
P_HTM[1301]="*Nāsīsatī lokamimaṃ parañcā”ti.**does not hope for this world or the next.”*";
P_HTM[1302]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1303]="*6. Dutiyarohitassasuttaṃ**With Rohitassa (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1304]="*Atha kho bhagavā tassā rattiyā accayena bhikkhū āmantesi:**Then, when the night had passed, the Buddha addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[1305]="*“imaṃ, bhikkhave, rattiṃ rohitasso devaputto abhikkantāya rattiyā abhikkantavaṇṇo kevalakappaṃ jetavanaṃ obhāsetvā yenāhaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā maṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhāsi. Ekamantaṃ ṭhito kho, bhikkhave, rohitasso devaputto maṃ etadavoca:**“Tonight, the glorious god Rohitassa, lighting up the entire Jeta’s Grove, came to me, bowed, stood to one side, and said to me:*";
P_HTM[1306]="*‘yattha nu kho, bhante, na jāyati na jīyati na mīyati na cavati na upapajjati, sakkā nu kho so, bhante, gamanena lokassa anto ñātuṃ vā daṭṭhuṃ vā pāpuṇituṃ vā’ti?**‘Sir, is it possible to know or see or reach the end of the world by traveling to a place where there’s no being born, growing old, dying, passing away, or being reborn?’ …*";
P_HTM[1307]="*Evaṃ vutte, ahaṃ, bhikkhave, rohitassaṃ devaputtaṃ etadavocaṃ:**(The rest of this discourse is the same as the previous discourse, AN 4.45.)*";
P_HTM[1308]="*‘yattha kho, āvuso, na jāyati na jīyati na mīyati na cavati na upapajjati, nāhaṃ taṃ gamanena lokassa antaṃ ñāteyyaṃ daṭṭheyyaṃ patteyyanti vadāmī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1309]="*Evaṃ vutte, bhikkhave, rohitasso devaputto maṃ etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[1310]="*‘acchariyaṃ, bhante, abbhutaṃ, bhante.* **";
P_HTM[1311]="*Yāva subhāsitamidaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā—* **";
P_HTM[1312]="*yattha kho, āvuso, na jāyati na jīyati na mīyati na cavati na upapajjati, nāhaṃ taṃ gamanena lokassa antaṃ ñāteyyaṃ daṭṭheyyaṃ patteyyanti vadāmi’.* **";
P_HTM[1313]="*Bhūtapubbāhaṃ, bhante, rohitasso nāma isi ahosiṃ bhojaputto iddhimā vehāsaṅgamo.* **";
P_HTM[1314]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhante, evarūpo javo ahosi, seyyathāpi nāma daḷhadhammā dhanuggaho sikkhito katahattho katūpāsano lahukena asanena appakasirena tiriyaṃ tālacchāyaṃ atipāteyya.* **";
P_HTM[1315]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhante, evarūpo padavītihāro ahosi, seyyathāpi nāma puratthimā samuddā pacchimo samuddo.* **";
P_HTM[1316]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhante, evarūpena javena samannāgatassa evarūpena ca padavītihārena evarūpaṃ icchāgataṃ uppajji:* **";
P_HTM[1317]="*‘ahaṃ gamanena lokassa antaṃ pāpuṇissāmī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1318]="*So kho ahaṃ, bhante, aññatreva asitapītakhāyitasāyitā aññatra uccārapassāvakammā aññatra niddākilamathapaṭivinodanā vassasatāyuko vassasatajīvī vassasataṃ gantvā appatvāva lokassa antaṃ antarāyeva kālaṅkato.* **";
P_HTM[1319]="*Acchariyaṃ, bhante, abbhutaṃ, bhante.* **";
P_HTM[1320]="*Yāva subhāsitamidaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā:* **";
P_HTM[1321]="*‘yattha kho, āvuso, na jāyati na jīyati na mīyati na cavati na upapajjati, nāhaṃ taṃ gamanena lokassa antaṃ ñāteyyaṃ daṭṭheyyaṃ patteyyanti vadāmī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1322]="*Evaṃ vutte, ahaṃ, bhikkhave, rohitassaṃ devaputtaṃ etadavocaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[1323]="*‘Yattha kho, āvuso, na jāyati na jīyati na mīyati na cavati na upapajjati, nāhaṃ, taṃ gamanena lokassa antaṃ ñāteyyaṃ daṭṭheyyaṃ patteyyanti vadāmī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1324]="*Na cāhaṃ, āvuso, appatvāva lokassa antaṃ dukkhassantakiriyaṃ vadāmi.* **";
P_HTM[1325]="*Api cāhaṃ, āvuso, imasmiṃyeva byāmamatte kaḷevare sasaññimhi samanake lokañca paññāpemi lokasamudayañca lokanirodhañca lokanirodhagāminiñca paṭipadanti.* **";
P_HTM[1326]="*Gamanena na pattabbo,* **";
P_HTM[1327]="*lokassanto kudācanaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[1328]="*Na ca appatvā lokantaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[1329]="*dukkhā atthi pamocanaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1330]="*Tasmā have lokavidū sumedho,* **";
P_HTM[1331]="*Lokantagū vusitabrahmacariyo;* **";
P_HTM[1332]="*Lokassa antaṃ samitāvi ñatvā,* **";
P_HTM[1333]="*Nāsīsatī lokamimaṃ parañcā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1334]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1335]="*7. Suvidūrasuttaṃ**Very Far Apart*";
P_HTM[1336]="*“Cattārimāni, bhikkhave, suvidūravidūrāni.**“Mendicants, these four things are very far apart.*";
P_HTM[1337]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1338]="*Nabhañca, bhikkhave, pathavī ca;**The sky and the earth. …*";
P_HTM[1339]="*idaṃ paṭhamaṃ suvidūravidūre.* **";
P_HTM[1340]="*Orimañca, bhikkhave, tīraṃ samuddassa pārimañca;**The near and the far shore of the ocean. …*";
P_HTM[1341]="*idaṃ dutiyaṃ suvidūravidūre.* **";
P_HTM[1342]="*Yato ca, bhikkhave, verocano abbhudeti yattha ca atthameti;**Where the sun rises and where it sets. …*";
P_HTM[1343]="*idaṃ tatiyaṃ suvidūravidūre.* **";
P_HTM[1344]="*Satañca, bhikkhave, dhammo asatañca dhammo;**The teaching of the virtuous and the teaching of the wicked. …*";
P_HTM[1345]="*idaṃ catutthaṃ suvidūravidūre.* **";
P_HTM[1346]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, cattāri suvidūravidūrānīti.**These are the four things very far apart.*";
P_HTM[1347]="*Nabhañca dūre pathavī ca dūre,**The sky is far from the earth;*";
P_HTM[1348]="*Pāraṃ samuddassa tadāhu dūre;**they say the other shore of the ocean is far;*";
P_HTM[1349]="*Yato ca verocano abbhudeti,**and where the sun rises is far*";
P_HTM[1350]="*Pabhaṅkaro yattha ca atthameti;**from where that shining one sets.*";
P_HTM[1351]="*Tato have dūrataraṃ vadanti,**But even further apart than that, they say,*";
P_HTM[1352]="*Satañca dhammaṃ asatañca dhammaṃ.**is the teaching of the virtuous from the wicked.*";
P_HTM[1353]="*Abyāyiko hoti sataṃ samāgamo,**The company of the virtuous is reliable;*";
P_HTM[1354]="*Yāvāpi tiṭṭheyya tatheva hoti;**as long as it remains, it stays the same.*";
P_HTM[1355]="*Khippañhi veti asataṃ samāgamo,**But the company of the wicked is fickle,*";
P_HTM[1356]="*Tasmā sataṃ dhammo asabbhi ārakā”ti.**and so the teaching of the virtuous is far from the wicked.”*";
P_HTM[1357]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1358]="*8. Visākhasuttaṃ**With Visākha*";
P_HTM[1359]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[1360]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā visākho pañcālaputto upaṭṭhānasālāyaṃ bhikkhū dhammiyā kathāya sandasseti samādapeti samuttejeti sampahaṃseti, poriyā vācāya vissaṭṭhāya anelagalāya atthassa viññāpaniyā pariyāpannāya anissitāya.**Now at that time Venerable Visākha, Pañcāli’s son, was educating, encouraging, firing up, and inspiring the mendicants in the assembly hall with a Dhamma talk. His words were polished, clear, articulate, expressing the meaning, comprehensive, and independent.*";
P_HTM[1361]="*Atha kho bhagavā sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhito yena upaṭṭhānasālā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi.**Then in the late afternoon, the Buddha came out of retreat and went to the assembly hall. He sat down on the seat spread out,*";
P_HTM[1362]="*Nisajja kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**and addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[1363]="*“Ko nu kho, bhikkhave, upaṭṭhānasālāyaṃ bhikkhū dhammiyā kathāya sandasseti samādapeti samuttejeti sampahaṃseti poriyā vācāya vissaṭṭhāya anelagalāya atthassa viññāpaniyā pariyāpannāya anissitāyā”ti?**“Mendicants, who was educating, encouraging, firing up, and inspiring the mendicants in the assembly hall with a Dhamma talk?”*";
P_HTM[1364]="*“Āyasmā, bhante, visākho pañcālaputto upaṭṭhānasālāyaṃ bhikkhū dhammiyā kathāya sandasseti samādapeti samuttejeti sampahaṃseti poriyā vācāya vissaṭṭhāya anelagalāya atthassa viññāpaniyā pariyāpannāya anissitāyā”ti.**“Sir, it was Venerable Visākha, Pañcāli’s son.”*";
P_HTM[1365]="*Atha kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ visākhaṃ pañcālaputtaṃ etadavoca:**Then the Buddha said to Visākha,*";
P_HTM[1366]="*“sādhu sādhu, visākha.**“Good, good, Visākha!*";
P_HTM[1367]="*Sādhu kho tvaṃ, visākha, bhikkhū dhammiyā kathāya sandassesi samādapesi samuttejesi sampahaṃsesi poriyā vācāya vissaṭṭhāya anelagalāya atthassa viññāpaniyā pariyāpannāya anissitāyāti.**It’s good that you educate, encourage, fire up, and inspire the mendicants in the assembly hall with a Dhamma talk, with words that are polished, clear, articulate, expressing the meaning, comprehensive, and independent.*";
P_HTM[1368]="*Nābhāsamānaṃ jānanti,**Though an astute person is mixed up with fools,*";
P_HTM[1369]="*missaṃ bālehi paṇḍitaṃ;**they don’t know unless he speaks.*";
P_HTM[1370]="*Bhāsamānañca jānanti,**But when he speaks they know,*";
P_HTM[1371]="*desentaṃ amataṃ padaṃ.**he’s teaching the deathless state.*";
P_HTM[1372]="*Bhāsaye jotaye dhammaṃ,**He should speak and illustrate the teaching,*";
P_HTM[1373]="*paggaṇhe isinaṃ dhajaṃ;**holding up the banner of the hermits.*";
P_HTM[1374]="*Subhāsitadhajā isayo,**Words well spoken are the hermits’ banner,*";
P_HTM[1375]="*dhammo hi isinaṃ dhajo”ti.**for the teaching is the banner of the hermits.”*";
P_HTM[1376]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1377]="*9. Vipallāsasuttaṃ**Perversions*";
P_HTM[1378]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, saññāvipallāsā cittavipallāsā diṭṭhivipallāsā.**“Mendicants, there are these four perversions of perception, mind, and view.*";
P_HTM[1379]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1380]="*Anicce, bhikkhave, niccanti saññāvipallāso cittavipallāso diṭṭhivipallāso;**Taking impermanence as permanence.*";
P_HTM[1381]="*dukkhe, bhikkhave, sukhanti saññāvipallāso cittavipallāso diṭṭhivipallāso;**Taking suffering as happiness.*";
P_HTM[1382]="*anattani, bhikkhave, attāti saññāvipallāso cittavipallāso diṭṭhivipallāso;**Taking not-self as self.*";
P_HTM[1383]="*asubhe, bhikkhave, subhanti saññāvipallāso cittavipallāso diṭṭhivipallāso.**Taking ugliness as beauty.*";
P_HTM[1384]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro saññāvipallāsā cittavipallāsā diṭṭhivipallāsā.**These are the four perversions of perception, mind, and view.*";
P_HTM[1385]="*Cattārome, bhikkhave, nasaññāvipallāsā nacittavipallāsā nadiṭṭhivipallāsā.**There are these four corrections of perception, mind, and view.*";
P_HTM[1386]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1387]="*Anicce, bhikkhave, aniccanti nasaññāvipallāso nacittavipallāso nadiṭṭhivipallāso;**Taking impermanence as impermanence.*";
P_HTM[1388]="*dukkhe, bhikkhave, dukkhanti nasaññāvipallāso nacittavipallāso nadiṭṭhivipallāso;**Taking suffering as suffering.*";
P_HTM[1389]="*anattani, bhikkhave, anattāti nasaññāvipallāso nacittavipallāso nadiṭṭhivipallāso;**Taking not-self as not-self.*";
P_HTM[1390]="*asubhe, bhikkhave, asubhanti nasaññāvipallāso nacittavipallāso nadiṭṭhivipallāso.**Taking ugliness as ugliness.*";
P_HTM[1391]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro nasaññāvipallāsā nacittavipallāsā nadiṭṭhivipallāsāti.**These are the four corrections of perception, mind, and view.*";
P_HTM[1392]="*Anicce niccasaññino,**Perceiving impermanence as permanence,*";
P_HTM[1393]="*dukkhe ca sukhasaññino;**suffering as happiness,*";
P_HTM[1394]="*Anattani ca attāti,**not-self as self,*";
P_HTM[1395]="*asubhe subhasaññino;**and ugliness as beauty—*";
P_HTM[1396]="*Micchādiṭṭhihatā sattā,**sentient beings are ruined by wrong view,*";
P_HTM[1397]="*khittacittā visaññino.**deranged, out of their mind.*";
P_HTM[1398]="*Te yogayuttā mārassa,**Yoked by Māra’s yoke, these people*";
P_HTM[1399]="*ayogakkhemino janā;**find no sanctuary from the yoke.*";
P_HTM[1400]="*Sattā gacchanti saṃsāraṃ,**Sentient beings continue to transmigrate,*";
P_HTM[1401]="*jātimaraṇagāmino.**with ongoing birth and death.*";
P_HTM[1402]="*Yadā ca buddhā lokasmiṃ,**But when the Buddhas arise in the world,*";
P_HTM[1403]="*Uppajjanti pabhaṅkarā;**shedding radiance,*";
P_HTM[1404]="*Te imaṃ dhammaṃ pakāsenti,**they shine a light on this teaching,*";
P_HTM[1405]="*Dukkhūpasamagāminaṃ.**that leads to the stilling of suffering.*";
P_HTM[1406]="*Tesaṃ sutvāna sappaññā,**When a wise person hears them,*";
P_HTM[1407]="*sacittaṃ paccaladdhā te;**they get their mind back.*";
P_HTM[1408]="*Aniccaṃ aniccato dakkhuṃ,**Seeing impermanence as impermanence,*";
P_HTM[1409]="*dukkhamaddakkhu dukkhato.**suffering as suffering,*";
P_HTM[1410]="*Anattani anattāti,**not-self as not-self,*";
P_HTM[1411]="*asubhaṃ asubhataddasuṃ;**and ugliness as ugliness—*";
P_HTM[1412]="*Sammādiṭṭhisamādānā,**taking up right view,*";
P_HTM[1413]="*sabbaṃ dukkhaṃ upaccagun”ti.**they’ve risen above all suffering.”*";
P_HTM[1414]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1415]="*10. Upakkilesasuttaṃ**Corruptions*";
P_HTM[1416]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, candimasūriyānaṃ upakkilesā, yehi upakkilesehi upakkiliṭṭhā candimasūriyā na tapanti na bhāsanti na virocanti.**“Mendicants, these four corruptions obscure the sun and moon, so they don’t shine and glow and radiate.*";
P_HTM[1417]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1418]="*Abbhā, bhikkhave, candimasūriyānaṃ upakkilesā, yena upakkilesena upakkiliṭṭhā candimasūriyā na tapanti na bhāsanti na virocanti.**Clouds …*";
P_HTM[1419]="*Mahikā, bhikkhave, candimasūriyānaṃ upakkilesā, yena upakkilesena upakkiliṭṭhā candimasūriyā na tapanti na bhāsanti na virocanti.**Fog …*";
P_HTM[1420]="*Dhūmo rajo, bhikkhave, candimasūriyānaṃ upakkileso, yena upakkilesena upakkiliṭṭhā candimasūriyā na tapanti na bhāsanti na virocanti.**Smoke …*";
P_HTM[1421]="*Rāhu, bhikkhave, asurindo candimasūriyānaṃ upakkileso, yena upakkilesena upakkiliṭṭhā candimasūriyā na tapanti na bhāsanti na virocanti.**An eclipse of Rāhu, lord of demons …*";
P_HTM[1422]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro candimasūriyānaṃ upakkilesā, yehi upakkilesehi upakkiliṭṭhā candimasūriyā na tapanti na bhāsanti na virocanti.**These are four corruptions that obscure the sun and moon, so they don’t shine and glow and radiate.*";
P_HTM[1423]="*Evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, cattārome samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ upakkilesā, yehi upakkilesehi upakkiliṭṭhā eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā na tapanti na bhāsanti na virocanti.**In the same way, these four things corrupt ascetics and brahmins, so they don’t shine and glow and radiate.*";
P_HTM[1424]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1425]="*Santi, bhikkhave, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā suraṃ pivanti merayaṃ, surāmerayapānā appaṭiviratā.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who drink liquor, not avoiding drinking liquor.*";
P_HTM[1426]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, paṭhamo samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ upakkileso, yena upakkilesena upakkiliṭṭhā eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā na tapanti na bhāsanti na virocanti.**This is the first thing that corrupts ascetics and brahmins …*";
P_HTM[1427]="*Santi, bhikkhave, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā methunaṃ dhammaṃ paṭisevanti, methunasmā dhammā appaṭiviratā.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who have sex, not avoiding sex.*";
P_HTM[1428]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, dutiyo samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ upakkileso, yena upakkilesena upakkiliṭṭhā eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā na tapanti na bhāsanti na virocanti.**This is the second thing that corrupts ascetics and brahmins …*";
P_HTM[1429]="*Santi, bhikkhave, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā jātarūparajataṃ sādiyanti, jātarūparajatapaṭiggahaṇā appaṭiviratā.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who accept gold and money, not avoiding receiving gold and money.*";
P_HTM[1430]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, tatiyo samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ upakkileso, yena upakkilesena upakkiliṭṭhā eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā na tapanti na bhāsanti na virocanti.**This is the third thing that corrupts ascetics and brahmins …*";
P_HTM[1431]="*Santi, bhikkhave, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā micchājīvena jīvanti, micchājīvā appaṭiviratā.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who make a living the wrong way, not avoiding wrong livelihood.*";
P_HTM[1432]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, catuttho samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ upakkileso, yena upakkilesena upakkiliṭṭhā eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā na tapanti na bhāsanti na virocanti.**This is the fourth thing that corrupts ascetics and brahmins …*";
P_HTM[1433]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ upakkilesā, yehi upakkilesehi upakkiliṭṭhā eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā na tapanti na bhāsanti na virocantīti.**These are four things that corrupt ascetics and brahmins, so they don’t shine and glow and radiate.*";
P_HTM[1434]="*Rāgadosaparikkiṭṭhā,**Some ascetics and brahmins*";
P_HTM[1435]="*eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā;**are plagued by greed and hate;*";
P_HTM[1436]="*Avijjānivutā posā,**men hindered by ignorance,*";
P_HTM[1437]="*piyarūpābhinandino.**enjoying things that seem pleasant.*";
P_HTM[1438]="*Suraṃ pivanti merayaṃ,**Drinking liquor,*";
P_HTM[1439]="*paṭisevanti methunaṃ;**having sex,*";
P_HTM[1440]="*Rajataṃ jātarūpañca,**accepting money and gold:*";
P_HTM[1441]="*sādiyanti aviddasū;**they’re ignorant.*";
P_HTM[1442]="*Micchājīvena jīvanti,**Some ascetics and brahmins*";
P_HTM[1443]="*eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā.**make a living the wrong way.*";
P_HTM[1444]="*Ete upakkilesā vuttā,**These corruptions were spoken of*";
P_HTM[1445]="*buddhenādiccabandhunā;**by the Buddha, Kinsman of the Sun.*";
P_HTM[1446]="*Yehi upakkilesehi,**When corrupted by these,*";
P_HTM[1447]="*eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā;**some ascetics and brahmins*";
P_HTM[1448]="*Na tapanti na bhāsanti,**don’t shine or glow.*";
P_HTM[1449]="*asuddhā sarajā magā.**Impure, dirty creatures,*";
P_HTM[1450]="*Andhakārena onaddhā,**shrouded in darkness,*";
P_HTM[1451]="*taṇhādāsā sanettikā;**bondservants of craving, full of attachments,*";
P_HTM[1452]="*Vaḍḍhenti kaṭasiṃ ghoraṃ,**swell the horrors of the charnel ground,*";
P_HTM[1453]="*ādiyanti punabbhavan”ti.**taking up future lives.*";
P_HTM[1454]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1455]="*Rohitassavaggo pañcamo.* **";
P_HTM[1456]="*Samādhipañhā dve kodhā,* **";
P_HTM[1457]="*Rohitassāpare duve;* **";
P_HTM[1458]="*Suvidūravisākhavipallāsā,* **";
P_HTM[1459]="*Upakkilesena te dasāti.* **";
P_HTM[1460]="*Paṭhamo paṇṇāsako samatto.* **";
P_HTM[1461]="*3____31-510. Dosaabhiññādisuttāni**Overflowing Merit*";
P_HTM[1462]="*1. Paṭhamapuññābhisandasuttaṃ**Overflowing Merit*";
P_HTM[1463]="*Sāvatthinidānaṃ.**At Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[1464]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, puññābhisandā kusalābhisandā sukhassāhārā sovaggikā sukhavipākā saggasaṃvattanikā iṭṭhāya kantāya manāpāya hitāya sukhāya saṃvattanti.**“Mendicants, there are these four kinds of overflowing merit, overflowing goodness. They nurture happiness and are conducive to heaven, ripening in happiness and leading to heaven. They lead to what is likable, desirable, agreeable, to welfare and happiness.*";
P_HTM[1465]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1466]="*Yassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhu cīvaraṃ paribhuñjamāno appamāṇaṃ cetosamādhiṃ upasampajja viharati, appamāṇo tassa puññābhisando kusalābhisando sukhassāhāro sovaggiko sukhavipāko saggasaṃvattaniko iṭṭhāya kantāya manāpāya hitāya sukhāya saṃvattati.**When a mendicant enters and remains in a limitless immersion of heart while using a robe, the overflowing of merit for the donor is limitless …*";
P_HTM[1467]="*Yassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhu piṇḍapātaṃ paribhuñjamāno appamāṇaṃ cetosamādhiṃ upasampajja viharati, appamāṇo tassa puññābhisando kusalābhisando sukhassāhāro sovaggiko sukhavipāko saggasaṃvattaniko iṭṭhāya kantāya manāpāya hitāya sukhāya saṃvattati.**When a mendicant enters and remains in a limitless immersion of heart while eating alms-food, the overflowing of merit for the donor is limitless …*";
P_HTM[1468]="*Yassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhu senāsanaṃ paribhuñjamāno appamāṇaṃ cetosamādhiṃ upasampajja viharati, appamāṇo tassa puññābhisando kusalābhisando sukhassāhāro sovaggiko sukhavipāko saggasaṃvattaniko iṭṭhāya kantāya manāpāya hitāya sukhāya saṃvattati.**When a mendicant enters and remains in a limitless immersion of heart while using lodgings, the overflowing of merit for the donor is limitless …*";
P_HTM[1469]="*Yassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhu gilānappaccayabhesajjaparikkhāraṃ paribhuñjamāno appamāṇaṃ cetosamādhiṃ upasampajja viharati, appamāṇo tassa puññābhisando kusalābhisando sukhassāhāro sovaggiko sukhavipāko saggasaṃvattaniko iṭṭhāya kantāya manāpāya hitāya sukhāya saṃvattati.**When a mendicant enters and remains in a limitless immersion of heart while using medicines and supplies for the sick, the overflowing of merit for the donor is limitless …*";
P_HTM[1470]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro puññābhisandā kusalābhisandā sukhassāhārā sovaggikā sukhavipākā saggasaṃvattanikā iṭṭhāya kantāya manāpāya hitāya sukhāya saṃvattanti.**These are the four kinds of overflowing merit, overflowing goodness. They nurture happiness and are conducive to heaven, ripening in happiness and leading to heaven. They lead to what is likable, desirable, agreeable, to welfare and happiness.*";
P_HTM[1471]="*Imehi ca pana, bhikkhave, catūhi puññābhisandehi kusalābhisandehi samannāgatassa ariyasāvakassa na sukaraṃ puññassa pamāṇaṃ gahetuṃ: ‘ettako puññābhisando kusalābhisando sukhassāhāro sovaggiko sukhavipāko saggasaṃvattaniko iṭṭhāya kantāya manāpāya hitāya sukhāya saṃvattatī’ti. Atha kho asaṅkhyeyyo appameyyo mahāpuññakkhandhotveva saṅkhyaṃ gacchati.**When a noble disciple has these four kinds of overflowing merit and goodness, it’s not easy to grasp how much merit they have by saying that this is the extent of their overflowing merit … that leads to happiness. It’s simply reckoned as an incalculable, immeasurable, great mass of merit.*";
P_HTM[1472]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, mahāsamudde na sukaraṃ udakassa pamāṇaṃ gahetuṃ: ‘ettakāni udakāḷhakānīti vā, ettakāni udakāḷhakasatānīti vā, ettakāni udakāḷhakasahassānīti vā, ettakāni udakāḷhakasatasahassānīti vā’, atha kho asaṅkhyeyyo appameyyo mahāudakakkhandhotveva saṅkhyaṃ gacchati;**It’s like trying to grasp how much water is in the ocean. It’s not easy to say how many gallons, how many hundreds, thousands, hundreds of thousands of gallons there are. It’s simply reckoned as an incalculable, immeasurable, great mass of water.*";
P_HTM[1473]="*evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, imehi catūhi puññābhisandehi kusalābhisandehi samannāgatassa ariyasāvakassa na sukaraṃ puññassa pamāṇaṃ gahetuṃ: ‘ettako puññābhisando kusalābhisando sukhassāhāro sovaggiko sukhavipāko saggasaṃvattaniko iṭṭhāya kantāya manāpāya hitāya sukhāya saṃvattatī’ti. Atha kho asaṅkhyeyyo appameyyo mahāpuññakkhandhotveva saṅkhyaṃ gacchatīti.**In the same way, when a noble disciple has these four kinds of overflowing merit it’s simply reckoned as an incalculable, immeasurable, great mass of merit.*";
P_HTM[1474]="*Mahodadhiṃ aparimitaṃ mahāsaraṃ,**Hosts of people use the rivers,*";
P_HTM[1475]="*Bahubheravaṃ ratanavarānamālayaṃ;**and though the rivers are many,*";
P_HTM[1476]="*Najjo yathā naragaṇasaṅghasevitā,**all reach the great deep, the boundless ocean,*";
P_HTM[1477]="*Puthū savantī upayanti sāgaraṃ.**the cruel sea that’s home to precious gems.*";
P_HTM[1478]="*Evaṃ naraṃ annadapānavatthadaṃ,**In the same way, when a person gives food, drink, and clothes;*";
P_HTM[1479]="*Seyyānisajjattharaṇassa dāyakaṃ;**and they’re a giver of beds, seats, and mats—*";
P_HTM[1480]="*Puññassa dhārā upayanti paṇḍitaṃ,**the streams of merit reach that astute person,*";
P_HTM[1481]="*Najjo yathā vārivahāva sāgaran”ti.**as the rivers bring their waters to the sea.”*";
P_HTM[1482]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1483]="*2. Dutiyapuññābhisandasuttaṃ**Overflowing Merit (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1484]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, puññābhisandā kusalābhisandā sukhassāhārā sovaggikā sukhavipākā saggasaṃvattanikā iṭṭhāya kantāya manāpāya hitāya sukhāya saṃvattanti.**“Mendicants, there are these four kinds of overflowing merit, overflowing goodness. They nurture happiness and are conducive to heaven, ripening in happiness and leading to heaven. They lead to what is likable, desirable, agreeable, to welfare and happiness.*";
P_HTM[1485]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1486]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti:**It’s when a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[1487]="*‘itipi so bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā’ti.**‘That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’*";
P_HTM[1488]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, paṭhamo puññābhisando kusalābhisando sukhassāhāro sovaggiko sukhavipāko saggasaṃvattaniko iṭṭhāya kantāya manāpāya hitāya sukhāya saṃvattati.**This is the first kind of overflowing merit …*";
P_HTM[1489]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako dhamme aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti:**Furthermore, a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the teaching:*";
P_HTM[1490]="*‘svākkhāto bhagavatā dhammo sandiṭṭhiko akāliko ehipassiko opaneyyiko paccattaṃ veditabbo viññūhī’ti.**‘The teaching is well explained by the Buddha—visible in this very life, immediately effective, inviting inspection, relevant, so that sensible people can know it for themselves.’*";
P_HTM[1491]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, dutiyo puññābhisando kusalābhisando sukhassāhāro sovaggiko sukhavipāko saggasaṃvattaniko iṭṭhāya kantāya manāpāya hitāya sukhāya saṃvattati.**This is the second kind of overflowing merit …*";
P_HTM[1492]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako saṅghe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti:**Furthermore, a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Saṅgha:*";
P_HTM[1493]="*‘suppaṭipanno bhagavato sāvakasaṅgho, ujuppaṭipanno bhagavato sāvakasaṅgho, ñāyappaṭipanno bhagavato sāvakasaṅgho, sāmīcippaṭipanno bhagavato sāvakasaṅgho, yadidaṃ cattāri purisayugāni aṭṭha purisapuggalā, esa bhagavato sāvakasaṅgho āhuneyyo pāhuneyyo dakkhiṇeyyo añjalikaraṇīyo anuttaraṃ puññakkhettaṃ lokassā’ti.**‘The Saṅgha of the Buddha’s disciples is practicing the way that’s good, straightforward, methodical, and proper. It consists of the four pairs, the eight individuals. This is the Saṅgha of the Buddha’s disciples that is worthy of offerings dedicated to the gods, worthy of hospitality, worthy of a religious donation, worthy of greeting with joined palms, and is the supreme field of merit for the world.’*";
P_HTM[1494]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, tatiyo puññābhisando kusalābhisando sukhassāhāro sovaggiko sukhavipāko saggasaṃvattaniko iṭṭhāya kantāya manāpāya hitāya sukhāya saṃvattati.**This is the third kind of overflowing merit …*";
P_HTM[1495]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgato hoti akhaṇḍehi acchiddehi asabalehi akammāsehi bhujissehi viññuppasatthehi aparāmaṭṭhehi samādhisaṃvattanikehi.**Furthermore, a noble disciple’s ethical conduct is loved by the noble ones, unbroken, impeccable, spotless, and unmarred, liberating, praised by sensible people, not mistaken, and leading to immersion.*";
P_HTM[1496]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, catuttho puññābhisando kusalābhisando sukhassāhāro sovaggiko sukhavipāko saggasaṃvattaniko iṭṭhāya kantāya manāpāya hitāya sukhāya saṃvattati.**This is the fourth kind of overflowing merit …*";
P_HTM[1497]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro puññābhisandā kusalābhisandā sukhassāhārā sovaggikā sukhavipākā saggasaṃvattanikā iṭṭhāya kantāya manāpāya hitāya sukhāya saṃvattantīti.**These are the four kinds of overflowing merit, overflowing goodness. They nurture happiness and are conducive to heaven, ripening in happiness and leading to heaven. They lead to what is likable, desirable, agreeable, to welfare and happiness.*";
P_HTM[1498]="*Yassa saddhā tathāgate,**Whoever has faith in the Realized One,*";
P_HTM[1499]="*acalā suppatiṭṭhitā;**unwavering and well grounded;*";
P_HTM[1500]="*Sīlañca yassa kalyāṇaṃ,**whose ethical conduct is good,*";
P_HTM[1501]="*ariyakantaṃ pasaṃsitaṃ.**praised and loved by the noble ones;*";
P_HTM[1502]="*Saṅghe pasādo yassatthi,**who has confidence in the Saṅgha,*";
P_HTM[1503]="*ujubhūtañca dassanaṃ;**and correct view:*";
P_HTM[1504]="*Adaliddoti taṃ āhu,**they’re said to be prosperous,*";
P_HTM[1505]="*amoghaṃ tassa jīvitaṃ.**their life is not in vain.*";
P_HTM[1506]="*Tasmā saddhañca sīlañca,**So let the wise devote themselves*";
P_HTM[1507]="*pasādaṃ dhammadassanaṃ;**to faith, ethical behavior,*";
P_HTM[1508]="*Anuyuñjetha medhāvī,**confidence, and insight into the teaching,*";
P_HTM[1509]="*saraṃ buddhāna sāsanan”ti.**remembering the instructions of the Buddhas.*";
P_HTM[1510]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1511]="*3. Paṭhamasaṃvāsasuttaṃ**Living Together (1st)*";
P_HTM[1512]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā antarā ca madhuraṃ antarā ca verañjaṃ addhānamaggappaṭipanno hoti.**At one time the Buddha was traveling along the road between Madhura and Verañja,*";
P_HTM[1513]="*Sambahulāpi kho gahapatī ca gahapatāniyo ca antarā ca madhuraṃ antarā ca verañjaṃ addhānamaggappaṭipannā honti.**as were several householders, both women and men.*";
P_HTM[1514]="*Atha kho bhagavā maggā okkamma aññatarasmiṃ rukkhamūle () nisīdi.**The Buddha left the road and sat at the root of a tree,*";
P_HTM[1515]="*Addasaṃsu kho gahapatī ca gahapatāniyo ca bhagavantaṃ aññatarasmiṃ rukkhamūle nisinnaṃ.**where the householders saw him.*";
P_HTM[1516]="*Disvā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinne kho te gahapatī ca gahapatāniyo ca bhagavā etadavoca:**They went up to the Buddha, bowed, and sat down to one side. The Buddha said to them:*";
P_HTM[1517]="*“Cattārome, gahapatayo, saṃvāsā.**“Householders, there are four ways of living together.*";
P_HTM[1518]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1519]="*Chavo chavāya saddhiṃ saṃvasati, chavo deviyā saddhiṃ saṃvasati, devo chavāya saddhiṃ saṃvasati, devo deviyā saddhiṃ saṃvasati.**~A male zombie living with a female zombie; ~a male zombie living with a goddess; ~a god living with a female zombie; ~a god living with a goddess.*";
P_HTM[1520]="*Kathañca, gahapatayo, chavo chavāya saddhiṃ saṃvasati?**And how does a male zombie live with a female zombie?*";
P_HTM[1521]="*Idha, gahapatayo, sāmiko hoti pāṇātipātī adinnādāyī kāmesumicchācārī musāvādī surāmerayamajjapamādaṭṭhāyī dussīlo pāpadhammo maccheramalapariyuṭṭhitena cetasā agāraṃ ajjhāvasati akkosakaparibhāsako samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ;**It’s when the husband kills living creatures, steals, commits sexual misconduct, lies, and uses alcoholic drinks that cause negligence. He’s unethical, of bad character, living at home with his heart full of the stain of stinginess, abusing and insulting ascetics and brahmins.*";
P_HTM[1522]="*bhariyāpissa hoti pāṇātipātinī adinnādāyinī kāmesumicchācārinī musāvādinī surāmerayamajjapamādaṭṭhāyinī dussīlā pāpadhammā maccheramalapariyuṭṭhitena cetasā agāraṃ ajjhāvasati akkosikaparibhāsikā samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ.**And the wife is also … unethical, of bad character …*";
P_HTM[1523]="*Evaṃ kho, gahapatayo, chavo chavāya saddhiṃ saṃvasati.**That’s how a male zombie lives with a female zombie.*";
P_HTM[1524]="*Kathañca, gahapatayo, chavo deviyā saddhiṃ saṃvasati?**And how does a male zombie live with a goddess?*";
P_HTM[1525]="*Idha, gahapatayo, sāmiko hoti pāṇātipātī adinnādāyī kāmesumicchācārī musāvādī surāmerayamajjapamādaṭṭhāyī dussīlo pāpadhammo maccheramalapariyuṭṭhitena cetasā agāraṃ ajjhāvasati akkosakaparibhāsako samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ;**It’s when the husband … is unethical, of bad character …*";
P_HTM[1526]="*bhariyā khvassa hoti pāṇātipātā paṭiviratā adinnādānā paṭiviratā kāmesumicchācārā paṭiviratā musāvādā paṭiviratā surāmerayamajjapamādaṭṭhānā paṭiviratā sīlavatī kalyāṇadhammā vigatamalamaccherena cetasā agāraṃ ajjhāvasati anakkosikaparibhāsikā samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ.**But the wife doesn’t kill living creatures, steal, commit sexual misconduct, lie, or use alcoholic drinks that cause negligence. She’s ethical, of good character, living at home with her heart rid of the stain of stinginess, not abusing and insulting ascetics and brahmins.*";
P_HTM[1527]="*Evaṃ kho, gahapatayo, chavo deviyā saddhiṃ saṃvasati.**That’s how a male zombie lives with a goddess.*";
P_HTM[1528]="*Kathañca, gahapatayo, devo chavāya saddhiṃ saṃvasati?**And how does a god live with a female zombie?*";
P_HTM[1529]="*Idha, gahapatayo, sāmiko hoti pāṇātipātā paṭivirato adinnādānā paṭivirato kāmesumicchācārā paṭivirato musāvādā paṭivirato surāmerayamajjapamādaṭṭhānā paṭivirato sīlavā kalyāṇadhammo vigatamalamaccherena cetasā agāraṃ ajjhāvasati anakkosakaparibhāsako samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ;**It’s when the husband … is ethical, of good character …*";
P_HTM[1530]="*bhariyā khvassa hoti pāṇātipātinī … pe … surāmerayamajjapamādaṭṭhāyinī dussīlā pāpadhammā maccheramalapariyuṭṭhitena cetasā agāraṃ ajjhāvasati akkosikaparibhāsikā samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ.**But the wife … is unethical, of bad character …*";
P_HTM[1531]="*Evaṃ kho, gahapatayo, devo chavāya saddhiṃ saṃvasati.**That’s how a god lives with a female zombie.*";
P_HTM[1532]="*Kathañca, gahapatayo, devo deviyā saddhiṃ saṃvasati?**And how does a god live with a goddess?*";
P_HTM[1533]="*Idha, gahapatayo, sāmiko hoti pāṇātipātā paṭivirato … pe … sīlavā kalyāṇadhammo vigatamalamaccherena cetasā agāraṃ ajjhāvasati anakkosakaparibhāsako samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ;**It’s when the husband … is ethical, of good character …*";
P_HTM[1534]="*bhariyāpissa hoti pāṇātipātā paṭiviratā … pe … surāmerayamajjapamādaṭṭhānā paṭiviratā sīlavatī kalyāṇadhammā vigatamalamaccherena cetasā agāraṃ ajjhāvasati anakkosikaparibhāsikā samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ.**And the wife is also … ethical, of good character …*";
P_HTM[1535]="*Evaṃ kho, gahapatayo, devo deviyā saddhiṃ saṃvasati.**That’s how a god lives with a goddess.*";
P_HTM[1536]="*Ime kho, gahapatayo, cattāro saṃvāsāti.**These are the four ways of living together.*";
P_HTM[1537]="*Ubho ca honti dussīlā,**When both are unethical,*";
P_HTM[1538]="*kadariyā paribhāsakā;**miserly and abusive,*";
P_HTM[1539]="*Te honti jānipatayo,**then wife and husband*";
P_HTM[1540]="*chavā saṃvāsamāgatā.**live together as zombies.*";
P_HTM[1541]="*Sāmiko hoti dussīlo,**When the husband is unethical,*";
P_HTM[1542]="*kadariyo paribhāsako;**miserly and abusive,*";
P_HTM[1543]="*Bhariyā sīlavatī hoti,**but the wife is ethical,*";
P_HTM[1544]="*vadaññū vītamaccharā;**kind, rid of stinginess,*";
P_HTM[1545]="*Sāpi devī saṃvasati,**she’s a goddess living*";
P_HTM[1546]="*chavena patinā saha.**with a zombie for a husband.*";
P_HTM[1547]="*Sāmiko sīlavā hoti,**When the husband is ethical,*";
P_HTM[1548]="*vadaññū vītamaccharo;**kind, rid of stinginess,*";
P_HTM[1549]="*Bhariyā hoti dussīlā,**but the wife is unethical,*";
P_HTM[1550]="*kadariyā paribhāsikā;**miserly and abusive,*";
P_HTM[1551]="*Sāpi chavā saṃvasati,**she’s a zombie living*";
P_HTM[1552]="*devena patinā saha.**with a god for a husband.*";
P_HTM[1553]="*Ubho saddhā vadaññū ca,**When both are faithful and kind,*";
P_HTM[1554]="*saññatā dhammajīvino;**disciplined, living properly,*";
P_HTM[1555]="*Te honti jānipatayo,**then wife and husband*";
P_HTM[1556]="*aññamaññaṃ piyaṃvadā.**say nice things to each other.*";
P_HTM[1557]="*Atthāsaṃ pacurā honti,**They get all the things they need,*";
P_HTM[1558]="*phāsukaṃ upajāyati;**so they live at ease.*";
P_HTM[1559]="*Amittā dummanā honti,**Their enemies are downhearted,*";
P_HTM[1560]="*ubhinnaṃ samasīlinaṃ.**when both are equal in ethics.*";
P_HTM[1561]="*Idha dhammaṃ caritvāna,**Having practiced the teaching here,*";
P_HTM[1562]="*samasīlabbatā ubho;**both equal in precepts and observances,*";
P_HTM[1563]="*Nandino devalokasmiṃ,**they delight in the heavenly realm,*";
P_HTM[1564]="*modanti kāmakāmino”ti.**enjoying all the pleasures they desire.”*";
P_HTM[1565]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1566]="*4. Dutiyasaṃvāsasuttaṃ**Living Together (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1567]="*“Cattārome, bhikkhave, saṃvāsā.**“Mendicants, there are four ways of living together.*";
P_HTM[1568]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1569]="*Chavo chavāya saddhiṃ saṃvasati, chavo deviyā saddhiṃ saṃvasati, devo chavāya saddhiṃ saṃvasati, devo deviyā saddhiṃ saṃvasati.**~A male zombie living with a female zombie; ~a male zombie living with a goddess; ~a god living with a female zombie; ~a god living with a goddess.*";
P_HTM[1570]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, chavo chavāya saddhiṃ saṃvasati.**And how does a male zombie live with a female zombie?*";
P_HTM[1571]="*Idha, bhikkhave, sāmiko hoti pāṇātipātī adinnādāyī kāmesumicchācārī musāvādī pisuṇavāco pharusavāco samphappalāpī abhijjhālu byāpannacitto micchādiṭṭhiko dussīlo pāpadhammo maccheramalapariyuṭṭhitena cetasā agāraṃ ajjhāvasati akkosakaparibhāsako samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ;**It’s when the husband kills living creatures, steals, commits sexual misconduct; he uses speech that’s false, divisive, harsh, or nonsensical; and he’s covetous, malicious, and has wrong view. He’s unethical, of bad character, living at home with his heart full of the stain of stinginess, abusing and insulting ascetics and brahmins.*";
P_HTM[1572]="*bhariyāpissa hoti pāṇātipātinī adinnādāyinī kāmesumicchācārinī musāvādinī pisuṇavācā pharusavācā samphappalāpinī abhijjhālunī byāpannacittā micchādiṭṭhikā dussīlā pāpadhammā maccheramalapariyuṭṭhitena cetasā agāraṃ ajjhāvasati akkosikaparibhāsikā samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ.**And the wife is also … unethical, of bad character …*";
P_HTM[1573]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, chavo chavāya saddhiṃ saṃvasati.**That’s how a male zombie lives with a female zombie.*";
P_HTM[1574]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, chavo deviyā saddhiṃ saṃvasati?**And how does a male zombie live with a goddess?*";
P_HTM[1575]="*Idha, bhikkhave, sāmiko hoti pāṇātipātī … pe … micchādiṭṭhiko dussīlo pāpadhammo maccheramalapariyuṭṭhitena cetasā agāraṃ ajjhāvasati akkosakaparibhāsako samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ;**It’s when the husband … is unethical, of bad character …*";
P_HTM[1576]="*bhariyā khvassa hoti pāṇātipātā paṭiviratā adinnādānā paṭiviratā kāmesumicchācārā paṭiviratā musāvādā paṭiviratā pisuṇāya vācāya paṭiviratā pharusāya vācāya paṭiviratā samphappalāpā paṭiviratā anabhijjhālunī abyāpannacittā sammādiṭṭhikā sīlavatī kalyāṇadhammā vigatamalamaccherena cetasā agāraṃ ajjhāvasati anakkosikaparibhāsikā samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ.**But the wife doesn’t kill living creatures, steal, commit sexual misconduct, lie, or use alcoholic drinks that cause negligence. She’s ethical, of good character, living at home with her heart rid of the stain of stinginess, not abusing and insulting ascetics and brahmins.*";
P_HTM[1577]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, chavo deviyā saddhiṃ saṃvasati.**That’s how a male zombie lives with a goddess.*";
P_HTM[1578]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, devo chavāya saddhiṃ saṃvasati?**And how does a god live with a female zombie?*";
P_HTM[1579]="*Idha, bhikkhave, sāmiko hoti pāṇātipātā paṭivirato adinnādānā paṭivirato kāmesumicchācārā paṭivirato musāvādā paṭivirato pisuṇāya vācāya paṭivirato pharusāya vācāya paṭivirato samphappalāpā paṭivirato anabhijjhālu abyāpannacitto sammādiṭṭhiko sīlavā kalyāṇadhammo vigatamalamaccherena cetasā agāraṃ ajjhāvasati anakkosakaparibhāsako samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ;**It’s when the husband … is ethical, of good character …*";
P_HTM[1580]="*bhariyā khvassa hoti pāṇātipātinī … pe … micchādiṭṭhikā dussīlā pāpadhammā maccheramalapariyuṭṭhitena cetasā agāraṃ ajjhāvasati akkosikaparibhāsikā samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ.**But the wife … is unethical, of bad character …*";
P_HTM[1581]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, devo chavāya saddhiṃ saṃvasati.**That’s how a god lives with a female zombie.*";
P_HTM[1582]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, devo deviyā saddhiṃ saṃvasati?**And how does a god live with a goddess?*";
P_HTM[1583]="*Idha, bhikkhave, sāmiko hoti pāṇātipātā paṭivirato … pe … sammādiṭṭhiko sīlavā kalyāṇadhammo vigatamalamaccherena cetasā agāraṃ ajjhāvasati anakkosakaparibhāsako samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ;**It’s when the husband … is ethical, of good character …*";
P_HTM[1584]="*bhariyāpissa hoti pāṇātipātā paṭiviratā … pe … sammādiṭṭhikā sīlavatī kalyāṇadhammā vigatamalamaccherena cetasā agāraṃ ajjhāvasati anakkosikaparibhāsikā samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ.**And the wife is also … ethical, of good character …*";
P_HTM[1585]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, devo deviyā saddhiṃ saṃvasati.**That’s how a god lives with a goddess.*";
P_HTM[1586]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro saṃvāsāti.**These are the four ways of living together.” …*";
